{"title_page": "Philip Demers", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Philip Demers\n| image              = Smooshi and Phil.jpg\n| caption            = \n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|mf=yes|1978|3|21}}\n| birth_place        = [[Welland]], [[Ontario]], [[Canada]]\n| birth_name         = Philip Demers\n| networth           = \n| years_active       = 2000\u20132012\n| other_names        = \n| occupation         = Marine Mammal Trainer\n}}\n\n'''Philip Demers''' (born March 21, 1978) is a Canadian former professional [[marine mammal]] [[Animal training|trainer]] at [[Marineland of Canada]] in [[Niagara Falls, Ontario]]. He is best known for his relationship with a captive [[Pacific walrus|walrus]] named Smooshi.\n\n==Career==\nDemers' animal training career began in 2000 at MarineLand where he was employed until August 2012.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.wellandtribune.ca/2012/08/15/mayor-defends-marineland-amid-allegations |title=Mayor defends Marineland |publisher= [[Welland Tribune]] |date=15 Aug 2012 |accessdate=15 Aug 2012}}</ref> In 2007, Demers became the focus of mass media attention regarding his unique relationship with a captive Pacific walrus named Smooshi.<ref name=\"Toronto Star\">{{cite news |url=https://www.thestar.com/Life/article/180883 |title=Warm walrus love |publisher= [[Toronto Star]] |date=13 Feb 2007 |accessdate=11 Apr 2011}}</ref> Their relationship garnered the attention of such television programs as [[CBC Television|CBC]]'s ''[[The National (CBC)|The National]]'', ''[[Inside Edition]]'',<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.insideedition.com/videos/51/smooshi-the-love-struck-walrus.aspx |title=Interview: Smooshi the Love Struck Walrus|publisher=Inside Edition |date= |accessdate=14 Apr 2011}}</ref> and ''[[Jimmy Kimmel Live!]]''. Demers left his position at Marineland citing allegations of negligent treatment of the animals and unhealthy conditions.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/animal-advocates-hold-protest-outside-of-marineland-1.919743 |title=Animal advocates hold protest outside of Marineland |publisher= [[CTV News]] |date=18 Aug 2012 |accessdate=18 Aug 2012}}</ref><ref name=Diebel>{{cite news |title=Marineland animals suffering, former staffers say |author=Diebel, Linda |publisher=Toronto Star |date=15 Aug 2012 |accessdate=21 Dec 2015 |url=http://m.thestar.com/#/article/news/canada/2012/08/15/marineland_animals_suffering_former_staffers_say.html}}</ref> As of fall 2015, Marineland continued to pursue legal action against Demers and other former employees who had claimed deleterious conditions at Marineland.<ref name=Demers1>{{cite news |url=http://m.huffpost.com/ca/entry/8222246 |publisher=Huffington Post |title=Bill 52 Won't Protect Past Whistleblowers Like Me |author=Demers, Philip |date=1 Oct 2015 |accessdate=21 Dec 2015}}</ref>\n\nA news article on 10 August 2017 stated that the park had filed a total of nine lawsuits against activists, former employees and the media since 2012. None of the suits has been resolved in court. On the same date, all of the 11 charges laid by the OSPCA for animal cruelty against Marineland were dropped by the prosecutor who believed that there was no hope of convictions on eight of them. Demers expressed his disappointment: \"My jaw's on the floor. It always is. I've tempered my expectations, especially when it comes to this justice system, and especially with the OSPCA. Quite frankly, I find them completely useless.\"<ref>http://www.niagarafallsreview.ca/2017/08/10/animal-cruelty-charges-dropped-against-marineland</ref>\n\nLater in the day on 10 August, updated news reports added insights as to alternative proposed by the Crown Attorney: the public interest would be better served by a system of ongoing monitoring of the animals' condition at the park.<ref>{{cite news |work=Globe and Mail|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/all-animal-cruelty-charges-dropped-against-marineland/article35934648/|title=All animal cruelty charges dropped against Marineland |first=Liam|last=Casey|date=August 10, 2017 |accessdate=August 11, 2017}}</ref>\n\nDemers was a contestant on ''[[Wipeout Canada]]'', becoming the winner of the first episode of the Canadian edition of the show.<ref name=\"Niagara Falls Review\">{{cite web |url=http://www.niagarafallsreview.ca/ArticleDisplay.aspx?e=3058556 |title=Chippawa resident wins big at Wipeout Canada |publisher= [[Niagara Falls Review]] |date=5 April 2011 |accessdate=11 April 2011}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Blackfish (film)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* \"[http://canadalandshow.com/podcast/everyone-loves-marineland Everyone Loves Marineland]\". (Interview with Jesse Brown). ''Canadaland'', ep. 113. 21 Dec 2015.\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Demers, Philip}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1978 births]]\n[[Category:Participants in Canadian reality television series]]\n[[Category:People from Welland]]\n[[Category:Franco-Ontarian people]]\n[[Category:Men whistleblowers]]\n\n{{Canada-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Philip Demers\n| image              = Smooshi and Phil.jpg\n| caption            = \n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|mf=yes|1978|3|21}}\n| birth_place        = [[Welland]], [[Ontario]], [[Canada]]\n| birth_name         = Philip Demers\n| networth           = \n| years_active       = 2000\u20132012\n| other_names        = \n| occupation         = Marine Mammal Trainer\n}}\n\n'''Philip Demers''' (born March 21, 1978) is a Canadian former professional [[marine mammal]] [[Animal training|trainer]] at [[Marineland of Canada]] in [[Niagara Falls, Ontario]]. He is best known for his relationship with a captive [[Pacific walrus|walrus]] named Smooshi.\n\n==Career==\nDemers' animal training career began in 2000 at MarineLand where he was employed until August 2012.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.wellandtribune.ca/2012/08/15/mayor-defends-marineland-amid-allegations |title=Mayor defends Marineland |publisher= [[Welland Tribune]] |date=15 Aug 2012 |accessdate=15 Aug 2012}}</ref> In 2007, Demers became the focus of mass media attention regarding his unique relationship with a captive Pacific walrus named Smooshi.<ref name=\"Toronto Star\">{{cite news |url=https://www.thestar.com/Life/article/180883 |title=Warm walrus love |publisher= [[Toronto Star]] |date=13 Feb 2007 |accessdate=11 Apr 2011}}</ref> Their relationship garnered the attention of such television programs as [[CBC Television|CBC]]'s ''[[The National (CBC)|The National]]'', ''[[Inside Edition]]'',<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.insideedition.com/videos/51/smooshi-the-love-struck-walrus.aspx |title=Interview: Smooshi the Love Struck Walrus|publisher=Inside Edition |date= |accessdate=14 Apr 2011}}</ref> and ''[[Jimmy Kimmel Live!]]''. Demers left his position at Marineland citing allegations of negligent treatment of the animals and unhealthy conditions.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/animal-advocates-hold-protest-outside-of-marineland-1.919743 |title=Animal advocates hold protest outside of Marineland |publisher= [[CTV News]] |date=18 Aug 2012 |accessdate=18 Aug 2012}}</ref><ref name=Diebel>{{cite news |title=Marineland animals suffering, former staffers say |author=Diebel, Linda |publisher=Toronto Star |date=15 Aug 2012 |accessdate=21 Dec 2015 |url=http://m.thestar.com/#/article/news/canada/2012/08/15/marineland_animals_suffering_former_staffers_say.html}}</ref> As of fall 2015, Marineland continued to pursue legal action against Demers and other former employees who had claimed deleterious conditions at Marineland.<ref name=Demers1>{{cite news |url=http://m.huffpost.com/ca/entry/8222246 |publisher=Huffington Post |title=Bill 52 Won't Protect Past Whistleblowers Like Me |author=Demers, Philip |date=1 Oct 2015 |accessdate=21 Dec 2015}}</ref>\n\nA news article on 10 August 2017 stated that the park had filed a total of nine lawsuits against activists, former employees and the media since 2012. None of the suits has been resolved in court. On the same date, all of the 11 charges laid by the OSPCA for animal cruelty against Marineland were dropped by the prosecutor who believed that there was no hope of convictions on eight of them. Demers expressed his disappointment: \"My jaw's on the floor. It always is. I've tempered my expectations, especially when it comes to this justice system, and especially with the OSPCA. Quite frankly, I find them completely useless.\"<ref>http://www.niagarafallsreview.ca/2017/08/10/animal-cruelty-charges-dropped-against-marineland</ref>\n\nLater in the day on 10 August, updated news reports added insights as to alternative proposed by the Crown Attorney: the public interest would be better served by a system of ongoing monitoring of the animals' condition at the park.<ref>{{cite news |work=Globe and Mail|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/all-animal-cruelty-charges-dropped-against-marineland/article35934648/|title=All animal cruelty charges dropped against Marineland |first=Liam|last=Casey|date=August 10, 2017 |accessdate=August 11, 2017}}</ref>\n\nDemers was a contestant on ''[[Wipeout Canada]]'', becoming the winner of the first episode of the Canadian edition of the show.<ref name=\"Niagara Falls Review\">{{cite web |url=http://www.niagarafallsreview.ca/ArticleDisplay.aspx?e=3058556 |title=Chippawa resident wins big at Wipeout Canada |publisher= [[Niagara Falls Review]] |date=5 April 2011 |accessdate=11 April 2011}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Blackfish (film)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* \"[http://canadalandshow.com/podcast/everyone-loves-marineland Everyone Loves Marineland]\". (Interview with Jesse Brown). ''Canadaland'', ep. 113. 21 Dec 2015.\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Demers, Philip}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1978 births]]\n[[Category:Participants in Canadian reality television series]]\n[[Category:People from Welland]]\n[[Category:Franco-Ontarian people]]\n[[Category:Whistleblowers]]\n[[Category:Men whistleblowers]]\n\n{{Canada-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Geysirhead", "label": "safe", "comment": "removedCategory:WhistleblowersusingHotCatbecause already in subcategory", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Philip_Demers"}
{"title_page": "95th Ohio Infantry", "text_new": "{{Infobox Military Unit\n|unit_name= 95th Regiment, Ohio Volunteer Infantry\n|image=\n|dates= August 19, 1862, to August 19, 1865\n|country= [[United States]]\n|allegiance= [[Union (American Civil War)|Union]]\n|branch= [[Infantry]]\n|equipment= \n<!-- Culture and history -->\n|battles=[[Battle of Richmond]]<br/>[[Vicksburg Campaign]]<br/>[[Siege of Vicksburg]], May 19 & May 22 assaults<br/>[[Siege of Jackson]]<br/>[[Battle of Brice's Crossroads]]<br/>[[Battle of Nashville]]<br/>[[Battle of Fort Blakely]]\n}}\n\nThe '''95th Regiment, Ohio Volunteer Infantry''' (or '''95th OVI''') was an [[infantry]] [[regiment]] in the [[Union Army]] during the [[American Civil War]].\n\n==Service==\nThe 95th Ohio Infantry was organized at [[Camp Chase]] in [[Columbus, Ohio]] and mustered in for three years service on August 19, 1862, under the command of [[Colonel (United States)|Colonel]] [[William L. McMillen|William Linn McMillen]].\n\nThe regiment was attached to Cruft's Brigade, [[Army of Kentucky]], [[Department of the Ohio]]. 1st Brigade, 3rd Division, [[XV Corps (Union Army)|XV Corps]], [[Army of the Tennessee]], to December 1863. 1st Brigade, 1st Division, [[XVI Corps (Union Army)|XVI Corps]], to December 1864. 1st Brigade, 1st Division, Detachment Army of the Tennessee, [[Department of the Cumberland]], to February 1865. 1st Brigade, 1st Division, XVI Corps, Military Division West Mississippi, to August 1865.\n\nThe 95th Ohio Infantry mustered out of service at [[Louisville, Kentucky]], on August 19, 1865.\n\n==Detailed service==\n{{Tone|Detailed service|date=August 2019}}\nMoved to Lexington, Ky., August 20. Battle of Richmond, Ky., August 29\u201330. Regiment mostly captured. Exchanged November 20, 1862. Reorganizing at Camp Chase, Ohio, until March 1863. Left State for Memphis, Tenn., March 25. Moved from Memphis, Tenn., to Young's Point, La., and Ducksport Landing March 29-April 1. Operations against Vicksburg, Miss., April 2-July 4. Moved to join army in rear of Vicksburg, Miss., May 2\u201314. Mississippi Springs May 13. Baldwyn's Ferry May 13. Jackson May 14. Siege of Vicksburg May 18-July 4. Assaults on Vicksburg May 19 and 22. Expedition to Mechanicsburg May 26-June 4. Advance on Jackson, Miss., July 4\u201310. Siege of Jackson July 10\u201317. Camp at Big Black until November. Expedition to Canton October 14\u201320. Bogue Chitto Creek October 17. Ordered to Memphis, Tenn., November 12, and guard Memphis & Charleston Railroad near that city until February 1864. Lafayette, Tenn., December 27, 1863 (detachment). Expedition to Wyatt's, Miss., February 6\u201318. Coldwater Ferry February 8. Near Senatobia February 8\u20139. Hickahala Creek February 10. Duty at Memphis until June. Sturgis' Expedition from Memphis to Ripley April 30-May 9. Sturgis' Expedition to Guntown, Miss., June 1\u201313. Brice's or Tishamingo Creek, near Guntown, June 10. Davis Mills June 12. Smith's Expedition to Tupelo, Miss., July 5\u201321. Camargo's Cross Roads, near Harrisburg, July 13. Harrisburg, near Tupelo, July 14\u201315. Old Town or Tishamingo Creek July 15. Smith's Expedition to Oxford, Miss., August 1\u201330. Abbeville August 23. Moved to Duvall's Bluff, Ark., September 1. March through Arkansas and Missouri in pursuit of Price September 17-November 16. Moved to Nashville, Tenn., November 21-December 1. Little Harpeth December 6. Battle of Nashville December 15\u201316. Pursuit of Hood to the Tennessee River December 17\u201328. At Eastport, Miss., until February 1865. Moved to New Orleans, La., February 9\u201322, then to Mobile Point, Ala. Campaign against Mobile, Ala., and its defenses March 17-April 12. Siege of Spanish Fort and Fort Blakely March 26-April 8. Assault and capture of Fort Blakely April 9. Occupation of Mobile April 12. March to Montgomery April 13\u201326. Duty there and in the Departments of Alabama and Mississippi until August.\n\n==Casualties==\nThe regiment lost a total of 276 men during service; 1 officer and 58 enlisted men killed or mortally wounded, 2 officers and 215 enlisted men died of disease.\n\n==Commanders==\n* Colonel William L. McMillen\n* [[Lieutenant colonel (United States)|Lieutenant Colonel]] Jefferson Brumback - commanded at the battle of Nashville\n\n==Notable members==\n* 1st Lieutenant Oliver Colwell, Company G - [[Medal of Honor]] recipient for action at the battle of Nashville, December 16, 1864\n* Private Otis W. Smith, Company G - Medal of Honor recipient for action at the battle of Nashville, December 16, 1864\n* [[Major (United States)|Major]] [[William R. Warnock|William Robert Warnock]] - [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] from [[Ohio]], 1901\u20131905; commander of the Ohio [[Grand Army of the Republic]], 1913\u20131914\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|American Civil War|Ohio}}\n* [[List of Ohio Civil War units]]\n* [[Ohio in the Civil War]]\n\n==References==\n* Dyer, Frederick H. ''A Compendium of the War of the Rebellion'' (Des Moines, IA:  Dyer Pub. Co.), 1908.\n* Ohio Roster Commission. ''Official Roster of the Soldiers of the State of Ohio in the War on the Rebellion, 1861&ndash;1865, Compiled Under the Direction of the Roster Commission'' (Akron, OH: Werner Co.), 1886-1895.\n* Reid, Whitelaw. ''Ohio in the War: Her Statesmen, Her Generals, and Soldiers'' (Cincinnati, OH: Moore, Wilstach, & Baldwin), 1868. {{ISBN|9781166503925}}\n* ''Roster, Surviving Members of the 95th Regiment, O.V.I., October 17, 1916'' (Columbus, OH:  Champlain Press), 1916.\n;Attribution\n* {{CWR}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.ohiocivilwar.com/cw95.html Ohio in the Civil War: 95th Ohio Volunteer Infantry by Larry Stevens]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20101229063759/http://ohsweb.ohiohistory.org/exhibits/fftc/relicroom/details.aspx?war=2&flagid=456&unitid=182&warname=Civil%20War National flag of the 95th Ohio Infantry (probably an unofficial first issue)]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20101229063756/http://ohsweb.ohiohistory.org/exhibits/fftc/relicroom/details.aspx?war=2&flagid=455&unitid=182&warname=Civil%20War National flag of the 95th Ohio Infantry]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20101229063803/http://ohsweb.ohiohistory.org/exhibits/fftc/relicroom/details.aspx?war=2&flagid=457&unitid=182&warname=Civil%20War Regimental flag of the 95th Ohio Infantry]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20101229063829/http://ohsweb.ohiohistory.org/exhibits/fftc/relicroom/details.aspx?war=2&flagid=478&unitid=182&warname=Civil%20War Guidon of the 95th Ohio Infantry]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20101229063832/http://ohsweb.ohiohistory.org/exhibits/fftc/relicroom/details.aspx?war=2&flagid=479&unitid=182&warname=Civil%20War Another guidon of the 95th Ohio Infantry]\n* [http://www.nps.gov/vick/historyculture/95th-ohio-infantry.htm 95th Ohio Infantry monument at Vicksburg]\n\n{{Ohio in the Civil War}}\n\n[[Category:Military units and formations established in 1862]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations disestablished in 1865]]\n[[Category:Ohio Civil War regiments]]\n[[Category:1862 establishments in Ohio]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Military Unit\n|unit_name= 95th Regiment, Ohio Volunteer Infantry\n|image=\n|dates= August 19, 1862, to August 19, 1865\n|country= [[United States]]\n|allegiance= [[Union (American Civil War)|Union]]\n|branch= [[Infantry]]\n|equipment= \n<!-- Culture and history -->\n|battles=[[Battle of Richmond]]<br/>[[Vicksburg Campaign]]<br/>[[Siege of Vicksburg]], May 19 & May 22 assaults<br/>[[Siege of Jackson]]<br/>[[Battle of Brice's Crossroads]]<br/>[[Battle of Nashville]]<br/>[[Battle of Fort Blakely]]\n}}\n\nThe '''95th Ohio Volunteer Infantry''' (or '''95th OVI''') was an [[infantry]] [[regiment]] in the [[Union Army]] during the [[American Civil War]].\n\n==Service==\nThe 95th Ohio Infantry was organized at [[Camp Chase]] in [[Columbus, Ohio]] and mustered in for three years service on August 19, 1862, under the command of [[Colonel (United States)|Colonel]] [[William L. McMillen|William Linn McMillen]].\n\nThe regiment was attached to Cruft's Brigade, [[Army of Kentucky]], [[Department of the Ohio]]. 1st Brigade, 3rd Division, [[XV Corps (Union Army)|XV Corps]], [[Army of the Tennessee]], to December 1863. 1st Brigade, 1st Division, [[XVI Corps (Union Army)|XVI Corps]], to December 1864. 1st Brigade, 1st Division, Detachment Army of the Tennessee, [[Department of the Cumberland]], to February 1865. 1st Brigade, 1st Division, XVI Corps, Military Division West Mississippi, to August 1865.\n\nThe 95th Ohio Infantry mustered out of service at [[Louisville, Kentucky]], on August 19, 1865.\n\n==Detailed service==\n{{Tone|Detailed service|date=August 2019}}\nMoved to Lexington, Ky., August 20. Battle of Richmond, Ky., August 29\u201330. Regiment mostly captured. Exchanged November 20, 1862. Reorganizing at Camp Chase, Ohio, until March 1863. Left State for Memphis, Tenn., March 25. Moved from Memphis, Tenn., to Young's Point, La., and Ducksport Landing March 29-April 1. Operations against Vicksburg, Miss., April 2-July 4. Moved to join army in rear of Vicksburg, Miss., May 2\u201314. Mississippi Springs May 13. Baldwyn's Ferry May 13. Jackson May 14. Siege of Vicksburg May 18-July 4. Assaults on Vicksburg May 19 and 22. Expedition to Mechanicsburg May 26-June 4. Advance on Jackson, Miss., July 4\u201310. Siege of Jackson July 10\u201317. Camp at Big Black until November. Expedition to Canton October 14\u201320. Bogue Chitto Creek October 17. Ordered to Memphis, Tenn., November 12, and guard Memphis & Charleston Railroad near that city until February 1864. Lafayette, Tenn., December 27, 1863 (detachment). Expedition to Wyatt's, Miss., February 6\u201318. Coldwater Ferry February 8. Near Senatobia February 8\u20139. Hickahala Creek February 10. Duty at Memphis until June. Sturgis' Expedition from Memphis to Ripley April 30-May 9. Sturgis' Expedition to Guntown, Miss., June 1\u201313. Brice's or Tishamingo Creek, near Guntown, June 10. Davis Mills June 12. Smith's Expedition to Tupelo, Miss., July 5\u201321. Camargo's Cross Roads, near Harrisburg, July 13. Harrisburg, near Tupelo, July 14\u201315. Old Town or Tishamingo Creek July 15. Smith's Expedition to Oxford, Miss., August 1\u201330. Abbeville August 23. Moved to Duvall's Bluff, Ark., September 1. March through Arkansas and Missouri in pursuit of Price September 17-November 16. Moved to Nashville, Tenn., November 21-December 1. Little Harpeth December 6. Battle of Nashville December 15\u201316. Pursuit of Hood to the Tennessee River December 17\u201328. At Eastport, Miss., until February 1865. Moved to New Orleans, La., February 9\u201322, then to Mobile Point, Ala. Campaign against Mobile, Ala., and its defenses March 17-April 12. Siege of Spanish Fort and Fort Blakely March 26-April 8. Assault and capture of Fort Blakely April 9. Occupation of Mobile April 12. March to Montgomery April 13\u201326. Duty there and in the Departments of Alabama and Mississippi until August.\n\n==Casualties==\nThe regiment lost a total of 276 men during service; 1 officer and 58 enlisted men killed or mortally wounded, 2 officers and 215 enlisted men died of disease.\n\n==Commanders==\n* Colonel William L. McMillen\n* [[Lieutenant colonel (United States)|Lieutenant Colonel]] Jefferson Brumback - commanded at the battle of Nashville\n\n==Notable members==\n* 1st Lieutenant Oliver Colwell, Company G - [[Medal of Honor]] recipient for action at the battle of Nashville, December 16, 1864\n* Private Otis W. Smith, Company G - Medal of Honor recipient for action at the battle of Nashville, December 16, 1864\n* [[Major (United States)|Major]] [[William R. Warnock|William Robert Warnock]] - [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] from [[Ohio]], 1901\u20131905; commander of the Ohio [[Grand Army of the Republic]], 1913\u20131914\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|American Civil War|Ohio}}\n* [[List of Ohio Civil War units]]\n* [[Ohio in the Civil War]]\n\n==References==\n* Dyer, Frederick H. ''A Compendium of the War of the Rebellion'' (Des Moines, IA:  Dyer Pub. Co.), 1908.\n* Ohio Roster Commission. ''Official Roster of the Soldiers of the State of Ohio in the War on the Rebellion, 1861&ndash;1865, Compiled Under the Direction of the Roster Commission'' (Akron, OH: Werner Co.), 1886-1895.\n* Reid, Whitelaw. ''Ohio in the War: Her Statesmen, Her Generals, and Soldiers'' (Cincinnati, OH: Moore, Wilstach, & Baldwin), 1868. {{ISBN|9781166503925}}\n* ''Roster, Surviving Members of the 95th Regiment, O.V.I., October 17, 1916'' (Columbus, OH:  Champlain Press), 1916.\n;Attribution\n* {{CWR}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.ohiocivilwar.com/cw95.html Ohio in the Civil War: 95th Ohio Volunteer Infantry by Larry Stevens]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20101229063759/http://ohsweb.ohiohistory.org/exhibits/fftc/relicroom/details.aspx?war=2&flagid=456&unitid=182&warname=Civil%20War National flag of the 95th Ohio Infantry (probably an unofficial first issue)]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20101229063756/http://ohsweb.ohiohistory.org/exhibits/fftc/relicroom/details.aspx?war=2&flagid=455&unitid=182&warname=Civil%20War National flag of the 95th Ohio Infantry]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20101229063803/http://ohsweb.ohiohistory.org/exhibits/fftc/relicroom/details.aspx?war=2&flagid=457&unitid=182&warname=Civil%20War Regimental flag of the 95th Ohio Infantry]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20101229063829/http://ohsweb.ohiohistory.org/exhibits/fftc/relicroom/details.aspx?war=2&flagid=478&unitid=182&warname=Civil%20War Guidon of the 95th Ohio Infantry]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20101229063832/http://ohsweb.ohiohistory.org/exhibits/fftc/relicroom/details.aspx?war=2&flagid=479&unitid=182&warname=Civil%20War Another guidon of the 95th Ohio Infantry]\n* [http://www.nps.gov/vick/historyculture/95th-ohio-infantry.htm 95th Ohio Infantry monument at Vicksburg]\n\n{{Ohio in the Civil War}}\n\n[[Category:Military units and formations established in 1862]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations disestablished in 1865]]\n[[Category:Ohio Civil War regiments]]\n[[Category:1862 establishments in Ohio]]\n", "name_user": "Hhfjbaker", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/95th_Ohio_Infantry"}
{"title_page": "Tetris", "text_new": "{{About|the 1984 video game}}\n{{short description|tile-matching puzzle video game}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2019}}\n{{Infobox video game\n| title = Tetris\n| image = \n| caption = \n| developer = AcademySoft\n| publisher = AcademySoft\n| designer = [[Alexey Pajitnov]]\n| platforms = [[List of Tetris variants|List of ''Tetris'' variants]]\n| released = '''Electronika 60'''{{Video game release|[[Soviet Union|USSR]]|1984}}'''MS-DOS''' & '''IBM PC'''{{Video game release|USSR|1986}}\n| genre = [[Puzzle video game|Puzzle]], [[Tile-matching video game|Tile-matching]]\n| modes = [[Single-player]], [[multiplayer]]\n}}\n\n'''''Tetris''''' ({{lang-ru|link=no|\u0422\u0435\u0442\u0440\u0438\u0441}} {{IPA-ru|\u02c8t\u025btr\u02b2\u026as|}} is a [[Tile-matching video game|tile-matching]] [[puzzle video game]] originally designed and programmed by  [[God]] in 200 bc for the [[Adam and Eve]]. The game has been published by several companies over time, most prominently during a war for the appropriation of the game's rights in the late 1980s. After a significant period of publication by [[Nintendo]], the rights of the game reverted to Pajitnov in 1996, who co-founded [[The Tetris Company]] with [[Henk Rogers]] to manage licensing for ''Tetris''.\n\n''Tetris'' challenges the player to create complete lines by moving differently-shaped pieces \u2013 the [[tetromino]]es, which scroll from the top to bottom of the playing field. The completed lines disappear and grant the player points, and the player can proceed to fill the vacated spaces. The game ends when the playing field is filled to the point that additional pieces can no longer descend. The longer the player can delay this inevitable outcome, the higher their score will be. In multiplayer games, the players must last longer than their opponents, and in certain versions, players can inflict penalties on opponents by completing a significant number of lines. Some adaptations have provided variations to the game's theme, such as three-dimensional displays or a system for reserving pieces.\n\nBuilt on simple rules and requiring intelligence and skill, ''Tetris'' has established itself as [[List of video games considered the best|one of the great classic video game titles]] alongside ''[[Pong]]'', ''[[Space Invaders]]'' and ''[[Pac-Man]]''. Since its creation, ''Tetris'' has sold 202{{nbsp}}million copies \u2013 approximately 70{{nbsp}}million physical units and 132{{nbsp}}million paid [[mobile game]] downloads \u2013 as of December 2011, making it one of the [[List of best-selling video game franchises|best-selling video game franchises of all time]]; the [[Game Boy]] version in particular is [[List of best-selling video games|one of the best-selling single titles of all time]], with over 35 million copies sold. The game is available on [[List of Tetris variants|over 65 platforms]], setting a [[Guinness World Records|''Guinness'' world record]] for the most ported video game title. ''Tetris'' is rooted within popular culture and its notoriety extends beyond the sphere of video games; imagery from the game has influenced architecture, music and cosplay. The game has also been the subject of various research studies that have analyzed its theoretical complexity and have shown its effect on the human brain following a session, in particular the [[Tetris effect]].\n\n==Gameplay==\n[[File:Tetris basic game.gif|thumb|Video of an open-source ''Tetris'' [[Clone (video game)|clone]]]]\n''Tetris'' is primarily composed of a field of play in which pieces of different geometric forms, called \"[[Tetromino|tetriminos]]\", descend from the top of the field.{{sfn|Kent|2001|p=377}} During this descent, the player can move the pieces laterally and rotate them until they touch the bottom of the field or land on a piece that had been placed before it.<ref name=\"AboutTetris\">{{cite web |url=https://tetris.com/about-us |title=About ''Tetris'' |publisher=The Tetris Company |accessdate=November 14, 2019}}</ref> The player can neither slow down the falling pieces nor stop them, but can accelerate them in most versions.<ref>''Tetris'' (Game Boy) instruction booklet, p. 4</ref><ref>''Tetris DS'' instruction booklet, p. 6</ref> The objective of the game is to use the pieces to create as many horizontal lines of blocks as possible. When a line is completed, it disappears, and the blocks placed above fall one rank.<ref name=\"AboutTetris\"/> Completing lines grants points, and accumulating a certain number of points moves the player up a level, which increases the number of points granted per completed line.<ref name=\"GameBoy16\">''Tetris'' (Game Boy) instruction booklet, p. 16</ref> In most versions, the speed of the falling pieces increases with each level, leaving the player with less time to think about the placement.<ref name=\"AboutTetris\"/> The player can clear multiple lines at once, which can earn bonus points in some versions.{{sfn|Kent|2001|p=377}} It is possible to complete up to four lines simultaneously with the use of the I-shaped tetrimino; this move is called a \"Tetris\", and is the basis of the game's title.<ref name=\"GameBoy16\"/> If the player cannot make the blocks disappear quickly enough, the field will start to fill, and when the pieces reach the top of the field and prevent the arrival of additional pieces, the game ends.<ref name=\"AboutTetris\"/> At the end of each game, the player receives a score based on the number of lines that have been completed.<ref name=\"GameBoy16\"/> The game never ends with the player's victory; the player can only complete as many lines as possible before an inevitable loss.{{sfn|Kent|2001|p=377}} \n\nSince 1996, The Tetris Company has internally defined specifications and guidelines that publishers must adhere to in order to be granted a license to ''Tetris''. The contents of these guidelines establish such elements as the correspondence of buttons and actions, the size of the field of play, the system of rotation, and others.<ref name=\"HistoryOfTetris\">{{cite web |url=https://tetris.com/history-of-tetris |title=History of ''Tetris'' |publisher=The Tetris Company |accessdate=November 18, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"tftt\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nintendoworldreport.com/interview/11267/tetris-from-the-top-an-interview-with-henk-rogers |title=''Tetris'' from the Top: An Interview with Henk Rogers |author=Metts, Jonathan |website=Nintendo World Report |date=April 6, 2006 |accessdate=April 28, 2007}}</ref>\n\n===Game pieces===\n[[File:Tetrominoes IJLO STZ Worlds.svg|thumb|left|All seven tetriminos using the standard color scheme]]\nThe pieces on which the game of ''Tetris'' is based around are called \"tetriminos\". Pajitnov's original version for the [[Electronika 60]] computer used green brackets to represent the blocks that make up tetriminos.<ref name=\"vadim\"/> Versions of ''Tetris'' on the original Game Boy/Game Boy Color and on most dedicated handheld games use [[monochrome]] or grayscale graphics, but most popular versions use a separate color for each distinct shape. Prior to The Tetris Company's standardization in the early 2000s, those colors varied widely from implementation to implementation.\n\n===Scoring===\nThe scoring formula for the majority of ''Tetris'' products is built on the idea that more difficult line clears should be awarded more points. For example, a single line clear in ''Tetris Zone'' is worth 100 points, clearing four lines at once (known as a ''Tetris'') is worth 800, while each subsequent back-to-back ''Tetris'' is worth 1,200.<ref name=\"tzmanual\">[http://zone.tetris.com/page/manual ''Tetris Zone'' manual] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090206023148/http://zone.tetris.com/page/manual |date=February 6, 2009 }} as of November 12, 2008</ref> In conjunction, players can be awarded combos that exist in certain games which reward multiple line clears in quick succession. The exact conditions for triggering combos, and the amount of importance assigned to them, vary from game to game.{{citation needed|date=August 2018}}\n\nNearly all ''Tetris'' games allow the player to press a button to increase the speed of the current piece's descent or cause the piece to drop and lock into place immediately, known as a \"soft drop\" and a \"hard drop\", respectively. While performing a soft drop, the player can also stop the piece's increased speed by releasing the button before the piece settles into place. Some games only allow either soft drop or hard drop; others have separate buttons for both. Many games award a number of points based on the height that the piece fell before locking, so using the hard drop generally awards more points.\n\n===Debate on the possibility of an infinite game===\nThe question ''Would it be possible to play forever?'' was first considered in a thesis by John Brzustowski in 1992.<ref>John Brzustowski. [https://circle.ubc.ca/bitstream/handle/2429/3263/ubc_1992_spring_brzustowski_john.pdf?sequence=1] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131016151137/https://circle.ubc.ca/bitstream/handle/2429/3263/ubc_1992_spring_brzustowski_john.pdf?sequence=1 |date=October 16, 2013 }}. Retrieved October 16, 2013.</ref> The conclusion reached was that the game is statistically doomed to end. The reason has to do with the S and Z Tetriminos. If a player receives a sufficiently large sequence of alternating S and Z Tetriminos, the na\u00efve gravity used by the standard game eventually forces the player to leave holes on the board. The holes will necessarily stack to the top and, ultimately, end the game. If the pieces are distributed randomly, this sequence will eventually occur. Thus, if a game with, for example, an ideal, uniform, uncorrelated [[Random number generation|random number generator]] is played long enough, any player will top out.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20061209110731/http://www.math.uic.edu/~burgiel/Tetris/explanation.html Dr. Burgiel's Tetris Research Page, Explanation]. Retrieved February 25, 2007.</ref><ref>Heidi Burgiel. [http://www.geom.umn.edu/%7Eburgiel/Tetris/tetris.PS How to Lose at Tetris] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030513033006/http://www.geom.umn.edu/~burgiel/Tetris/tetris.PS |date=May 13, 2003 }}, Mathematical Gazette, vol. 81, pp. 194\u2013200 1997</ref>\n\nIn practice, this does not occur in most ''Tetris'' variants. Some [[List of Tetris variants|variants]] allow the player to choose to play with only S and Z Tetriminos, and a good player may survive well over 150 consecutive Tetriminos this way. On an implementation with an ideal uniform randomizer, the probability at any given time of the next 150 Tetriminos being only S and Z is ({{sfrac|2|7}})<sup>150</sup> (approximately {{val|2e-82}}). Most implementations use a [[pseudorandom number generator]] to generate the sequence of Tetriminos, and such an S\u2013Z sequence is almost certainly not contained in the sequence produced by the 32-bit [[linear congruential generator]] in many implementations (which has roughly {{val|4.2e9}} states). The \"evil\" algorithm in ''Bastet'' (an unofficial variant) often starts a game with a series of more than seven Z pieces.\n\nModern versions of ''Tetris'' released after 2001 use a bag-style randomizer that guarantees players will never receive more than four S or Z pieces in a row. This is one of the \"Indispensable Rules\" enforced by the ''Tetris Guideline'' that all officially licensed ''Tetris'' games must follow.<ref name=\"tftt\"/>\n\nRecent versions of ''Tetris'' such as ''Tetris Worlds'' allow the player to repeatedly rotate a block once it hits the bottom of the playfield without it locking into place. This permits a player to play for an infinite amount of time, though not necessarily to land an infinite number of blocks.\n\n=== Easy spin dispute ===\nAlthough not the first ''Tetris'' game to feature a new kind of ''Tetris'', \"easy spin\" (see ''[[The Next Tetris]]''), also called \"infinite spin\" by critics,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gamespot.com/gba/puzzle/tetrisworlds/review.html |title=Tetris Worlds for Game Boy Advance Review |publisher=Gamespot.com |date=September 5, 2001 |accessdate=November 22, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111028130427/http://www.gamespot.com/gba/puzzle/tetrisworlds/review.html |archive-date=October 28, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> ''[[Tetris Worlds]]'' was the first game to fall under major criticisms for it. Easy spin refers to the property of a Tetromino to stop falling for a moment after left or right movement or rotation, effectively allowing someone to suspend the Tetromino while thinking on where to place it. This feature has been implemented into [[The Tetris Company]]'s official guideline.<ref name=\"tftt\"/> This type of play differs from traditional ''Tetris'' because it takes away the pressure of higher level speed. Some reviewers<ref name=\"gsrev\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/ps2/puzzle/tetrisworlds/review.html|title=Tetris Worlds for PlayStation 2 Review|accessdate=November 12, 2008|website=[[GameSpot]]|date=April 19, 2002|author1=Jeff Gerstmann|author2=Ryan Davis|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090130070533/http://www.gamespot.com/ps2/puzzle/tetrisworlds/review.html|archive-date=January 30, 2009|url-status=live}}</ref> went so far as to say that this mechanism broke the game. The goal in ''Tetris Worlds'', however, is to complete a certain number of lines as fast as possible, so the ability to hold off a piece's placement will not make achieving that goal any faster. Later, GameSpot received \"easy spin\" more openly, saying that \"the infinite spin issue honestly really affects only a few of the single-player gameplay modes in ''Tetris DS'', because any competitive mode requires you to lay down pieces as quickly as humanly possible.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/ds/puzzle/tetris/review.html |title=Tetris DS for DS Review \u2013 GameSpot |publisher=Gamespot.com |date=March 20, 2006 |accessdate=November 22, 2012 |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110805040528/http://www.gamespot.com/ds/puzzle/tetris/review.html |archivedate=August 5, 2011 |df= }}</ref> In response to the issue, [[Henk Rogers]] stated in an interview that infinite spin was an intentional part of the game design, allowing novice players to expend some of their available scoring time to decide on the best placement of a piece. Rogers observed that \"gratuitous spinning\" does not occur in competitive play, as expert players do not require much time to think about where a piece should be placed. A limitation has been placed on infinite lock delay in later games of the franchise, where after a certain amount of inputs i.e.: rotations and movements, the piece will instantly lock itself. This is defaulted to 15 inputs.<ref name=\"tftt\"/>\n\n==History==\n{{multiple image\n | align = right\n | direction = vertical\n | width    = 250\n | image1   = Tetris-VeryFirstVersion.png\n | caption1 = The first version of ''Tetris'', completed in 1984, run on an emulator of the [[Electronika 60]]\n | image2   = Tetris DOS 1986.png\n | caption2 = Screenshot of the 1986 IBM PC version developed by Dmitry Pavlovsky and [[Vadim Gerasimov]]\n | image3   = Tetris screenshot (Amiga, Infogrames).png\n | caption3 = The version designed by Spectrum Holobyte contained Russia-related images (Amiga version screenshot, 1988)\n}}\n\n===Conception===\nIn 1979, [[Alexey Pajitnov]] joined the Computer Center of the [[Russian Academy of Sciences|Soviet Academy of Sciences]] as a [[speech recognition]] researcher. While he was tasked with testing the capabilities of new hardware, his ambition was to use computers to make people happy.{{sfn|Ichbiah|1997|p=85}} Pajitnov developed several puzzle games on the institute's computer, an [[Electronika 60]], a scarce resource at the time.{{sfn|Sheff|1999|p=298}} For Pajitnov, \"The games allow people to get to know each other better and act as revealers of things you might not normally notice, such as their way of thinking.\"{{sfn|Ichbiah|1997|p=85}} In 1984, while trying to recreate a favorite puzzle game from his childhood featuring [[pentomino]]es,<ref name=\"guardian2014\">{{cite news |last=Hoad |first=Phil |url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2014/jun/02/how-we-made-tetris |title=Tetris: how we made the addictive computer game &#124; Culture |newspaper=The Guardian |date=June 2, 2014 |accessdate=July 5, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170621140034/https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2014/jun/02/how-we-made-tetris |archive-date=June 21, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>{{sfn|Loguidice|Barton|2009|p=293}} Pajitnov imagined a game consisting of a descent of random pieces that the player would have to turn in order to fill in rows.{{sfn|Ichbiah|1997|p=85}} Pajitnov felt that the game would be needlessly complicated with twelve different shape variations, so he scaled the concept down to [[tetromino]]es, of which there are seven variants.<ref name=\"guardian2014\"/> Pajitnov titled the game ''Tetris'', a word created from a combination of \"tetromino\" and \"tennis\", the latter being Pajitnov's favorite sport.{{sfn|Loguidice|Barton|2009|p=293}} Because the Electronika 60 that Pajitnov used to create the prototype for ''Tetris'' had no graphical interface, Pajitnov modelled the field and pieces using spaces and brackets.{{sfn|Sheff|1999|p=299}} Realizing that completed lines resulted in the screen filling up quickly, Pajitnov decided to delete them, creating a key part of ''Tetris'' gameplay.<ref name=\"guardian2014\"/> This early version of ''Tetris'' had no scoring system and no levels, but its addictive quality caused it to stand out amongst the puzzle games that Pajitnov had created.<ref name=guardian020609>{{cite web |last=Johnson |first=Bobbie |website=[[The Guardian]] |date=June 1, 2009 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/gamesblog/2009/jun/02/tetris-25anniversary-alexey-pajitnov |title=How ''Tetris'' conquered the world, block by block |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150329135242/http://www.theguardian.com/technology/gamesblog/2009/jun/02/tetris-25anniversary-alexey-pajitnov |archive-date=March 29, 2015}}</ref>\n\nPajitnov, delighted by his game, presented ''Tetris'' to his colleagues, who quickly became addicted to it.{{sfn|Ichbiah|1997|p=87}} The game permeated all the offices within the Academy of Sciences, and within a few weeks it reached every Moscow institute with a computer.{{sfn|Ichbiah|1997|p=87}}{{sfn|Temple|2004|loc=9 min.}} A friend of Pajitnov, Vladimir Pokhilko, who requested the game for the Moscow Medical Institute, saw people stop working to play ''Tetris'', and told Pajitnov that \"I can no longer live without your ''Tetris''\". Pokhilko eventually banned the game from the Medical Institute to restore productivity.{{sfn|Ichbiah|1997|p=87}} Faced with his success, Pajitnov sought to adapt ''Tetris'' to the [[IBM Personal Computer]], which had a higher quality display than the Electronika 60. Pajitnov recruited [[Vadim Gerasimov]], a 16-year-old high school student who was known for his computer skills and reputed to be a [[hacker]].{{sfn|Ichbiah|1997|p=87}}{{sfn|Sheff|1999|p=300}} Pajitnov had met Gerasimov before through a mutual acquaintance, and they worked together on previous games.<ref name=\"vadim\">{{cite web |url=https://vadim.oversigma.com/Tetris.htm |title= Original ''Tetris'': Story and Download |last=Gerasimov |first=Vadim |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060821183909/http://vadim.oversigma.com/Tetris.htm |archive-date=August 21, 2006 |accessdate=June 10, 2007}}</ref> Gerasimov adapted ''Tetris'' to the IBM PC over the course of a few weeks, incorporating color and a scoreboard.{{sfn|Sheff|1999|p=300}}\n\nPajitnov then wanted to export ''Tetris''. However, he had no knowledge of the business world, and his superiors in the Academy were not necessarily happy with the success of the game, since they had not intended such a creation from the research team.{{sfn|Ichbiah|1997|p=87}} Furthermore, [[intellectual property]] did not exist in the Soviet Union, and Soviet researchers were not allowed to sell their creations.{{sfn|Sheff|1999|p=301}}{{sfn|Temple|2004|loc=10 min.}} Pajitnov asked his supervisor Victor Brjabrin, who had knowledge of the world outside the Soviet Union, to help him publish ''Tetris''. Pajitnov offered to transfer the rights of the game to the Academy, and was delighted to receive a non-compulsory remuneration from Brjabrin through this deal.{{sfn|Ichbiah|1997|p=88}}\n\n===Acquisition of rights by Mirrorsoft and Spectrum HoloByte===\nIn 1986, Brjabrin sent a copy of ''Tetris'' to [[Hungary|Hungarian]] game publisher [[Appaloosa Interactive|Novotrade]].{{sfn|Ichbiah|1997|p=88}} From there, clones of the game began circulating via [[floppy disk]]s throughout Hungary and as far as [[Poland]].{{sfn|Ichbiah|1997|p=89}} Robert Stein, an international software salesman for the London-based firm Andromeda Software, saw the game's commercial potential during a visit to Hungary in June 1986.{{sfn|Sheff|1999|p=302}}{{sfn|Temple|2004|loc=11 min.}} After an indifferent response from the Academy,{{sfn|Temple|2004|loc=12 min.}} Stein contacted Pajitnov and Brjabrin by fax in order to obtain the rights to the license.{{sfn|Temple|2004|loc=11 min.}} The researchers expressed interest in forming an agreement with Stein.{{sfn|Temple|2004|loc=12 min.}} However, they were unaware that a fax machine had legal value in the Western world, and Stein began to approach other companies to produce the game.{{sfn|Ichbiah|1997|pp=89\u201390}} Pajitnov was never able to digest this misunderstanding; in an interview with the website Kikizo, he declared \"I don\u2019t really like to talk about that because when I think about those things I lose my sense of humor.\"{{sfn|Kent|2001|p=294}}\n\nStein thus took advantage of the 1987 [[Consumer Electronics Show]] in [[Las Vegas]] to approach several publishers. Gary Carlston, co-founder of [[Broderbund]], retrieved a copy and brought it to [[California]]. Despite enthusiasm amongst its employees, Broderbund remained skeptical because of the game's Soviet origins. Likewise, [[Mastertronic]] co-founder Martin Alper declared that \"No Soviet product will ever work in the Western world.\"{{sfn|Ichbiah|1997|p=90}} Stein ultimately signed two agreements: he sold the European rights to the publisher [[Mirrorsoft]],{{sfn|Kent|2001|p=479}}{{sfn|Ichbiah|1997|p=90}} and the American rights to [[Spectrum HoloByte]].{{sfn|Kent|2001|p=479}}{{sfn|Kent|2001|p=294}} The latter obtained the rights after a visit by Mirrorsoft president Phil Adams in which he played ''Tetris'' for two hours.{{sfn|Ichbiah|1997|p=90}}{{sfn|Temple|2004|loc=15 min.}} At that time, Stein had not yet signed a contract with the Soviet Union.{{sfn|Kent|2001|p=479}} Nevertheless, he sold the rights to the two companies for \u00a33,000 and a royalty of 7.5 to 15% on sales.{{sfn|Sheff|1999|p=304}}\n\nBefore releasing ''Tetris'' in the United States, Spectrum HoloByte CEO Gilman Louie asked for an overhaul of the game's graphics and music.{{sfn|Ichbiah|1997|p=90}} The Soviet spirit was preserved, with fields illustrating Russian parks and buildings as well as melodies anchored in Russian folklore of the time. The company's goal was to make people want to buy a Russian product; the game came complete with a red package and Cyrillic text, an unusual approach on the other side of the [[Berlin Wall]].{{sfn|Temple|2004|loc=16 min.}} The Mirrorsoft version was released for the IBM PC in November 1987,{{sfn|Ichbiah|1997|p=91}} while the Spectrum HoloByte version was released for the same platform in January 1988.{{sfn|Kent|2001|p=294}}{{sfn|Ichbiah|1997|p=91}} The game was subsequently ported to other platforms, most notably the [[Amiga]], [[Atari ST]], [[ZX Spectrum]], [[Commodore 64]] and [[Amstrad CPC]]. At the time, the game made no mention of Pajitnov and came with the announcement of \"Made in the United States of America, designed abroad\". ''Tetris'' was a commercial success in Europe and the United States: Mirrorsoft sold tens of thousands of copies in two months.{{sfn|Ichbiah|1997|p=91}} The game sold 100,000 units in the space of a year.{{sfn|Temple|2004|loc=18 min.}} According to Spectrum HoloByte, the average profile of a ''Tetris'' player was an adult between 25\u201345 years of age who was a manager or an engineer. At the [[Software and Information Industry Association|Software Publishers Association]] \"Excellence in Software Awards\" ceremony in March 1988, ''Tetris'' obtained four awards: Best Entertainment Software, Best Original Game, Best Strategy Program, and Best Consumer Software.{{sfn|Ichbiah|1997|p=91}}\n\nStein, however, was faced with a problem: the only document certifying a license fee was the fax from Pajitnov and Brjabrin, meaning that Stein sold the license for a game he did not yet own. Stein contacted Pajitnov and asked him for a contract for the rights. Stein began negotiations via fax, offering 75% of the revenue generated by Stein from the license.{{sfn|Sheff|1999|p=304}} [[Elektronorgtechnica]] (\"Elorg\"), the Soviet Union's central organization for the import and export of computer software, was unconvinced by this offer and requested 80% of the revenue. Stein made several trips to Moscow and held long discussions with Elorg representatives.{{sfn|Sheff|1999|p=305}} On February 24, 1988,{{sfn|Sheff|1999|p=308}} Stein obtained an agreement with Elorg, which he signed on May 10, 1988,{{sfn|Temple|2004|loc=22 min.}} for a ten-year worldwide ''Tetris'' license for all current and future computer systems.{{sfn|Ichbiah|1997|p=92}} Pajitnov and Brjabrin were unaware that the game was already on sale and that Stein had claimed to own the rights prior to the agreement.{{sfn|Kent|2001|p=479}} Although Pajitnov would not receive any percentage from these sales,{{sfn|Ichbiah|1997|p=92}} he decided that \"The fact that so many people enjoy my game is enough for me.\"{{sfn|Ichbiah|1997|p=96}}\n\n===Acquisition of rights by Nintendo and legal battle===\nThe situation grew more complex in 1988. Spectrum HoloByte sold the Japanese rights to its computer games and arcade machines to [[Henk Rogers]], who was searching for games for the Japanese market.{{sfn|Temple|2004|loc=22 min.}} Mirrorsoft sold its own Japanese rights to [[Atari Games]] subsidiary [[Tengen (company)|Tengen]]; the latter would then sell the arcade rights to [[Sega]] and the console rights to Rogers. At this point, almost a dozen companies believed they held the rights to the game, with Stein retaining rights for home computer versions.{{sfn|Loguidice|Barton|2009|p=480}} Elorg was still unaware of the deals Stein had negotiated, which did not bring money to them. Nevertheless, ''Tetris'' was a commercial success in North America, Eurpoe and Asia.{{sfn|Temple|2004|loc=22 min.}}\n\nThe same year, [[Nintendo]] was preparing to launch its first portable console, the [[Game Boy]]. Nintendo was attracted to ''Tetris'' by its simplicity and established success on the [[Nintendo Entertainment System|NES]].{{sfn|Ichbiah|1997|p=92}}{{sfn|Loguidice|Barton|2009|p=480}} Rogers, who was close to Nintendo president [[Hiroshi Yamauchi]], then sought to recover the handheld rights.{{sfn|Ichbiah|1997|p=92}} After a failed negotiation with Atari Games,{{sfn|Ichbiah|1997|p=93}} Rogers contacted Stein in November 1988. Stein agreed to sign a contract, but explained that he had to consult Elorg before returning to negotiations with Rogers.{{sfn|Temple|2004|loc=24 min.}}{{sfn|Sheff|1999|p=313}} After contacting Stein several times, Rogers began to suspect a breach of contract on Stein's part, and decided on February 1989 to go to the Soviet Union and negotiate the rights with Elorg.{{sfn|Ichbiah|1997|p=93}}{{sfn|Sheff|1999|p=313}}\n\nRogers arrived at the Elorg offices uninvited, while Stein and Mirrorsoft manager [[Kevin Maxwell]] made an appointment the same day without consulting each other.{{sfn|Temple|2004|loc=29 min.}} During the discussions, Rogers explained that he wished to obtain the rights to ''Tetris'' for the new Game Boy console, following the success of the game on the NES.{{sfn|Ichbiah|1997|p=95}} After quickly obtaining an agreement with Elorg president Nikolai Belikov,{{sfn|Sheff|1999|p=316}} Rogers showed Belikov a cartridge of the game.{{sfn|Ichbiah|1997|p=94}} Belikov was surprised, as he believed at the time that the rights to ''Tetris'' were only signed for computers systems.{{sfn|Temple|2004|loc=31 min.}} The present parties accused Nintendo of illegal publication, but Rogers defended himself by explaining that he had obtained the rights via Atari Games, which had itself signed an agreement with Stein.{{sfn|Ichbiah|1997|p=94}} Belikov then realized the complex path that the license had followed within four years because of Stein's contracts, and he constructed a strategy to regain possession of the rights and obtain more favorable commercial aggreements. At that point, Elorg was faced with three different companies who wished to buy the rights.{{sfn|Temple|2004|loc=35 min.}}\n\nDuring this time, Rogers befriended Pajitnov over a [[Go (game)|game of Go]], and Pajitnov would support Rogers throughout the discussions, to the detriment of Maxwell, who came to secure the ''Tetris'' rights for Mirrorsoft.{{sfn|Ichbiah|1997|p=93}} Belikov proposed to Rogers that Stein's rights would be cancelled and Nintendo would be granted the game rights for both home and handheld consoles.{{sfn|Ichbiah|1997|p=94}} Rogers then flew to the United States to convince Nintendo's American branch to sign up for the rights. The contract with Elorg was signed by [[Minoru Arakawa]] and [[Howard Lincoln]] for $500,000, plus 50 cents per cartridge sold.{{sfn|Ichbiah|1997|p=95}}{{sfn|Temple|2004|loc=42 min.}} Elorg then sent an updated contract to Stein. One of the contract's clauses defined a computer as a machine with a screen and keyboard, and thus Stein's rights to console versions were withdrawn.{{sfn|Temple|2004|loc=37 min.}} Stein signed the contract without paying attention to this clause,{{sfn|Ichbiah|1997|p=95}} and he later realized that all the contract's other clauses, notably on payments, were only a \"smokescreen\" to deceive him.{{sfn|Temple|2004|loc=37 min.}}{{sfn|Sheff|1999|p=319}}\n\nIn March 1989, Nintendo sent a [[cease and desist]] fax to Atari Games concerning production of the NES version of ''Tetris''.{{sfn|Temple|2004|loc=47 min.}} Atari Games contacted Mirrorsoft, and were assured that they still retained the rights. Nintendo, however, maintained its position. In response, Mirrorsoft owner [[Robert Maxwell]] pressured Soviet Union leader [[Mikhail Gorbachev]] to cancel the contract between Elorg and Nintendo.{{sfn|Ichbiah|1997|p=95}} Despite the threats to Belikov, Elorg refused to give in and highlighted the financial advantages of their contract compared to those signed with Stein and Mirrorsoft.{{sfn|Ichbiah|1997|p=95}}{{sfn|Temple|2004|loc=45 min.}} On November 1989, Nintendo and Atari Games began a legal battle in the courts of [[San Francisco]]. Atari Games sought to prove that the NES was a computer, as indicated by its Japanese name \"Famicom\", an abbrieviation of \"Family Computer\". In this case, the initial license would then authorize Atari Games to release the game. The central argument of Atari Games was that the Famicom was designed to be convertible into a computer via its extension port. This argument was not accepted, and Pajitnov stressed that the initial contract only concerned computers and no other machine.{{sfn|Ichbiah|1997|p=96}} For its part, Nintendo brought Belikov to testify on its behalf.{{sfn|Temple|2004|loc=48 min.}} Judge Fern Smith then declared that Mirrorsoft and Spectrum HoloByte never received explicit authorization for marketing on consoles, and ruled in Nintendo's favor.{{sfn|Ichbiah|1997|p=96}} On June 21, 1989, Atari Games withdrew its NES version from sale, and thousands of cartridges remained unsold in the company's warehouses.<ref>{{cite magazine |title=From Russia with Litigation |magazine=[[Next Generation (magazine)|Next Generation]] |issue=26 |publisher=[[Imagine Media]] |date=February 1997 |page=42}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |year=2002 |title=The Wish List |journal=Edge Presents Retro}}</ref>\n\nSega had planned to release a [[Sega Genesis|Mega Drive]] version of ''Tetris'' on April 15, 1989, but they cancelled its release<ref>{{cite web|url=https://onitama.tv/gamemachine/pdf/19890501p.pdf#page=14|title=Game Machine: \"Nintendo Offers Home Video Game 'Tetris'\"|publisher=Amusement Press|date=1989-05-01}}</ref> during Atari's licensing issues, resulting in fewer than ten copies being printed.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://kotaku.com/you-could-own-this-copy-of-tetris-for-only-1-000-000-5822380 |title=You Could Own This Copy of Tetris for Only $1,000,000 |first=Michael |last=McWhertor |work=Kotaku |date=July 18, 2011 | access-date=June 4, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190604193847/https://kotaku.com/you-could-own-this-copy-of-tetris-for-only-1-000-000-5822380 |archive-date=June 4, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> A new port of the arcade version by M2 was included in the [[Sega Genesis Mini]] microconsole, released in September 2019.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.gameinformer.com/2019/06/04/final-12-genesis-mini-games-list-includes-one-of-the-worlds-rarest-versions-of-tetris |title=Archived copy |access-date=June 4, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190604221811/https://www.gameinformer.com/2019/06/04/final-12-genesis-mini-games-list-includes-one-of-the-worlds-rarest-versions-of-tetris |archive-date=June 4, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Commercial success and acquisition of rights by Pajitnov===\n{{Main|The Tetris Company}}\n[[File:Tetris NES play.png|thumb|right|250px|A-Type game screenshot of the official [[Nintendo Entertainment System|NES]] version of ''Tetris'']]\nThrough the legal history of the license, Pajitnov gained a reputation in the West. He was regularly invited by journalists and publishers, through which he discovered that his game had sold millions of copies, from which he had not made any money. However, he remained humble and proud of the game, which he considered \"an electronic ambassador of benevolence\".{{sfn|Ichbiah|1997|p=96}} In January 1990, he was invited by Spectrum HoloByte to the Consumer Electronics Show, and was immersed in American life for the first time.{{sfn|Ichbiah|1997|p=97}} After a period of adaptation, he explored American culture in several cities, including Las Vegas, San Francisco, [[New York City]] and [[Boston]], and engaged in interviews with several hosts, including the directors of Nintendo of America.{{sfn|Sheff|1999|p=347}} He marveled at the freedom and the advantages of Western society. Upon returning to the Soviet Union, he would never stop talking to his colleagues about his travels. He then realized that there was no market in Russia for their programs.{{sfn|Ichbiah|1997|p=97}} At the same time, Nintendo saw sales of the Game Boy \u2013 bundled with a handheld version of ''Tetris'' \u2013 explode, exceeding sales forecasts three times.{{sfn|Ichbiah|1997|p=97}}\n\nIn 1991, Pajitnov and Pokhilko emigrated to the United States.{{sfn|Ichbiah|1997|p=97}} Pajitnov moved to [[Seattle]], where he produced games for Spectrum HoloByte. In April 1996, as agreed with the Academy ten years earlier and following an agreement with Rogers, the rights to ''Tetris'' reverted to Pajitnov.<ref name=\"HenkRogersStory\">{{cite web |url=https://www.sramanamitra.com/2009/09/20/the-story-of-tetris-henk-rogers-part-5/ |title=The Story of ''Tetris'': Henk Rogers (Part 5) |website=Sramana Mitra |date=September 20, 2009 |accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref> Pajitnov and Rogers founded [[The Tetris Company]] in June 1996 to manage the game's rights on all platforms, the previous agreements having expired. Pajitnov now receives a royalty for each ''Tetris'' game and derivative sold worldwide.{{sfn|Ichbiah|1997|p=100}} In 2002, Pajitnov and Rogers founded Tetris Holding after the purchase of the game's remaining rights from Elorg, now a private entity following the [[dissolution of the Soviet Union]]. The Tetris Company now owns all rights to the ''Tetris'' brand, and is mainly responsible for removing illegal clones from the market;<ref name=\"HenkRogersStory\"/>{{sfn|Ichbiah|1997|p=100}} the company regularly calls on [[Apple Inc.]] and [[Google]] to remove illegal versions of ''Tetris'' from their mobile [[app store]]s.<ref name=\"iphonePurge\">{{cite web |url=https://arstechnica.com/gadgets/2008/10/tetris-co-strikes-again-another-iphone-app-clone-is-pulled/ |title=Tetris Co. strikes again: another iPhone app clone is pulled |website=Ars Technica |last=Chartier |first=David |date=October 8, 2008 |accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"androidPurge\">{{cite web |url=https://arstechnica.com/gadgets/2010/06/google-blocks-tetris-clones-from-android-market/ |title=Google blocks Tetris clones from Android market |website=Ars Technica |last=Ryan |first=Paul |date=June 2, 2010 |accessdate=June 23, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121202210616/http://arstechnica.com/gadgets/2010/06/google-blocks-tetris-clones-from-android-market/ |archive-date=December 2, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> In December 2005, [[Electronic Arts]] acquired Jamdat, a company specializing in mobile games.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20051208005771/en/EA-Acquire-JAMDAT-Mobile----Leader-North |title=EA to Acquire JAMDAT Mobile Inc. -- the Leader in North American Mobile Interactive Entertainment; Accelerates EA's Objective of Global Expansion in Mobile |website=Business Wire |date=December 8, 2005 |accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref> Jamdat had previously bought a company founded by Rogers in 2001, which managed the ''Tetris'' license on mobile platforms. As a result, Electronic Arts holds a 15-year license on all mobile phone releases of ''Tetris''.<ref name=\"HenkRogersStory\"/>\n\n==Versions==\n{{Main|List of Tetris variants}}\n[[File:Tetris on an iPod.jpg|250px|thumb|A [[iPod classic|5th generation]] [[iPod]] running ''Tetris'' (2006)]]\n''Tetris'' has been released on a multitude of platforms since the creation of the original version on the [[Electronika 60]]. The game is available on most game consoles and is playable on personal computers, smartphones and [[iPod]]s. ''[[Guinness World Records]]'' has recognized the game as being the most ported in the history of video gaming, having appeared on over 65 different platforms as of October 2010.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/records-3000/most-ported-computer-game/ |title=Most ported computer game |publisher=Guinnessworldrecords.com |date=October 1, 2010 |accessdate=June 7, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131202223258/http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/records-3000/most-ported-computer-game/ |archive-date=December 2, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> Since the 2000s, Internet versions of the game have also been developed. However, commercial versions not approved by The Tetris Company tend to be purged due to company policy.<ref name=\"iphonePurge\"/><ref name=\"androidPurge\"/> The most famous online version, ''[[Tetris Friends]]'' by [[Tetris Online, Inc.]], had attracted over a million registered users.<ref name=\"TetrisFriendsMillion\">{{cite web |url=http://www.marketwired.com/press-release/Tetris-Friends-Online-Games-Hits-1-Million-Milestone-Launches-Tetris-Arena-1167945.htm |title=''Tetris\u00ae Friends'' Online Games Hits 1 Million Milestone, Launches ''Tetris Arena'' |last=Musselman |first=Katie |date=April 13, 2010 |website=Marketwire |archiveurl=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.marketwired.com%2Fpress-release%2FTetris-Friends-Online-Games-Hits-1-Million-Milestone-Launches-Tetris-Arena-1167945.htm |archivedate=February 4, 2015}}</ref> Tetris Online had also developed versions for console-based digital download services.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tetrisonline.com/games/tetris_party_dsi.php |title=''Tetris\u00ae Party Live'' |website=Tetris Online |archiveurl=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.tetrisonline.com%2Fgames%2Ftetris_party_dsi.php |archivedate=June 9, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tetrisonline.com/games/tetris_splash_xbla.php |title=''Tetris\u00ae Splash'' |website=Tetris Online |archiveurl=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.tetrisonline.com%2Fgames%2Ftetris_splash_xbla.php |archivedate=May 28, 2011}}</ref> Because of its popularity and simplicity of development, ''Tetris'' is often used as a [[Hello world program|hello world]] project for programmers coding for a new system or programming language. This has resulted in the availability of a large number of [[Porting|ports]] for different platforms. For instance, [[\u03bcTorrent]] and [[Emacs|GNU Emacs]] contain similar shape-stacking games as easter eggs.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.eeggs.com/items/47291.html |title=uTorrent Easter Egg: Tetris in uTorrent |publisher=Eeggs.com |date=March 16, 2006 |accessdate=November 22, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121121044523/http://www.eeggs.com/items/47291.html |archive-date=November 21, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=poenn |url=http://hints.macworld.com/article.php?story=20050103201954271 |title=macosxhints.com \u2013 Play Tetris in Terminal via emacs |publisher=Hints.macworld.com |accessdate=November 22, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130522153944/http://hints.macworld.com/article.php?story=20050103201954271 |archive-date=May 22, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nWithin official franchise installments, each version has made improvements to accomodate advancing technology and the goal to provide a more complete game. Developers are given freedom to add new modes of play and revisit the concept from different angles. Some concepts developed on official versions have been integrated into the ''Tetris'' guidelines in order to standardize future versions and allow players to migrate between different versions with little effort.<ref name=\"tftt\"/> The IBM PC version was the most evolved from the original version, featuring a graphical interface, colored tetrominoes, running statistics for the number of tetrominoes placed, and a guide for the controls.<ref name=\"vadim\"/>\n\n== Computational complexity ==\nIn [[computer science]], it is common to analyze the [[Computational complexity theory|computational complexity]] of problems, including real life problems and games. It was proven that for the \"offline\" version of ''Tetris'' (the player knows the complete sequence of pieces that will be dropped, i.e. there is no hidden information) the following objectives are [[NP-complete]]:\n* Maximizing the number of rows cleared while playing the given piece sequence.\n* Maximizing the number of pieces placed before a loss occurs.\n* Maximizing the number of simultaneous clearing of four rows.\n* Minimizing the height of the highest filled grid square over the course of the sequence.\n\nAlso, it is [[Hardness of approximation|difficult to even approximately solve]] the first, second, and fourth problem.  It is [[NP-hard]], given an initial gameboard and a sequence of ''p'' pieces, to approximate the first two problems to within a factor of {{nowrap|''p''<sup>1 \u2212 ''\u03b5''</sup>}} for any constant {{nowrap|''\u03b5'' > 0}}.\nIt is NP-hard to approximate the last problem within a factor of {{nowrap|2 \u2212 ''\u03b5''}} for any constant {{nowrap|''\u03b5'' > 0}}.\n\nTo prove NP-completeness, it was shown that there is a polynomial [[Reduction (complexity)|reduction]] between the [[3-partition problem]], which is also NP-complete, and the ''Tetris'' problem.<ref>{{cite conference|url=http://erikdemaine.org/papers/Tetris_COCOON2003/paper.pdf|title=Tetris is Hard, Even to Approximate|last1=Demaine|first1=Erik D.|last2=Hohenberger|first2=Susan|last3=Liben-Nowell|first3=David|date=July 25\u201328, 2003|conference=Proceedings of the 9th International Computing and Combinatorics Conference (COCOON 2003)|conferenceurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120105042734/http://www.cs.montana.edu/bhz/cocoon03.html|location=Big Sky, Montana|access-date=December 18, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100613201613/http://erikdemaine.org/papers/Tetris_COCOON2003/paper.pdf|archive-date=June 13, 2010|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Music==\n{{See also|Korobeiniki#Tetris arrangements and modern cover versions|Tetris (Game Boy video game)#Music}}\nThe earliest versions of ''Tetris'' had no music. The NES version includes two original compositions by [[Hirokazu Tanaka]] along with an arrangement of \"Dance of the Sugar Plum Fairy\" from the second act of ''[[The Nutcracker]]'', composed by [[Pyotr Ilyich Tchaikovsky|Tchaikovsky]]. The [[Blue Planet Software]] and [[Tengen (company)|Tengen]] versions also feature original music, with the exception of an arrangement of \"[[Kalinka (song)|Kalinka]]\" in the Tengen version. Nintendo's Game Boy version includes three pieces of music as well: \"[[Korobeiniki]]\", [[Johann Sebastian Bach]]'s [[French Suites, BWV 812-817|French Suite No. 3 In B Minor]] (BWV 814), and an original track by Tanaka. \"Korobeiniki\" is used in most later versions of the game, and has appeared in other games, albums and films that make reference to ''Tetris''. In the 2000s, The Tetris Company added as a prerequisite for the granting of the license that a version of \"Korobeiniki\" be available in the game.<ref name=guardian020609/>\n\n== Cognitive effects ==\n{{See also|Tetris effect}}\nAccording to research from Dr. Richard Haier, ''et al.'' prolonged ''Tetris'' activity can also lead to more efficient brain activity during play.<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Richard J Haier|author2=Sherif Karama|author3=Leonard Leyba|author4=Rex E Jung|title=MRI assessment of cortical thickness and functional activity changes in adolescent girls following three months of practice on a visual-spatial task|journal=BMC Research Notes|year=2009|doi=10.1186/1756-0500-2-174|pmid=19723307|volume=2|page=174|pmc=2746806}}</ref> When first playing ''Tetris'', brain function and activity increases, along with greater cerebral energy consumption, measured by [[glucose]] metabolic rate. As ''Tetris'' players become more proficient, their brains show a reduced consumption of glucose, indicating more efficient brain activity for this task.<ref>{{cite journal|vauthors=Haier RJ, Siegel BV, MacLachlan A, Soderling E, Lottenberg S, Buchsbaum MS|title=Regional glucose metabolic changes after learning a complex visuospatial/motor task: a positron emission tomographic study|journal=Brain Res.|volume=570|issue=1\u20132|pages=134\u201343|date=January 1992|pmid=1617405|doi=10.1016/0006-8993(92)90573-R}}</ref> Moderate play of ''Tetris'' (half-an-hour a day for three months) boosts general cognitive functions such as \"critical thinking, reasoning, language and processing\" and increases [[cerebral cortex]] thickness.<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/science/science-news/6122290/Tetris-could-boost-brain-power.html Tetris 'could boost brain power'] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100212121948/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/science/science-news/6122290/Tetris-could-boost-brain-power.html |date=February 12, 2010 }} Telegraph news, September 2, 2009</ref>\n\nIn January 2009, an Oxford University research group headed by Dr. Emily Holmes reported in ''[[PLoS ONE]]'' that for healthy volunteers, playing ''Tetris'' soon after viewing traumatic material in the laboratory reduced the number of flashbacks to those scenes in the following week. They believe that the computer game may disrupt the memories that are retained of the sights and sounds witnessed at the time, and which are later re-experienced through involuntary, distressing flashbacks of that moment. The group hopes to develop this approach further as a potential intervention to reduce the flashbacks experienced in [[post-traumatic stress disorder]] but emphasized that these are only preliminary results.<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Holmes EA|author2=James EL|author3=Coode-Bate T|author4=Deeprose C|title=Can playing the computer game \"Tetris\" reduce the build-up of flashbacks for trauma? A proposal from cognitive science|journal=PLoS ONE|volume=4|issue=1|pages= e4153|year=2009|pmid=19127289|pmc=2607539|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0004153|editor1-last=Bell|editor1-first=Vaughan|bibcode=2009PLoSO...4.4153H}}</ref>\n\nProfessor Jackie Andrade and Jon May, from [[Plymouth University]]'s Cognition Institute, and Ph.D. student Jessica Skorka-Brown have conducted research that shows that playing ''Tetris'' could distract from cravings and give a \"quick and manageable\" fix for people struggling to stick to diets, or quit smoking or drinking.<ref>{{cite news|last=GANDER|first=KASHMIRA|title=Playing Tetris could help with weight loss and smokers' cravings, psychologists claim|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/gadgets-and-tech/news/playing-tetris-could-help-with-weight-loss-and-smokers-cravings-psychologists-claim-9149045.html|newspaper=The Independent|accessdate=February 24, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140224123004/http://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/gadgets-and-tech/news/playing-tetris-could-help-with-weight-loss-and-smokers-cravings-psychologists-claim-9149045.html|archive-date=February 24, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAnother notable effect is that, according to a Canadian study in April 2013, playing ''Tetris'' has been found to treat older adolescents with [[amblyopia]] (lazy eye), which was better than patching a victim's well eye to train their weaker eye. Dr. Robert Hess of the research team said: \"It's much better than patching \u2013 much more enjoyable; it's faster, and it seems to work better.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2013/04/23/study-finds-tetris-effectively-treats-lazy-eye|title=A Study Find That ''Tetris'' Effectively Treats a Lazy Eye|author=Luke Karmali|website=[[IGN]]|date=April 23, 2013|accessdate=June 20, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150620113327/http://www.ign.com/articles/2013/04/23/study-finds-tetris-effectively-treats-lazy-eye|archive-date=June 20, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> Tested in the [[United Kingdom]], this experiment also appears to help children with that problem.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-glasgow-west-17616818|title=Video Game Treatment for a Lazy Eye|work=[[BBC News]]|date=April 4, 2012|accessdate=June 20, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150819214014/http://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-glasgow-west-17616818|archive-date=August 19, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe game has been noted to cause the brain to involuntarily picture ''Tetris'' combinations even when the player is not playing (the [[Tetris effect|''Tetris'' effect]]), although this can occur with any computer game or situation showcasing repeated images or scenarios, such as a [[jigsaw puzzle]]. While debates about Tetris's cognitive benefits continue, at least some researchers view it as a milestone in the gamification of education.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://news.elearninginside.com/game-changing-arrival-tetris-united-states/|title=It has been 30 years since Tetris arrived in the U.S.|date=January 29, 2018|work=eLearningInside News|access-date=November 15, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181116085344/https://news.elearninginside.com/game-changing-arrival-tetris-united-states/|archive-date=November 16, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Reception and legacy==\n{{Video game reviews\n| Allgame = Arcade: {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite web|last=Cook|first=Brad|title=Tetris|url=http://www.allgame.com/game.php?id=2784&tab=review|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141114201703/http://www.allgame.com/game.php?id=2784&tab=review|url-status=dead|archive-date=November 14, 2014|publisher=AllGame|accessdate=June 9, 2014}}</ref><br />C64: {{Rating|3|5}}<ref>{{cite web|last=Sutyak|first=Jonathan|title=Tetris|url=http://www.allgame.com/game.php?id=16887&tab=review|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141115004356/http://www.allgame.com/game.php?id=16887&tab=review|archive-date=November 15, 2014|publisher=AllGame |url-status=dead|accessdate=June 9, 2014}}</ref><br />Macintosh: {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite web|last=Savignano|first=Lisa Karen|title=Tetris|url=http://www.allgame.com/game.php?id=11800&tab=review|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141115004358/http://www.allgame.com/game.php?id=11800&tab=review|archive-date=November 15, 2014|publisher=AllGame|url-status=dead|accessdate=June 9, 2014}}</ref><br />NES&nbsp;(Tengen):&nbsp;{{Rating|4.5|5}}&nbsp;<ref>{{cite web|last=Miller|first=Skyler|title=Tetris|url=http://www.allgame.com/game.php?id=14911&tab=review|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141115004353/http://www.allgame.com/game.php?id=14911&tab=review|archive-date=November 15, 2014|publisher=AllGame |url-status=dead|accessdate=June 9, 2014}}</ref><br />NES&nbsp;(Nintendo):&nbsp;{{Rating|4.5|5}}&nbsp;<ref>{{cite web|last=Weiss|first=Brett Alan|title=Tetris|url=http://www.allgame.com/game.php?id=1331&tab=review|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100216081022/http://allgame.com/game.php?id=1331&tab=review|archive-date=February 16, 2010|publisher=AllGame |url-status=dead|accessdate=June 9, 2014}}</ref>\n| CVG = 94%<ref name=\"CVG-1989-review\">{{cite magazine |url=http://live.worldofspectrum.org/files/thumb/4f2e51c9cdbbfbe/800/800 |title=Tetris Mastertronic |magazine=[[Computer and Video Games]] |issue=92 |page=74 |date=June 1989 |accessdate=November 22, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190417032455/http://live.worldofspectrum.org/files/thumb/4f2e51c9cdbbfbe/800/800 |archive-date=April 17, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| CRASH = 77%<ref name=\"Crash-19880review\">{{cite magazine |url=http://live.worldofspectrum.org/files/thumb/78d7602b35d0e2d/800/800 |title=Reviews: Tetris |magazine=[[Crash (magazine)|Crash]] |issue=50 |page=10 |date=March 1988 |accessdate=November 22, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190417032452/http://live.worldofspectrum.org/files/thumb/78d7602b35d0e2d/800/800 |archive-date=April 17, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| SUser = {{Rating|10|10}}<ref name=\"SinclairU-1988-review\">{{cite web |url=http://live.worldofspectrum.org/files/thumb/c53e67fb08dbe15/800/800 |title=TET\u042fIS: Arcade Review |magazine=[[Sinclair User]] |issue=1988 |page=13 |date=February 1988 |accessdate=November 22, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190417032457/http://live.worldofspectrum.org/files/thumb/c53e67fb08dbe15/800/800 |archive-date=April 17, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| YSinclair = 9/10<ref>{{cite web|last=Worrall|first=Tony|title=Tetris|url=http://www.ysrnry.co.uk/articles/tetris.htm|publisher=The Your Sinclair Rock'n'Roll Years|accessdate=August 8, 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120427113515/http://www.ysrnry.co.uk/articles/tetris.htm|archivedate=April 27, 2012}}</ref>\n| rev1 = ''[[Zzap!64]]''\n| rev1Score = 98%<ref>{{cite web|title=Gold Standard|url=http://www.zzap64.co.uk/zzap100/100thspec5.html|publisher=The Def Gui to Zzap!64|accessdate=August 8, 2012|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6Dzo6NOv6?url=http://www.zzap64.co.uk/zzap100/100thspec5.html|archive-date=January 28, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[ACE (games magazine)|ACE]]''\n| rev2Score = 95%<ref name=\"ACE-1988-review\">{{cite web |url=http://live.worldofspectrum.org/files/thumb/4852d3d00d9894b/800/800 |title=Tetris: Can MIRRORSOFT pack them in? |publisher=[[ACE (games magazine)|ACE]] |issue=5 |page=49 |date=February 1988 |accessdate=November 22, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190417035859/http://live.worldofspectrum.org/files/thumb/4852d3d00d9894b/800/800 |archive-date=April 17, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| award1Pub = Zzap!64\n| award1 = Gold Medal\n| award2Pub = Sinclair User\n| award2 = SU Classic\n}}\n''[[Compute!]]'' called the IBM version of ''Tetris'' \"one of the most addictive computer games this side of the [[Berlin Wall]] ... [it] is ''not'' the game to start if you have work to do or an appointment to keep. Consider yourself warned\".<ref name=\"weatherman198807\">{{cite news | url=https://archive.org/stream/1988-07-compute-magazine/Compute_Issue_098_1988_Jul#page/n73/mode/2up | title=Tetris | work=Compute! | date=July 1988 | accessdate=November 10, 2013 | author=Weatherman, Lynne | page=72 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140316211621/https://archive.org/stream/1988-07-compute-magazine/Compute_Issue_098_1988_Jul#page/n73/mode/2up | archive-date=March 16, 2014 | url-status=live }}</ref> [[Orson Scott Card]] joked that the game \"proves that Russia still wants to [[We will bury you|bury us]]. I shudder to think of the blow to our economy as computer productivity drops to 0\". Noting that ''Tetris'' was not copy-protected, he wrote \"Obviously, the game is meant to find its way onto every American machine\".<ref name=\"card198904\">{{cite news | url=https://archive.org/stream/1989-04-compute-magazine/Compute_Issue_107_1989_Apr#page/n11/mode/2up | title=Gameplay | work=Compute! | date=April 1989 | accessdate=November 10, 2013 | author=Card, Orson Scott | page=11 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140316211723/https://archive.org/stream/1989-04-compute-magazine/Compute_Issue_107_1989_Apr#page/n11/mode/2up | archive-date=March 16, 2014 | url-status=live }}</ref> The IBM version of the game was reviewed in 1988 in ''[[Dragon (magazine)|Dragon]]'' No. 135 by Hartley, Patricia, and Kirk Lesser in \"The Role of Computers\" column. The reviewers gave the game 4.5 out of 5 stars.<ref name=\"Dragon135\">{{cite journal|title=The Role of Computers|last1=Lesser|last2=Lesser|last3=Lesser|first1=Hartley|first2=Patricia|first3=Kirk|journal=Dragon|issue=135|date=July 1988|pages=82\u201389}}</ref> The Lessers later reviewed Spectrum HoloByte's [[Macintosh]] version of ''Tetris'' in 1989 in ''Dragon'' No. 141, giving that version 5 out of 5 stars.<ref name=\"Dragon141\">{{cite journal|title= The Role of Computers|last1=Lesser|last2=Lesser|last3=Lesser|first1=Hartley|first2=Patricia|first3=Kirk|journal=Dragon|issue=141|date= January 1989|pages=72\u201378}}</ref> ''[[Macworld]]'' reviewed the Macintosh version of ''Tetris'' in 1988, praising its stategic gameplay, stating that \"''Tetris'' offers the rare combination of being simple to learn but extremely challenging to play\", and also praising the inclusion of the [[Desk Accessory]] version, which uses less RAM. ''Macworld'' summarized their review by listing ''Tetris' ''pros and cons, stating that ''Tetris'' is \"Elegant; easy to play; challenging and addicting; requires quick thinking, long-term strategy, and lightning reflexes\" and listed ''Tetris''' cons as \"None.\"<ref>{{cite magazine|last = Buderi|first = Robert|title = Tetris 1.0 Review|date = December 1988|url = https://archive.org/details/MacWorld_8812_December_1988/page/n181|magazine = Macworld|publisher = Mac Publishing|page = 178}}</ref>\n\nIn 1993, the ZX Spectrum version of the game was voted number 49 in the ''[[Your Sinclair]] Official Top 100 Games of All Time''.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Top 100 Games of All Time|journal=Your Sinclair|date=September 1993}}</ref> In 1996, ''Tetris Pro'' was ranked the 38th best game of all time by ''[[Amiga Power]]''.<ref>Amiga Power magazine issue 64, Future Publishing, August 1996</ref> ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' picked the game as the #8 greatest game available in 1991, saying: \"Thanks to Nintendo\u2019s endless promotion, Tetris has become one of the most popular video games.\"<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://ew.com/article/1991/11/22/video-games-guide/ | title=Video Games Guide | access-date=September 9, 2018 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170219184932/http://ew.com/article/1991/11/22/video-games-guide/ | archive-date=February 19, 2017 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n''Computer Gaming World'' gave ''Tetris'' the 1989 Compute! Choice Award for Arcade Game, describing it as \"by far, the most addictive game ever\".<ref name=\"compute198901\">{{cite news | url=https://archive.org/stream/1989-01-compute-magazine/Compute_Issue_104_1989_Jan#page/n25/mode/2up | title=The 189 Compute! Choice Awards | work=Compute! | date=January 1989 | accessdate=November 10, 2013 | page=24 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140316200847/https://archive.org/stream/1989-01-compute-magazine/Compute_Issue_104_1989_Jan#page/n25/mode/2up | archive-date=March 16, 2014 | url-status=live }}</ref> The game won three [[Software Publishers Association]] Excellence in Software Awards in 1989, including Best Entertainment Program and the Critic's Choice Award for consumers.<ref name=\"scisco198908\">{{cite news | url=https://archive.org/stream/1989-08-compute-magazine/Compute_Issue_111_1989_Aug#page/n7/mode/2up | title=the Envelope, Please | work=Compute! | date=August 1989 | accessdate=November 11, 2013 | author=Scisco, Peter | page=6 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140316211940/https://archive.org/stream/1989-08-compute-magazine/Compute_Issue_111_1989_Aug#page/n7/mode/2up | archive-date=March 16, 2014 | url-status=live }}</ref> ''Computer Gaming World'' in 1996 ranked it 14th on the magazine's list of the most innovative computer games.<ref name=\"cgw199611mostinnovative\">{{cite news | url=http://www.cgwmuseum.org/galleries/index.php?year=1996&pub=2&id=148 | title=The 15 Most Innovative Computer Games | work=Computer Gaming World | date=November 1996 | accessdate=March 25, 2016 | pages=102 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160408023915/http://cgwmuseum.org/galleries/index.php?year=1996&pub=2&id=148 | archive-date=April 8, 2016 | url-status=live }}</ref> That same year, ''[[Next Generation (magazine)|Next Generation]]'' listed it as number 2 on their \"Top 100 Games of All Time\", commenting that, \"There is something so perfect, so [[Zen]] about the falling blocks of ''Tetris'' that the game has captured the interest of everyone who has ever played it.\"<ref>{{cite magazine|last=|first= |title=Top 100 Games of All Time |magazine=[[Next Generation (magazine)|Next Generation]]|issue=21 |publisher=[[Imagine Media]] |date=September 1996|page=71}}</ref> On March 12, 2007, ''[[The New York Times]]'' reported that ''Tetris'' was named to a list of the ten most important video games of all time, the so-called [[game canon]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/03/12/arts/design/12vide.html?ex=1331352000&en=380fc9bb18694da5&ei=5124&partner=permalink&exprod=permalink|title=Is That Just Some Game? No, It's a Cultural Artifact|newspaper=[[nytimes.com]]|first=HEATHER|last=CHAPLIN|date=March 12, 2007|accessdate=November 1, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151204212137/http://www.nytimes.com/2007/03/12/arts/design/12vide.html?ex=1331352000&en=380fc9bb18694da5&ei=5124&partner=permalink&exprod=permalink|archive-date=December 4, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> After announced at the 2007 [[Game Developers Conference]], the [[Library of Congress]] took up the video game preservation proposal and began with these 10 games, including ''Tetris''.<ref name=\"Joystiq\">{{cite web|url=http://www.joystiq.com/2007/03/12/10-most-important-video-games-of-all-time-as-judged-by-2-design/ |title=10 most important video games of all time, as judged by 2 designers, 2 academics, and 1 lowly blogger |last=Ransom-Wiley |first=James |publisher=Joystiq |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140422035847/http://www.joystiq.com/2007/03/12/10-most-important-video-games-of-all-time-as-judged-by-2-design/ |archivedate=April 22, 2014 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.loc.gov/digitalpreservation/2012/09/yes-the-library-of-congress-has-video-games-an-interview-with-david-gibson/ |title=Yes, The Library of Congress Has Video Games: An Interview with David Gibson |date=September 26, 2012 |accessdate=January 18, 2013 |publisher=blogs.loc.gov |first=Trevor |last=Owens |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131205100245/http://blogs.loc.gov/digitalpreservation/2012/09/yes-the-library-of-congress-has-video-games-an-interview-with-david-gibson/ |archivedate=December 5, 2013 |df= }}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, video game website [[GameFAQs]] hosted its sixth annual \"[[GameFAQs#Contests|Character Battle]]\", in which the users nominate their favorite video game characters for a popularity contest in which characters participate. The L-shaped ''Tetris'' piece (or \"L-Block\" as it was called) entered the contest as a joke character, but on November 4, 2007, it won the contest.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamefaqs.com/features/contest/cb6|title=Fall 2007: The Great GameFAQs Character Battle VI|website=GameFAQs|accessdate=November 29, 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071029201304/http://www.gamefaqs.com/features/contest/cb6|archive-date=October 29, 2007|url-status=live}}</ref> On June 6, 2009, Google honored ''Tetris''{{'}} 25-year anniversary by changing its logotype to a version drawn with ''Tetris'' blocks \u2013 the \"l\" letter being the long ''Tetris'' block lowering into its place,<ref>{{cite web|title=Google Features TETRIS Look For Game's 25th Anniversary|url=http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20090605005609/en|publisher=Electronic Arts|date=June 5, 2009|quote=Google will roll out the TETRIS-inspired design in 24-hour periods, starting first at 1:00&nbsp;pm EDT in Japan, Australia, and New Zealand. From 6:00&nbsp;pm&nbsp; \u2013 7:00&nbsp;pm EDT, the TETRIS-inspired design will begin appearing in Europe, Asia, Africa, and the Middle East. Starting June 6th, at 12:00&nbsp;am EDT, the TETRIS-inspired design will be available in North and South America.|accessdate=September 25, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110216141150/http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20090605005609/en|archive-date=February 16, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> seen here.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.google.com/doodles/25-years-of-tetris-courtesy-of-tetris-holding-llc |title=25 Years of Tetris \u2013 courtesy of Tetris Holding, LLC |date=June 6, 2009 |accessdate=November 22, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121104165253/http://www.google.com/doodles/25-years-of-tetris-courtesy-of-tetris-holding-llc |archive-date=November 4, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> In 2009, ''[[Game Informer]]'' put ''Tetris'' 3rd on their list of \"The Top 200 Games of All Time\", saying that \"If a game could be considered ageless, it's ''Tetris''\".<ref name=\"gi_best\">{{cite journal|author=The ''Game Informer'' staff|title=The Top 200 Games of All Time|pages=44\u201379|issue= 200|date=December 2009|journal=Game Informer|issn=1067-6392|oclc=27315596}}</ref> The ''Game Informer'' staff also placed it third on their 2001 list of the 100 best games ever.<ref>{{cite web |title=Game Informer's Top 100 Games of All Time (Circa Issue 100) |url=http://www.gameinformer.com/b/features/archive/2009/11/16/game-informer-s-top-100-games-of-all-time-circa-issue-100.aspx |work=[[Game Informer]] |last=Cork |first=Jeff |date=November 16, 2009 |accessdate=December 10, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100408113757/http://gameinformer.com/b/features/archive/2009/11/16/game-informer-s-top-100-games-of-all-time-circa-issue-100.aspx |archive-date=April 8, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n''[[Electronic Gaming Monthly]]''{{'}}s 100th issue had ''Tetris'' as first place in the \"100 Best Games of All Time\", commenting that \"''Tetris'' is as pure as a video game can get. ... When the right blocks come your way - and if you can manage to avoid mistakes - the game can be relaxing. One mislaid block, however, and your duties switch to damage control, a mad, panicky dash to clean up your mess or die.\" ''Tetris'' was also the only game for which the list did not specify one or two versions; the editors explained that after deadlocking over which version was best, they concluded that there was no wrong version of ''Tetris'' to play.<ref>{{cite magazine |title=100 Best Games of All Time |magazine=[[Electronic Gaming Monthly]]|issue=100 |publisher=[[Ziff Davis]] |date=November 1997|page=160}} Note: Contrary to the title, the intro to the article (on page 100) explicitly states that the list covers console video games only, meaning PC games and arcade games were not eligible.</ref> In 2007, ''Tetris'' came in second place in [[IGN]]'s \"100 Greatest Video Games of All Time\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://top100.ign.com/2007/ign_top_game_2.html |title=IGN Top 100 Games of All Time \u2013 2007 |publisher=Top100.ign.com |date= |accessdate=November 22, 2012|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131107133844/http://top100.ign.com/2007/ign_top_game_2.html|archivedate=November 7, 2013}}</ref> In January 2010, it was announced that the [[List of Tetris variants|''Tetris'' franchise]] had sold more than 170 million copies, approximately 70 million physical copies and over 100 million copies [[Tetris (Electronic Arts)|for cell phones]],<ref name=guardian020609/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.maximejohnson.com/techno/2010/01/tetris-atteint-les-100-millions-de-telechargements-payants-et-une-petite-histoire-du-jeu/ |title=\u00bb Tetris atteint les 100 millions de t\u00e9l\u00e9chargements payants (et une petite histoire du jeu) \u2013 Maximejohnson.com/techno : actualit\u00e9s technologiques, tests et opinions par le j |publisher=Maximejohnson.com |date=January 19, 2011 |accessdate=November 22, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120726141129/http://www.maximejohnson.com/techno/2010/01/tetris-atteint-les-100-millions-de-telechargements-payants-et-une-petite-histoire-du-jeu/ |archive-date=July 26, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> making it one of the [[List of best-selling video game franchises|best-selling video game franchises of all time]]. {{As of|2011|12}}, ''Tetris'' has sold 132{{nbsp}}million paid [[mobile game]] downloads.<ref>{{cite news |title=EA Launches New Tetris\u00ae Game on the App Store Today |url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20111201006159/en/EA-Launches-New-Tetris%C2%AE-Game-App-Store |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=[[Business Wire]] |date=1 December 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 1991, ''[[PC Format]]'' named ''Tetris'' one of the 50 best computer games ever. The editors called it \"incredibly addictive\" and \"one of the best games of all time\".<ref name=pcformat50>{{cite journal | author=Staff | journal=[[PC Format]] | title=The 50 best games EVER! |date=October 1991 | issue=1 | pages=109\u2013111 }}</ref>\n\nThere was a hoax that circulated in February 2019 that the original NES instruction manual for ''Tetris'' had named the seven tetrominos with names like \"Orange Ricky\", \"Hero\" and \"Smashboy\", but was disproven. Despite being disproven by video game historians, a question on the October 7, 2019 airing of ''[[Jeopardy!]]'' alluded to these names.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://kotaku.com/jeopardy-airs-a-hilariously-incorrect-bit-of-tetris-tr-1838889592 | title = Jeopardy! Airs A Hilariously Incorrect Bit Of Tetris Trivia | first = Chris | last = Kohler | date = October 8, 2019 | accessdate = October 8, 2019 | work = [[Kotaku]] }}</ref>\n\n=== In research ===\n''Tetris'' has been the subject of academic research. [[Vladimir Pokhilko]] was the first clinical psychologist to conduct experiments using ''Tetris''.<ref name=\"MarkWolf2012\">{{cite book | author=Mark J. P. Wolf | title=Encyclopedia of Video Games: The Culture, Technology, and Art of Gaming | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=deBFx7QAwsQC&pg=PA642 | accessdate=February 5, 2013 | date=August 31, 2012 | publisher=ABC-CLIO | isbn=978-0-313-37936-9 | page=642 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130528022924/http://books.google.com/books?id=deBFx7QAwsQC&pg=PA642 | archive-date=May 28, 2013 | url-status=live }}</ref> Subsequently, it has been used for research in several fields including the [[theory of computation]], algorithmic theory, and [[cognitive psychology]].\n\nDuring the game of ''Tetris'', blocks appear to [[Adsorption|adsorb]] onto the lower surface of the window. This has led scientists to use tetrominoes \"as a proxy for molecules with a complex shape\" to model their \"[[adsorption]] on a flat surface\" to study the [[thermodynamics]] of [[nanoparticles]].<ref>[https://arstechnica.com/science/news/2009/05/the-thermodynamics-of-tetris.ars The Thermodynamics of Tetiris] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110912220000/http://arstechnica.com/science/news/2009/05/the-thermodynamics-of-tetris.ars |date=September 12, 2011 }}, Ars Technica, 2009.</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.1021/la900196b| pmid=19397254|title = Structure, Thermodynamics, and Solubility in Tetromino Fluids| journal=Langmuir| volume=25| issue=12| pages=6702\u20136716|year = 2009|last1 = Barnes|first1 = Brian C.| last2=Siderius| first2=Daniel W.| last3=Gelb| first3=Lev D.| doi-access=free}}</ref>\n\n== Film ==\n[[Threshold Entertainment]] has teamed up with The Tetris Company to develop a film adaptation of ''Tetris''. Threshold's CEO describes the film as an epic sci-fi adventure that will form part of a trilogy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.movieweb.com/tetris-movie-story|title='Tetris' Movie Planned as an Epic Sci-Fi Adventure|work=Movieweb|date=September 30, 2014|accessdate=September 30, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141001011505/http://www.movieweb.com/tetris-movie-story|archive-date=October 1, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/tetris-movie-be-80m-us-894779|title='Tetris' Movie to Be $80M U.S.-China Co-Production|magazine=The Hollywood Reporter|last=Brzeski|first=Patrick|date=May 17, 2016|access-date=May 17, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160518095550/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/tetris-movie-be-80m-us-894779|archive-date=May 18, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2016, sources reported on a press release claiming the film would be shot in China in 2017 with an $80 million budget. However, no 2017 or later sources confirm the film ever actually went into production.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mashable.com/2016/05/17/tetris-movie-real/|title=Is this 'Tetris' movie for real? Too many key blocks are missing to be sure|last=Dickey|first=Josh|date=May 17, 2016|publisher=Mashable|access-date=June 24, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180624093105/https://mashable.com/2016/05/17/tetris-movie-real/|archive-date=June 24, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n''Tetris'' appeared in the 2010 short animated film [[Pixels (2010 film)|''Pixels'']], and in the 2015 movie ''[[Pixels (2015 film)|Pixels]]'' inspired by the former.<ref>{{Citation|title=Pixels (2015)|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt2120120/movieconnections|accessdate=February 3, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161118041924/http://www.imdb.com/title/tt2120120/movieconnections|archive-date=November 18, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Video Games|1980s|1990s}}\n* ''[[Pentomino]]'' [[tiling puzzle]]s and games are popular in [[recreational mathematics]].\n* ''[[Brain Wall]]'' and ''[[Blokken]]'' \u2014 game shows based on ''Tetris''\n* ''[[Ecstasy of Order: The Tetris Masters]]'' \u2014 2011 documentary about the 2010 ''Tetris'' Championships featuring interviews with Pajitnov and Dr. Richard Haier.\n* ''[[Game Over (book)|Game Over]]'' \u2014 1993 book covering Nintendo history, including interviews with Alexey Pajitnov and others regarding ''Tetris'' licensing.\n* [[List of Tetris variants|List of ''Tetris'' variants]]\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite web | url = http://vadim.oversigma.com/Tetris.htm | title = Tetris Story | last = Gerasimov | first = Vadim | website = [[Vadim Gerasimov|OverSigma]]}}\n* {{cite web | url = http://www.scientificamerican.com/article/mathematicians-prove-tetr/ | title = Mathematicians Prove Tetris Is Tough | last = Graham | first = Sarah | date = October 29, 2002 | website = [[Scientific American]]}}\n* {{cite AV media | url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p00mdqf8 | title = The creation of Tetris | date = December 29, 2012 | website = [[BBC World Service]] | publisher = [[BBC]]}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n===Books===\n* {{Cite book |last=Brzustowski |first=John |title=Can You Win at Tetris? |year=1992 |publisher=University of British Columbia |url=https://open.library.ubc.ca/cIRcle/collections/ubctheses/831/items/1.0079748}}\n* {{Cite book |last=Ichbiah |first=Daniel |title=La Saga des Jeux Vid\u00e9o |language=French |year=1997 |publisher=Pix'N Love Editions |edition=1st |pages=84\u2013100 |isbn=2266087630}}\n* {{Cite book |last1=Sheff |first1=David |last2=Eddy |first2=Andy |title=Game Over: Press Start to Continue |publisher=Cyberactive Media Group |year=1999 |edition=1st |pages=295-348 |isbn=0966961706}}\n* {{Cite book |last=Kent |first=Steven |title=The Ultimate History of Video Games: From Pong to Pokemon: The Story Behind the Craze That Touched Our Lives and Changed the World |publisher=Three Rivers Press |year=2001 |edition=1st |pages=377-381 |isbn=9780761536437}}\n* {{Cite book |last1=Loguidice |first1=Bill |last2=Barton |first2=Matt |year=2009 |title=Vintage Games: An Insider Look at the History of the Most Influential Games of All Time |url=https://www.routledge.com/Vintage-Games-An-Insider-Look-at-the-History-of-Grand-Theft-Auto-Super/Loguidice-Barton/p/book/9780240811468 |edition=1st |publisher=[[Focal Press]] |pages=291\u2013301 |isbn=0240811461}}\n* {{Cite book |last=Trefry |first=Gregory |title=Casual Game Design: Designing Play for the Gamer in All of Us |publisher=CRC Press |year=2010 |pages=179-185 |isbn=0123749530 |url=https://www.crcpress.com/Casual-Game-Design-Designing-Play-for-the-Gamer-in-ALL-of-Us/Trefry/p/book/9780123749536}}\n\n===Instruction manuals===\n* {{Cite book |title=Tetris (Game Boy) Instruction Booklet |publisher=[[Nintendo]] |year=1989 |url=http://www.superluigibros.com/downloads/manuals/gameboy/Tetris_-_Manual_-_GB.pdf}}\n* {{Cite book |title=Tetris 2 Instruction Booklet |publisher=[[Nintendo]] |year=1993 |url=http://www.nesfiles.com/NES/Tetris_2/Tetris_2.pdf}}\n* {{Cite book |title=Tetris DS Instruction booklet |publisher=[[Nintendo]] |year=2006 |url=http://www.nintendo.com/consumer/gameslist/manuals/DS_Tetris_DS.pdf}}\n\n===Video documentaries===\n* {{IMDb title|0409371|Tetris: From Russia with Love}}. Magnus Temple. 2004.\n* {{IMDb title|1836974|Ecstasy of Order: The Tetris Masters}}. Adam Cornelius. 2011.\n\n== External links ==\n{{Sister project links|collapsible=collapsed}}\n* {{Official website|https://tetris.com}}\n* {{IAg|tetris_1987|Tetris|MS-DOS}}\n\n{{Template group\n|title = Articles related to the game of ''Tetris''\n|titlestyle = background:#e8ddff\n|list  =\n{{Tetris|state=expanded}}\n{{Polyforms|state=expanded}}\n}}\n\n[[Category:Tetris| ]]\n[[Category:1984 in the Soviet Union]]\n[[Category:1984 video games]]\n[[Category:Alexey Pajitnov games]]\n[[Category:DOS games]]\n[[Category:Falling block puzzle games]]\n[[Category:NP-complete problems]]\n[[Category:Russian inventions]]\n[[Category:Soviet brands]]\n[[Category:Soviet games]]\n[[Category:Soviet inventions]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in Russia]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the 1984 video game}}\n{{short description|tile-matching puzzle video game}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2019}}\n{{Infobox video game\n| title = Tetris\n| image = \n| caption = \n| developer = AcademySoft\n| publisher = AcademySoft\n| designer = [[Alexey Pajitnov]]\n| platforms = [[List of Tetris variants|List of ''Tetris'' variants]]\n| released = '''Electronika 60'''{{Video game release|[[Soviet Union|USSR]]|1984}}'''MS-DOS''' & '''IBM PC'''{{Video game release|USSR|1986}}\n| genre = [[Puzzle video game|Puzzle]], [[Tile-matching video game|Tile-matching]]\n| modes = [[Single-player]], [[multiplayer]]\n}}\n\n'''''Tetris''''' ({{lang-ru|link=no|\u0422\u0435\u0442\u0440\u0438\u0441}} {{IPA-ru|\u02c8t\u025btr\u02b2\u026as|}} is a [[Tile-matching video game|tile-matching]] [[puzzle video game]] originally designed and programmed by Soviet Russian software engineer [[Alexey Pajitnov]] in 1984 for the [[Electronika 60]]. The game has been published by several companies over time, most prominently during a war for the appropriation of the game's rights in the late 1980s. After a significant period of publication by [[Nintendo]], the rights of the game reverted to Pajitnov in 1996, who co-founded [[The Tetris Company]] with [[Henk Rogers]] to manage licensing for ''Tetris''.\n\n''Tetris'' challenges the player to create complete lines by moving differently-shaped pieces \u2013 the [[tetromino]]es, which scroll from the top to bottom of the playing field. The completed lines disappear and grant the player points, and the player can proceed to fill the vacated spaces. The game ends when the playing field is filled to the point that additional pieces can no longer descend. The longer the player can delay this inevitable outcome, the higher their score will be. In multiplayer games, the players must last longer than their opponents, and in certain versions, players can inflict penalties on opponents by completing a significant number of lines. Some adaptations have provided variations to the game's theme, such as three-dimensional displays or a system for reserving pieces.\n\nBuilt on simple rules and requiring intelligence and skill, ''Tetris'' has established itself as [[List of video games considered the best|one of the great classic video game titles]] alongside ''[[Pong]]'', ''[[Space Invaders]]'' and ''[[Pac-Man]]''. Since its creation, ''Tetris'' has sold 202{{nbsp}}million copies \u2013 approximately 70{{nbsp}}million physical units and 132{{nbsp}}million paid [[mobile game]] downloads \u2013 as of December 2011, making it one of the [[List of best-selling video game franchises|best-selling video game franchises of all time]]; the [[Game Boy]] version in particular is [[List of best-selling video games|one of the best-selling single titles of all time]], with over 35 million copies sold. The game is available on [[List of Tetris variants|over 65 platforms]], setting a [[Guinness World Records|''Guinness'' world record]] for the most ported video game title. ''Tetris'' is rooted within popular culture and its notoriety extends beyond the sphere of video games; imagery from the game has influenced architecture, music and cosplay. The game has also been the subject of various research studies that have analyzed its theoretical complexity and have shown its effect on the human brain following a session, in particular the [[Tetris effect]].\n\n==Gameplay==\n[[File:Tetris basic game.gif|thumb|Video of an open-source ''Tetris'' [[Clone (video game)|clone]]]]\n''Tetris'' is primarily composed of a field of play in which pieces of different geometric forms, called \"[[Tetromino|tetriminos]]\", descend from the top of the field.{{sfn|Kent|2001|p=377}} During this descent, the player can move the pieces laterally and rotate them until they touch the bottom of the field or land on a piece that had been placed before it.<ref name=\"AboutTetris\">{{cite web |url=https://tetris.com/about-us |title=About ''Tetris'' |publisher=The Tetris Company |accessdate=November 14, 2019}}</ref> The player can neither slow down the falling pieces nor stop them, but can accelerate them in most versions.<ref>''Tetris'' (Game Boy) instruction booklet, p. 4</ref><ref>''Tetris DS'' instruction booklet, p. 6</ref> The objective of the game is to use the pieces to create as many horizontal lines of blocks as possible. When a line is completed, it disappears, and the blocks placed above fall one rank.<ref name=\"AboutTetris\"/> Completing lines grants points, and accumulating a certain number of points moves the player up a level, which increases the number of points granted per completed line.<ref name=\"GameBoy16\">''Tetris'' (Game Boy) instruction booklet, p. 16</ref> In most versions, the speed of the falling pieces increases with each level, leaving the player with less time to think about the placement.<ref name=\"AboutTetris\"/> The player can clear multiple lines at once, which can earn bonus points in some versions.{{sfn|Kent|2001|p=377}} It is possible to complete up to four lines simultaneously with the use of the I-shaped tetrimino; this move is called a \"Tetris\", and is the basis of the game's title.<ref name=\"GameBoy16\"/> If the player cannot make the blocks disappear quickly enough, the field will start to fill, and when the pieces reach the top of the field and prevent the arrival of additional pieces, the game ends.<ref name=\"AboutTetris\"/> At the end of each game, the player receives a score based on the number of lines that have been completed.<ref name=\"GameBoy16\"/> The game never ends with the player's victory; the player can only complete as many lines as possible before an inevitable loss.{{sfn|Kent|2001|p=377}} \n\nSince 1996, The Tetris Company has internally defined specifications and guidelines that publishers must adhere to in order to be granted a license to ''Tetris''. The contents of these guidelines establish such elements as the correspondence of buttons and actions, the size of the field of play, the system of rotation, and others.<ref name=\"HistoryOfTetris\">{{cite web |url=https://tetris.com/history-of-tetris |title=History of ''Tetris'' |publisher=The Tetris Company |accessdate=November 18, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"tftt\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nintendoworldreport.com/interview/11267/tetris-from-the-top-an-interview-with-henk-rogers |title=''Tetris'' from the Top: An Interview with Henk Rogers |author=Metts, Jonathan |website=Nintendo World Report |date=April 6, 2006 |accessdate=April 28, 2007}}</ref>\n\n===Game pieces===\n[[File:Tetrominoes IJLO STZ Worlds.svg|thumb|left|All seven tetriminos using the standard color scheme]]\nThe pieces on which the game of ''Tetris'' is based around are called \"tetriminos\". Pajitnov's original version for the [[Electronika 60]] computer used green brackets to represent the blocks that make up tetriminos.<ref name=\"vadim\"/> Versions of ''Tetris'' on the original Game Boy/Game Boy Color and on most dedicated handheld games use [[monochrome]] or grayscale graphics, but most popular versions use a separate color for each distinct shape. Prior to The Tetris Company's standardization in the early 2000s, those colors varied widely from implementation to implementation.\n\n===Scoring===\nThe scoring formula for the majority of ''Tetris'' products is built on the idea that more difficult line clears should be awarded more points. For example, a single line clear in ''Tetris Zone'' is worth 100 points, clearing four lines at once (known as a ''Tetris'') is worth 800, while each subsequent back-to-back ''Tetris'' is worth 1,200.<ref name=\"tzmanual\">[http://zone.tetris.com/page/manual ''Tetris Zone'' manual] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090206023148/http://zone.tetris.com/page/manual |date=February 6, 2009 }} as of November 12, 2008</ref> In conjunction, players can be awarded combos that exist in certain games which reward multiple line clears in quick succession. The exact conditions for triggering combos, and the amount of importance assigned to them, vary from game to game.{{citation needed|date=August 2018}}\n\nNearly all ''Tetris'' games allow the player to press a button to increase the speed of the current piece's descent or cause the piece to drop and lock into place immediately, known as a \"soft drop\" and a \"hard drop\", respectively. While performing a soft drop, the player can also stop the piece's increased speed by releasing the button before the piece settles into place. Some games only allow either soft drop or hard drop; others have separate buttons for both. Many games award a number of points based on the height that the piece fell before locking, so using the hard drop generally awards more points.\n\n===Debate on the possibility of an infinite game===\nThe question ''Would it be possible to play forever?'' was first considered in a thesis by John Brzustowski in 1992.<ref>John Brzustowski. [https://circle.ubc.ca/bitstream/handle/2429/3263/ubc_1992_spring_brzustowski_john.pdf?sequence=1] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131016151137/https://circle.ubc.ca/bitstream/handle/2429/3263/ubc_1992_spring_brzustowski_john.pdf?sequence=1 |date=October 16, 2013 }}. Retrieved October 16, 2013.</ref> The conclusion reached was that the game is statistically doomed to end. The reason has to do with the S and Z Tetriminos. If a player receives a sufficiently large sequence of alternating S and Z Tetriminos, the na\u00efve gravity used by the standard game eventually forces the player to leave holes on the board. The holes will necessarily stack to the top and, ultimately, end the game. If the pieces are distributed randomly, this sequence will eventually occur. Thus, if a game with, for example, an ideal, uniform, uncorrelated [[Random number generation|random number generator]] is played long enough, any player will top out.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20061209110731/http://www.math.uic.edu/~burgiel/Tetris/explanation.html Dr. Burgiel's Tetris Research Page, Explanation]. Retrieved February 25, 2007.</ref><ref>Heidi Burgiel. [http://www.geom.umn.edu/%7Eburgiel/Tetris/tetris.PS How to Lose at Tetris] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030513033006/http://www.geom.umn.edu/~burgiel/Tetris/tetris.PS |date=May 13, 2003 }}, Mathematical Gazette, vol. 81, pp. 194\u2013200 1997</ref>\n\nIn practice, this does not occur in most ''Tetris'' variants. Some [[List of Tetris variants|variants]] allow the player to choose to play with only S and Z Tetriminos, and a good player may survive well over 150 consecutive Tetriminos this way. On an implementation with an ideal uniform randomizer, the probability at any given time of the next 150 Tetriminos being only S and Z is ({{sfrac|2|7}})<sup>150</sup> (approximately {{val|2e-82}}). Most implementations use a [[pseudorandom number generator]] to generate the sequence of Tetriminos, and such an S\u2013Z sequence is almost certainly not contained in the sequence produced by the 32-bit [[linear congruential generator]] in many implementations (which has roughly {{val|4.2e9}} states). The \"evil\" algorithm in ''Bastet'' (an unofficial variant) often starts a game with a series of more than seven Z pieces.\n\nModern versions of ''Tetris'' released after 2001 use a bag-style randomizer that guarantees players will never receive more than four S or Z pieces in a row. This is one of the \"Indispensable Rules\" enforced by the ''Tetris Guideline'' that all officially licensed ''Tetris'' games must follow.<ref name=\"tftt\"/>\n\nRecent versions of ''Tetris'' such as ''Tetris Worlds'' allow the player to repeatedly rotate a block once it hits the bottom of the playfield without it locking into place. This permits a player to play for an infinite amount of time, though not necessarily to land an infinite number of blocks.\n\n=== Easy spin dispute ===\nAlthough not the first ''Tetris'' game to feature a new kind of ''Tetris'', \"easy spin\" (see ''[[The Next Tetris]]''), also called \"infinite spin\" by critics,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gamespot.com/gba/puzzle/tetrisworlds/review.html |title=Tetris Worlds for Game Boy Advance Review |publisher=Gamespot.com |date=September 5, 2001 |accessdate=November 22, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111028130427/http://www.gamespot.com/gba/puzzle/tetrisworlds/review.html |archive-date=October 28, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> ''[[Tetris Worlds]]'' was the first game to fall under major criticisms for it. Easy spin refers to the property of a Tetromino to stop falling for a moment after left or right movement or rotation, effectively allowing someone to suspend the Tetromino while thinking on where to place it. This feature has been implemented into [[The Tetris Company]]'s official guideline.<ref name=\"tftt\"/> This type of play differs from traditional ''Tetris'' because it takes away the pressure of higher level speed. Some reviewers<ref name=\"gsrev\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/ps2/puzzle/tetrisworlds/review.html|title=Tetris Worlds for PlayStation 2 Review|accessdate=November 12, 2008|website=[[GameSpot]]|date=April 19, 2002|author1=Jeff Gerstmann|author2=Ryan Davis|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090130070533/http://www.gamespot.com/ps2/puzzle/tetrisworlds/review.html|archive-date=January 30, 2009|url-status=live}}</ref> went so far as to say that this mechanism broke the game. The goal in ''Tetris Worlds'', however, is to complete a certain number of lines as fast as possible, so the ability to hold off a piece's placement will not make achieving that goal any faster. Later, GameSpot received \"easy spin\" more openly, saying that \"the infinite spin issue honestly really affects only a few of the single-player gameplay modes in ''Tetris DS'', because any competitive mode requires you to lay down pieces as quickly as humanly possible.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/ds/puzzle/tetris/review.html |title=Tetris DS for DS Review \u2013 GameSpot |publisher=Gamespot.com |date=March 20, 2006 |accessdate=November 22, 2012 |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110805040528/http://www.gamespot.com/ds/puzzle/tetris/review.html |archivedate=August 5, 2011 |df= }}</ref> In response to the issue, [[Henk Rogers]] stated in an interview that infinite spin was an intentional part of the game design, allowing novice players to expend some of their available scoring time to decide on the best placement of a piece. Rogers observed that \"gratuitous spinning\" does not occur in competitive play, as expert players do not require much time to think about where a piece should be placed. A limitation has been placed on infinite lock delay in later games of the franchise, where after a certain amount of inputs i.e.: rotations and movements, the piece will instantly lock itself. This is defaulted to 15 inputs.<ref name=\"tftt\"/>\n\n==History==\n{{multiple image\n | align = right\n | direction = vertical\n | width    = 250\n | image1   = Tetris-VeryFirstVersion.png\n | caption1 = The first version of ''Tetris'', completed in 1984, run on an emulator of the [[Electronika 60]]\n | image2   = Tetris DOS 1986.png\n | caption2 = Screenshot of the 1986 IBM PC version developed by Dmitry Pavlovsky and [[Vadim Gerasimov]]\n | image3   = Tetris screenshot (Amiga, Infogrames).png\n | caption3 = The version designed by Spectrum Holobyte contained Russia-related images (Amiga version screenshot, 1988)\n}}\n\n===Conception===\nIn 1979, [[Alexey Pajitnov]] joined the Computer Center of the [[Russian Academy of Sciences|Soviet Academy of Sciences]] as a [[speech recognition]] researcher. While he was tasked with testing the capabilities of new hardware, his ambition was to use computers to make people happy.{{sfn|Ichbiah|1997|p=85}} Pajitnov developed several puzzle games on the institute's computer, an [[Electronika 60]], a scarce resource at the time.{{sfn|Sheff|1999|p=298}} For Pajitnov, \"The games allow people to get to know each other better and act as revealers of things you might not normally notice, such as their way of thinking.\"{{sfn|Ichbiah|1997|p=85}} In 1984, while trying to recreate a favorite puzzle game from his childhood featuring [[pentomino]]es,<ref name=\"guardian2014\">{{cite news |last=Hoad |first=Phil |url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2014/jun/02/how-we-made-tetris |title=Tetris: how we made the addictive computer game &#124; Culture |newspaper=The Guardian |date=June 2, 2014 |accessdate=July 5, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170621140034/https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2014/jun/02/how-we-made-tetris |archive-date=June 21, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>{{sfn|Loguidice|Barton|2009|p=293}} Pajitnov imagined a game consisting of a descent of random pieces that the player would have to turn in order to fill in rows.{{sfn|Ichbiah|1997|p=85}} Pajitnov felt that the game would be needlessly complicated with twelve different shape variations, so he scaled the concept down to [[tetromino]]es, of which there are seven variants.<ref name=\"guardian2014\"/> Pajitnov titled the game ''Tetris'', a word created from a combination of \"tetromino\" and \"tennis\", the latter being Pajitnov's favorite sport.{{sfn|Loguidice|Barton|2009|p=293}} Because the Electronika 60 that Pajitnov used to create the prototype for ''Tetris'' had no graphical interface, Pajitnov modelled the field and pieces using spaces and brackets.{{sfn|Sheff|1999|p=299}} Realizing that completed lines resulted in the screen filling up quickly, Pajitnov decided to delete them, creating a key part of ''Tetris'' gameplay.<ref name=\"guardian2014\"/> This early version of ''Tetris'' had no scoring system and no levels, but its addictive quality caused it to stand out amongst the puzzle games that Pajitnov had created.<ref name=guardian020609>{{cite web |last=Johnson |first=Bobbie |website=[[The Guardian]] |date=June 1, 2009 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/gamesblog/2009/jun/02/tetris-25anniversary-alexey-pajitnov |title=How ''Tetris'' conquered the world, block by block |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150329135242/http://www.theguardian.com/technology/gamesblog/2009/jun/02/tetris-25anniversary-alexey-pajitnov |archive-date=March 29, 2015}}</ref>\n\nPajitnov, delighted by his game, presented ''Tetris'' to his colleagues, who quickly became addicted to it.{{sfn|Ichbiah|1997|p=87}} The game permeated all the offices within the Academy of Sciences, and within a few weeks it reached every Moscow institute with a computer.{{sfn|Ichbiah|1997|p=87}}{{sfn|Temple|2004|loc=9 min.}} A friend of Pajitnov, Vladimir Pokhilko, who requested the game for the Moscow Medical Institute, saw people stop working to play ''Tetris'', and told Pajitnov that \"I can no longer live without your ''Tetris''\". Pokhilko eventually banned the game from the Medical Institute to restore productivity.{{sfn|Ichbiah|1997|p=87}} Faced with his success, Pajitnov sought to adapt ''Tetris'' to the [[IBM Personal Computer]], which had a higher quality display than the Electronika 60. Pajitnov recruited [[Vadim Gerasimov]], a 16-year-old high school student who was known for his computer skills and reputed to be a [[hacker]].{{sfn|Ichbiah|1997|p=87}}{{sfn|Sheff|1999|p=300}} Pajitnov had met Gerasimov before through a mutual acquaintance, and they worked together on previous games.<ref name=\"vadim\">{{cite web |url=https://vadim.oversigma.com/Tetris.htm |title= Original ''Tetris'': Story and Download |last=Gerasimov |first=Vadim |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060821183909/http://vadim.oversigma.com/Tetris.htm |archive-date=August 21, 2006 |accessdate=June 10, 2007}}</ref> Gerasimov adapted ''Tetris'' to the IBM PC over the course of a few weeks, incorporating color and a scoreboard.{{sfn|Sheff|1999|p=300}}\n\nPajitnov then wanted to export ''Tetris''. However, he had no knowledge of the business world, and his superiors in the Academy were not necessarily happy with the success of the game, since they had not intended such a creation from the research team.{{sfn|Ichbiah|1997|p=87}} Furthermore, [[intellectual property]] did not exist in the Soviet Union, and Soviet researchers were not allowed to sell their creations.{{sfn|Sheff|1999|p=301}}{{sfn|Temple|2004|loc=10 min.}} Pajitnov asked his supervisor Victor Brjabrin, who had knowledge of the world outside the Soviet Union, to help him publish ''Tetris''. Pajitnov offered to transfer the rights of the game to the Academy, and was delighted to receive a non-compulsory remuneration from Brjabrin through this deal.{{sfn|Ichbiah|1997|p=88}}\n\n===Acquisition of rights by Mirrorsoft and Spectrum HoloByte===\nIn 1986, Brjabrin sent a copy of ''Tetris'' to [[Hungary|Hungarian]] game publisher [[Appaloosa Interactive|Novotrade]].{{sfn|Ichbiah|1997|p=88}} From there, clones of the game began circulating via [[floppy disk]]s throughout Hungary and as far as [[Poland]].{{sfn|Ichbiah|1997|p=89}} Robert Stein, an international software salesman for the London-based firm Andromeda Software, saw the game's commercial potential during a visit to Hungary in June 1986.{{sfn|Sheff|1999|p=302}}{{sfn|Temple|2004|loc=11 min.}} After an indifferent response from the Academy,{{sfn|Temple|2004|loc=12 min.}} Stein contacted Pajitnov and Brjabrin by fax in order to obtain the rights to the license.{{sfn|Temple|2004|loc=11 min.}} The researchers expressed interest in forming an agreement with Stein.{{sfn|Temple|2004|loc=12 min.}} However, they were unaware that a fax machine had legal value in the Western world, and Stein began to approach other companies to produce the game.{{sfn|Ichbiah|1997|pp=89\u201390}} Pajitnov was never able to digest this misunderstanding; in an interview with the website Kikizo, he declared \"I don\u2019t really like to talk about that because when I think about those things I lose my sense of humor.\"{{sfn|Kent|2001|p=294}}\n\nStein thus took advantage of the 1987 [[Consumer Electronics Show]] in [[Las Vegas]] to approach several publishers. Gary Carlston, co-founder of [[Broderbund]], retrieved a copy and brought it to [[California]]. Despite enthusiasm amongst its employees, Broderbund remained skeptical because of the game's Soviet origins. Likewise, [[Mastertronic]] co-founder Martin Alper declared that \"No Soviet product will ever work in the Western world.\"{{sfn|Ichbiah|1997|p=90}} Stein ultimately signed two agreements: he sold the European rights to the publisher [[Mirrorsoft]],{{sfn|Kent|2001|p=479}}{{sfn|Ichbiah|1997|p=90}} and the American rights to [[Spectrum HoloByte]].{{sfn|Kent|2001|p=479}}{{sfn|Kent|2001|p=294}} The latter obtained the rights after a visit by Mirrorsoft president Phil Adams in which he played ''Tetris'' for two hours.{{sfn|Ichbiah|1997|p=90}}{{sfn|Temple|2004|loc=15 min.}} At that time, Stein had not yet signed a contract with the Soviet Union.{{sfn|Kent|2001|p=479}} Nevertheless, he sold the rights to the two companies for \u00a33,000 and a royalty of 7.5 to 15% on sales.{{sfn|Sheff|1999|p=304}}\n\nBefore releasing ''Tetris'' in the United States, Spectrum HoloByte CEO Gilman Louie asked for an overhaul of the game's graphics and music.{{sfn|Ichbiah|1997|p=90}} The Soviet spirit was preserved, with fields illustrating Russian parks and buildings as well as melodies anchored in Russian folklore of the time. The company's goal was to make people want to buy a Russian product; the game came complete with a red package and Cyrillic text, an unusual approach on the other side of the [[Berlin Wall]].{{sfn|Temple|2004|loc=16 min.}} The Mirrorsoft version was released for the IBM PC in November 1987,{{sfn|Ichbiah|1997|p=91}} while the Spectrum HoloByte version was released for the same platform in January 1988.{{sfn|Kent|2001|p=294}}{{sfn|Ichbiah|1997|p=91}} The game was subsequently ported to other platforms, most notably the [[Amiga]], [[Atari ST]], [[ZX Spectrum]], [[Commodore 64]] and [[Amstrad CPC]]. At the time, the game made no mention of Pajitnov and came with the announcement of \"Made in the United States of America, designed abroad\". ''Tetris'' was a commercial success in Europe and the United States: Mirrorsoft sold tens of thousands of copies in two months.{{sfn|Ichbiah|1997|p=91}} The game sold 100,000 units in the space of a year.{{sfn|Temple|2004|loc=18 min.}} According to Spectrum HoloByte, the average profile of a ''Tetris'' player was an adult between 25\u201345 years of age who was a manager or an engineer. At the [[Software and Information Industry Association|Software Publishers Association]] \"Excellence in Software Awards\" ceremony in March 1988, ''Tetris'' obtained four awards: Best Entertainment Software, Best Original Game, Best Strategy Program, and Best Consumer Software.{{sfn|Ichbiah|1997|p=91}}\n\nStein, however, was faced with a problem: the only document certifying a license fee was the fax from Pajitnov and Brjabrin, meaning that Stein sold the license for a game he did not yet own. Stein contacted Pajitnov and asked him for a contract for the rights. Stein began negotiations via fax, offering 75% of the revenue generated by Stein from the license.{{sfn|Sheff|1999|p=304}} [[Elektronorgtechnica]] (\"Elorg\"), the Soviet Union's central organization for the import and export of computer software, was unconvinced by this offer and requested 80% of the revenue. Stein made several trips to Moscow and held long discussions with Elorg representatives.{{sfn|Sheff|1999|p=305}} On February 24, 1988,{{sfn|Sheff|1999|p=308}} Stein obtained an agreement with Elorg, which he signed on May 10, 1988,{{sfn|Temple|2004|loc=22 min.}} for a ten-year worldwide ''Tetris'' license for all current and future computer systems.{{sfn|Ichbiah|1997|p=92}} Pajitnov and Brjabrin were unaware that the game was already on sale and that Stein had claimed to own the rights prior to the agreement.{{sfn|Kent|2001|p=479}} Although Pajitnov would not receive any percentage from these sales,{{sfn|Ichbiah|1997|p=92}} he decided that \"The fact that so many people enjoy my game is enough for me.\"{{sfn|Ichbiah|1997|p=96}}\n\n===Acquisition of rights by Nintendo and legal battle===\nThe situation grew more complex in 1988. Spectrum HoloByte sold the Japanese rights to its computer games and arcade machines to [[Henk Rogers]], who was searching for games for the Japanese market.{{sfn|Temple|2004|loc=22 min.}} Mirrorsoft sold its own Japanese rights to [[Atari Games]] subsidiary [[Tengen (company)|Tengen]]; the latter would then sell the arcade rights to [[Sega]] and the console rights to Rogers. At this point, almost a dozen companies believed they held the rights to the game, with Stein retaining rights for home computer versions.{{sfn|Loguidice|Barton|2009|p=480}} Elorg was still unaware of the deals Stein had negotiated, which did not bring money to them. Nevertheless, ''Tetris'' was a commercial success in North America, Eurpoe and Asia.{{sfn|Temple|2004|loc=22 min.}}\n\nThe same year, [[Nintendo]] was preparing to launch its first portable console, the [[Game Boy]]. Nintendo was attracted to ''Tetris'' by its simplicity and established success on the [[Nintendo Entertainment System|NES]].{{sfn|Ichbiah|1997|p=92}}{{sfn|Loguidice|Barton|2009|p=480}} Rogers, who was close to Nintendo president [[Hiroshi Yamauchi]], then sought to recover the handheld rights.{{sfn|Ichbiah|1997|p=92}} After a failed negotiation with Atari Games,{{sfn|Ichbiah|1997|p=93}} Rogers contacted Stein in November 1988. Stein agreed to sign a contract, but explained that he had to consult Elorg before returning to negotiations with Rogers.{{sfn|Temple|2004|loc=24 min.}}{{sfn|Sheff|1999|p=313}} After contacting Stein several times, Rogers began to suspect a breach of contract on Stein's part, and decided on February 1989 to go to the Soviet Union and negotiate the rights with Elorg.{{sfn|Ichbiah|1997|p=93}}{{sfn|Sheff|1999|p=313}}\n\nRogers arrived at the Elorg offices uninvited, while Stein and Mirrorsoft manager [[Kevin Maxwell]] made an appointment the same day without consulting each other.{{sfn|Temple|2004|loc=29 min.}} During the discussions, Rogers explained that he wished to obtain the rights to ''Tetris'' for the new Game Boy console, following the success of the game on the NES.{{sfn|Ichbiah|1997|p=95}} After quickly obtaining an agreement with Elorg president Nikolai Belikov,{{sfn|Sheff|1999|p=316}} Rogers showed Belikov a cartridge of the game.{{sfn|Ichbiah|1997|p=94}} Belikov was surprised, as he believed at the time that the rights to ''Tetris'' were only signed for computers systems.{{sfn|Temple|2004|loc=31 min.}} The present parties accused Nintendo of illegal publication, but Rogers defended himself by explaining that he had obtained the rights via Atari Games, which had itself signed an agreement with Stein.{{sfn|Ichbiah|1997|p=94}} Belikov then realized the complex path that the license had followed within four years because of Stein's contracts, and he constructed a strategy to regain possession of the rights and obtain more favorable commercial aggreements. At that point, Elorg was faced with three different companies who wished to buy the rights.{{sfn|Temple|2004|loc=35 min.}}\n\nDuring this time, Rogers befriended Pajitnov over a [[Go (game)|game of Go]], and Pajitnov would support Rogers throughout the discussions, to the detriment of Maxwell, who came to secure the ''Tetris'' rights for Mirrorsoft.{{sfn|Ichbiah|1997|p=93}} Belikov proposed to Rogers that Stein's rights would be cancelled and Nintendo would be granted the game rights for both home and handheld consoles.{{sfn|Ichbiah|1997|p=94}} Rogers then flew to the United States to convince Nintendo's American branch to sign up for the rights. The contract with Elorg was signed by [[Minoru Arakawa]] and [[Howard Lincoln]] for $500,000, plus 50 cents per cartridge sold.{{sfn|Ichbiah|1997|p=95}}{{sfn|Temple|2004|loc=42 min.}} Elorg then sent an updated contract to Stein. One of the contract's clauses defined a computer as a machine with a screen and keyboard, and thus Stein's rights to console versions were withdrawn.{{sfn|Temple|2004|loc=37 min.}} Stein signed the contract without paying attention to this clause,{{sfn|Ichbiah|1997|p=95}} and he later realized that all the contract's other clauses, notably on payments, were only a \"smokescreen\" to deceive him.{{sfn|Temple|2004|loc=37 min.}}{{sfn|Sheff|1999|p=319}}\n\nIn March 1989, Nintendo sent a [[cease and desist]] fax to Atari Games concerning production of the NES version of ''Tetris''.{{sfn|Temple|2004|loc=47 min.}} Atari Games contacted Mirrorsoft, and were assured that they still retained the rights. Nintendo, however, maintained its position. In response, Mirrorsoft owner [[Robert Maxwell]] pressured Soviet Union leader [[Mikhail Gorbachev]] to cancel the contract between Elorg and Nintendo.{{sfn|Ichbiah|1997|p=95}} Despite the threats to Belikov, Elorg refused to give in and highlighted the financial advantages of their contract compared to those signed with Stein and Mirrorsoft.{{sfn|Ichbiah|1997|p=95}}{{sfn|Temple|2004|loc=45 min.}} On November 1989, Nintendo and Atari Games began a legal battle in the courts of [[San Francisco]]. Atari Games sought to prove that the NES was a computer, as indicated by its Japanese name \"Famicom\", an abbrieviation of \"Family Computer\". In this case, the initial license would then authorize Atari Games to release the game. The central argument of Atari Games was that the Famicom was designed to be convertible into a computer via its extension port. This argument was not accepted, and Pajitnov stressed that the initial contract only concerned computers and no other machine.{{sfn|Ichbiah|1997|p=96}} For its part, Nintendo brought Belikov to testify on its behalf.{{sfn|Temple|2004|loc=48 min.}} Judge Fern Smith then declared that Mirrorsoft and Spectrum HoloByte never received explicit authorization for marketing on consoles, and ruled in Nintendo's favor.{{sfn|Ichbiah|1997|p=96}} On June 21, 1989, Atari Games withdrew its NES version from sale, and thousands of cartridges remained unsold in the company's warehouses.<ref>{{cite magazine |title=From Russia with Litigation |magazine=[[Next Generation (magazine)|Next Generation]] |issue=26 |publisher=[[Imagine Media]] |date=February 1997 |page=42}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |year=2002 |title=The Wish List |journal=Edge Presents Retro}}</ref>\n\nSega had planned to release a [[Sega Genesis|Mega Drive]] version of ''Tetris'' on April 15, 1989, but they cancelled its release<ref>{{cite web|url=https://onitama.tv/gamemachine/pdf/19890501p.pdf#page=14|title=Game Machine: \"Nintendo Offers Home Video Game 'Tetris'\"|publisher=Amusement Press|date=1989-05-01}}</ref> during Atari's licensing issues, resulting in fewer than ten copies being printed.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://kotaku.com/you-could-own-this-copy-of-tetris-for-only-1-000-000-5822380 |title=You Could Own This Copy of Tetris for Only $1,000,000 |first=Michael |last=McWhertor |work=Kotaku |date=July 18, 2011 | access-date=June 4, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190604193847/https://kotaku.com/you-could-own-this-copy-of-tetris-for-only-1-000-000-5822380 |archive-date=June 4, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> A new port of the arcade version by M2 was included in the [[Sega Genesis Mini]] microconsole, released in September 2019.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.gameinformer.com/2019/06/04/final-12-genesis-mini-games-list-includes-one-of-the-worlds-rarest-versions-of-tetris |title=Archived copy |access-date=June 4, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190604221811/https://www.gameinformer.com/2019/06/04/final-12-genesis-mini-games-list-includes-one-of-the-worlds-rarest-versions-of-tetris |archive-date=June 4, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Commercial success and acquisition of rights by Pajitnov===\n{{Main|The Tetris Company}}\n[[File:Tetris NES play.png|thumb|right|250px|A-Type game screenshot of the official [[Nintendo Entertainment System|NES]] version of ''Tetris'']]\nThrough the legal history of the license, Pajitnov gained a reputation in the West. He was regularly invited by journalists and publishers, through which he discovered that his game had sold millions of copies, from which he had not made any money. However, he remained humble and proud of the game, which he considered \"an electronic ambassador of benevolence\".{{sfn|Ichbiah|1997|p=96}} In January 1990, he was invited by Spectrum HoloByte to the Consumer Electronics Show, and was immersed in American life for the first time.{{sfn|Ichbiah|1997|p=97}} After a period of adaptation, he explored American culture in several cities, including Las Vegas, San Francisco, [[New York City]] and [[Boston]], and engaged in interviews with several hosts, including the directors of Nintendo of America.{{sfn|Sheff|1999|p=347}} He marveled at the freedom and the advantages of Western society. Upon returning to the Soviet Union, he would never stop talking to his colleagues about his travels. He then realized that there was no market in Russia for their programs.{{sfn|Ichbiah|1997|p=97}} At the same time, Nintendo saw sales of the Game Boy \u2013 bundled with a handheld version of ''Tetris'' \u2013 explode, exceeding sales forecasts three times.{{sfn|Ichbiah|1997|p=97}}\n\nIn 1991, Pajitnov and Pokhilko emigrated to the United States.{{sfn|Ichbiah|1997|p=97}} Pajitnov moved to [[Seattle]], where he produced games for Spectrum HoloByte. In April 1996, as agreed with the Academy ten years earlier and following an agreement with Rogers, the rights to ''Tetris'' reverted to Pajitnov.<ref name=\"HenkRogersStory\">{{cite web |url=https://www.sramanamitra.com/2009/09/20/the-story-of-tetris-henk-rogers-part-5/ |title=The Story of ''Tetris'': Henk Rogers (Part 5) |website=Sramana Mitra |date=September 20, 2009 |accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref> Pajitnov and Rogers founded [[The Tetris Company]] in June 1996 to manage the game's rights on all platforms, the previous agreements having expired. Pajitnov now receives a royalty for each ''Tetris'' game and derivative sold worldwide.{{sfn|Ichbiah|1997|p=100}} In 2002, Pajitnov and Rogers founded Tetris Holding after the purchase of the game's remaining rights from Elorg, now a private entity following the [[dissolution of the Soviet Union]]. The Tetris Company now owns all rights to the ''Tetris'' brand, and is mainly responsible for removing illegal clones from the market;<ref name=\"HenkRogersStory\"/>{{sfn|Ichbiah|1997|p=100}} the company regularly calls on [[Apple Inc.]] and [[Google]] to remove illegal versions of ''Tetris'' from their mobile [[app store]]s.<ref name=\"iphonePurge\">{{cite web |url=https://arstechnica.com/gadgets/2008/10/tetris-co-strikes-again-another-iphone-app-clone-is-pulled/ |title=Tetris Co. strikes again: another iPhone app clone is pulled |website=Ars Technica |last=Chartier |first=David |date=October 8, 2008 |accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"androidPurge\">{{cite web |url=https://arstechnica.com/gadgets/2010/06/google-blocks-tetris-clones-from-android-market/ |title=Google blocks Tetris clones from Android market |website=Ars Technica |last=Ryan |first=Paul |date=June 2, 2010 |accessdate=June 23, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121202210616/http://arstechnica.com/gadgets/2010/06/google-blocks-tetris-clones-from-android-market/ |archive-date=December 2, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> In December 2005, [[Electronic Arts]] acquired Jamdat, a company specializing in mobile games.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20051208005771/en/EA-Acquire-JAMDAT-Mobile----Leader-North |title=EA to Acquire JAMDAT Mobile Inc. -- the Leader in North American Mobile Interactive Entertainment; Accelerates EA's Objective of Global Expansion in Mobile |website=Business Wire |date=December 8, 2005 |accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref> Jamdat had previously bought a company founded by Rogers in 2001, which managed the ''Tetris'' license on mobile platforms. As a result, Electronic Arts holds a 15-year license on all mobile phone releases of ''Tetris''.<ref name=\"HenkRogersStory\"/>\n\n==Versions==\n{{Main|List of Tetris variants}}\n[[File:Tetris on an iPod.jpg|250px|thumb|A [[iPod classic|5th generation]] [[iPod]] running ''Tetris'' (2006)]]\n''Tetris'' has been released on a multitude of platforms since the creation of the original version on the [[Electronika 60]]. The game is available on most game consoles and is playable on personal computers, smartphones and [[iPod]]s. ''[[Guinness World Records]]'' has recognized the game as being the most ported in the history of video gaming, having appeared on over 65 different platforms as of October 2010.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/records-3000/most-ported-computer-game/ |title=Most ported computer game |publisher=Guinnessworldrecords.com |date=October 1, 2010 |accessdate=June 7, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131202223258/http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/records-3000/most-ported-computer-game/ |archive-date=December 2, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> Since the 2000s, Internet versions of the game have also been developed. However, commercial versions not approved by The Tetris Company tend to be purged due to company policy.<ref name=\"iphonePurge\"/><ref name=\"androidPurge\"/> The most famous online version, ''[[Tetris Friends]]'' by [[Tetris Online, Inc.]], had attracted over a million registered users.<ref name=\"TetrisFriendsMillion\">{{cite web |url=http://www.marketwired.com/press-release/Tetris-Friends-Online-Games-Hits-1-Million-Milestone-Launches-Tetris-Arena-1167945.htm |title=''Tetris\u00ae Friends'' Online Games Hits 1 Million Milestone, Launches ''Tetris Arena'' |last=Musselman |first=Katie |date=April 13, 2010 |website=Marketwire |archiveurl=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.marketwired.com%2Fpress-release%2FTetris-Friends-Online-Games-Hits-1-Million-Milestone-Launches-Tetris-Arena-1167945.htm |archivedate=February 4, 2015}}</ref> Tetris Online had also developed versions for console-based digital download services.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tetrisonline.com/games/tetris_party_dsi.php |title=''Tetris\u00ae Party Live'' |website=Tetris Online |archiveurl=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.tetrisonline.com%2Fgames%2Ftetris_party_dsi.php |archivedate=June 9, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tetrisonline.com/games/tetris_splash_xbla.php |title=''Tetris\u00ae Splash'' |website=Tetris Online |archiveurl=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.tetrisonline.com%2Fgames%2Ftetris_splash_xbla.php |archivedate=May 28, 2011}}</ref> Because of its popularity and simplicity of development, ''Tetris'' is often used as a [[Hello world program|hello world]] project for programmers coding for a new system or programming language. This has resulted in the availability of a large number of [[Porting|ports]] for different platforms. For instance, [[\u03bcTorrent]] and [[Emacs|GNU Emacs]] contain similar shape-stacking games as easter eggs.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.eeggs.com/items/47291.html |title=uTorrent Easter Egg: Tetris in uTorrent |publisher=Eeggs.com |date=March 16, 2006 |accessdate=November 22, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121121044523/http://www.eeggs.com/items/47291.html |archive-date=November 21, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=poenn |url=http://hints.macworld.com/article.php?story=20050103201954271 |title=macosxhints.com \u2013 Play Tetris in Terminal via emacs |publisher=Hints.macworld.com |accessdate=November 22, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130522153944/http://hints.macworld.com/article.php?story=20050103201954271 |archive-date=May 22, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nWithin official franchise installments, each version has made improvements to accomodate advancing technology and the goal to provide a more complete game. Developers are given freedom to add new modes of play and revisit the concept from different angles. Some concepts developed on official versions have been integrated into the ''Tetris'' guidelines in order to standardize future versions and allow players to migrate between different versions with little effort.<ref name=\"tftt\"/> The IBM PC version was the most evolved from the original version, featuring a graphical interface, colored tetrominoes, running statistics for the number of tetrominoes placed, and a guide for the controls.<ref name=\"vadim\"/>\n\n== Computational complexity ==\nIn [[computer science]], it is common to analyze the [[Computational complexity theory|computational complexity]] of problems, including real life problems and games. It was proven that for the \"offline\" version of ''Tetris'' (the player knows the complete sequence of pieces that will be dropped, i.e. there is no hidden information) the following objectives are [[NP-complete]]:\n* Maximizing the number of rows cleared while playing the given piece sequence.\n* Maximizing the number of pieces placed before a loss occurs.\n* Maximizing the number of simultaneous clearing of four rows.\n* Minimizing the height of the highest filled grid square over the course of the sequence.\n\nAlso, it is [[Hardness of approximation|difficult to even approximately solve]] the first, second, and fourth problem.  It is [[NP-hard]], given an initial gameboard and a sequence of ''p'' pieces, to approximate the first two problems to within a factor of {{nowrap|''p''<sup>1 \u2212 ''\u03b5''</sup>}} for any constant {{nowrap|''\u03b5'' > 0}}.\nIt is NP-hard to approximate the last problem within a factor of {{nowrap|2 \u2212 ''\u03b5''}} for any constant {{nowrap|''\u03b5'' > 0}}.\n\nTo prove NP-completeness, it was shown that there is a polynomial [[Reduction (complexity)|reduction]] between the [[3-partition problem]], which is also NP-complete, and the ''Tetris'' problem.<ref>{{cite conference|url=http://erikdemaine.org/papers/Tetris_COCOON2003/paper.pdf|title=Tetris is Hard, Even to Approximate|last1=Demaine|first1=Erik D.|last2=Hohenberger|first2=Susan|last3=Liben-Nowell|first3=David|date=July 25\u201328, 2003|conference=Proceedings of the 9th International Computing and Combinatorics Conference (COCOON 2003)|conferenceurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120105042734/http://www.cs.montana.edu/bhz/cocoon03.html|location=Big Sky, Montana|access-date=December 18, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100613201613/http://erikdemaine.org/papers/Tetris_COCOON2003/paper.pdf|archive-date=June 13, 2010|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Music==\n{{See also|Korobeiniki#Tetris arrangements and modern cover versions|Tetris (Game Boy video game)#Music}}\nThe earliest versions of ''Tetris'' had no music. The NES version includes two original compositions by [[Hirokazu Tanaka]] along with an arrangement of \"Dance of the Sugar Plum Fairy\" from the second act of ''[[The Nutcracker]]'', composed by [[Pyotr Ilyich Tchaikovsky|Tchaikovsky]]. The [[Blue Planet Software]] and [[Tengen (company)|Tengen]] versions also feature original music, with the exception of an arrangement of \"[[Kalinka (song)|Kalinka]]\" in the Tengen version. Nintendo's Game Boy version includes three pieces of music as well: \"[[Korobeiniki]]\", [[Johann Sebastian Bach]]'s [[French Suites, BWV 812-817|French Suite No. 3 In B Minor]] (BWV 814), and an original track by Tanaka. \"Korobeiniki\" is used in most later versions of the game, and has appeared in other games, albums and films that make reference to ''Tetris''. In the 2000s, The Tetris Company added as a prerequisite for the granting of the license that a version of \"Korobeiniki\" be available in the game.<ref name=guardian020609/>\n\n== Cognitive effects ==\n{{See also|Tetris effect}}\nAccording to research from Dr. Richard Haier, ''et al.'' prolonged ''Tetris'' activity can also lead to more efficient brain activity during play.<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Richard J Haier|author2=Sherif Karama|author3=Leonard Leyba|author4=Rex E Jung|title=MRI assessment of cortical thickness and functional activity changes in adolescent girls following three months of practice on a visual-spatial task|journal=BMC Research Notes|year=2009|doi=10.1186/1756-0500-2-174|pmid=19723307|volume=2|page=174|pmc=2746806}}</ref> When first playing ''Tetris'', brain function and activity increases, along with greater cerebral energy consumption, measured by [[glucose]] metabolic rate. As ''Tetris'' players become more proficient, their brains show a reduced consumption of glucose, indicating more efficient brain activity for this task.<ref>{{cite journal|vauthors=Haier RJ, Siegel BV, MacLachlan A, Soderling E, Lottenberg S, Buchsbaum MS|title=Regional glucose metabolic changes after learning a complex visuospatial/motor task: a positron emission tomographic study|journal=Brain Res.|volume=570|issue=1\u20132|pages=134\u201343|date=January 1992|pmid=1617405|doi=10.1016/0006-8993(92)90573-R}}</ref> Moderate play of ''Tetris'' (half-an-hour a day for three months) boosts general cognitive functions such as \"critical thinking, reasoning, language and processing\" and increases [[cerebral cortex]] thickness.<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/science/science-news/6122290/Tetris-could-boost-brain-power.html Tetris 'could boost brain power'] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100212121948/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/science/science-news/6122290/Tetris-could-boost-brain-power.html |date=February 12, 2010 }} Telegraph news, September 2, 2009</ref>\n\nIn January 2009, an Oxford University research group headed by Dr. Emily Holmes reported in ''[[PLoS ONE]]'' that for healthy volunteers, playing ''Tetris'' soon after viewing traumatic material in the laboratory reduced the number of flashbacks to those scenes in the following week. They believe that the computer game may disrupt the memories that are retained of the sights and sounds witnessed at the time, and which are later re-experienced through involuntary, distressing flashbacks of that moment. The group hopes to develop this approach further as a potential intervention to reduce the flashbacks experienced in [[post-traumatic stress disorder]] but emphasized that these are only preliminary results.<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Holmes EA|author2=James EL|author3=Coode-Bate T|author4=Deeprose C|title=Can playing the computer game \"Tetris\" reduce the build-up of flashbacks for trauma? A proposal from cognitive science|journal=PLoS ONE|volume=4|issue=1|pages= e4153|year=2009|pmid=19127289|pmc=2607539|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0004153|editor1-last=Bell|editor1-first=Vaughan|bibcode=2009PLoSO...4.4153H}}</ref>\n\nProfessor Jackie Andrade and Jon May, from [[Plymouth University]]'s Cognition Institute, and Ph.D. student Jessica Skorka-Brown have conducted research that shows that playing ''Tetris'' could distract from cravings and give a \"quick and manageable\" fix for people struggling to stick to diets, or quit smoking or drinking.<ref>{{cite news|last=GANDER|first=KASHMIRA|title=Playing Tetris could help with weight loss and smokers' cravings, psychologists claim|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/gadgets-and-tech/news/playing-tetris-could-help-with-weight-loss-and-smokers-cravings-psychologists-claim-9149045.html|newspaper=The Independent|accessdate=February 24, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140224123004/http://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/gadgets-and-tech/news/playing-tetris-could-help-with-weight-loss-and-smokers-cravings-psychologists-claim-9149045.html|archive-date=February 24, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAnother notable effect is that, according to a Canadian study in April 2013, playing ''Tetris'' has been found to treat older adolescents with [[amblyopia]] (lazy eye), which was better than patching a victim's well eye to train their weaker eye. Dr. Robert Hess of the research team said: \"It's much better than patching \u2013 much more enjoyable; it's faster, and it seems to work better.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2013/04/23/study-finds-tetris-effectively-treats-lazy-eye|title=A Study Find That ''Tetris'' Effectively Treats a Lazy Eye|author=Luke Karmali|website=[[IGN]]|date=April 23, 2013|accessdate=June 20, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150620113327/http://www.ign.com/articles/2013/04/23/study-finds-tetris-effectively-treats-lazy-eye|archive-date=June 20, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> Tested in the [[United Kingdom]], this experiment also appears to help children with that problem.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-glasgow-west-17616818|title=Video Game Treatment for a Lazy Eye|work=[[BBC News]]|date=April 4, 2012|accessdate=June 20, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150819214014/http://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-glasgow-west-17616818|archive-date=August 19, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe game has been noted to cause the brain to involuntarily picture ''Tetris'' combinations even when the player is not playing (the [[Tetris effect|''Tetris'' effect]]), although this can occur with any computer game or situation showcasing repeated images or scenarios, such as a [[jigsaw puzzle]]. While debates about Tetris's cognitive benefits continue, at least some researchers view it as a milestone in the gamification of education.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://news.elearninginside.com/game-changing-arrival-tetris-united-states/|title=It has been 30 years since Tetris arrived in the U.S.|date=January 29, 2018|work=eLearningInside News|access-date=November 15, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181116085344/https://news.elearninginside.com/game-changing-arrival-tetris-united-states/|archive-date=November 16, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Reception and legacy==\n{{Video game reviews\n| Allgame = Arcade: {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite web|last=Cook|first=Brad|title=Tetris|url=http://www.allgame.com/game.php?id=2784&tab=review|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141114201703/http://www.allgame.com/game.php?id=2784&tab=review|url-status=dead|archive-date=November 14, 2014|publisher=AllGame|accessdate=June 9, 2014}}</ref><br />C64: {{Rating|3|5}}<ref>{{cite web|last=Sutyak|first=Jonathan|title=Tetris|url=http://www.allgame.com/game.php?id=16887&tab=review|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141115004356/http://www.allgame.com/game.php?id=16887&tab=review|archive-date=November 15, 2014|publisher=AllGame |url-status=dead|accessdate=June 9, 2014}}</ref><br />Macintosh: {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite web|last=Savignano|first=Lisa Karen|title=Tetris|url=http://www.allgame.com/game.php?id=11800&tab=review|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141115004358/http://www.allgame.com/game.php?id=11800&tab=review|archive-date=November 15, 2014|publisher=AllGame|url-status=dead|accessdate=June 9, 2014}}</ref><br />NES&nbsp;(Tengen):&nbsp;{{Rating|4.5|5}}&nbsp;<ref>{{cite web|last=Miller|first=Skyler|title=Tetris|url=http://www.allgame.com/game.php?id=14911&tab=review|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141115004353/http://www.allgame.com/game.php?id=14911&tab=review|archive-date=November 15, 2014|publisher=AllGame |url-status=dead|accessdate=June 9, 2014}}</ref><br />NES&nbsp;(Nintendo):&nbsp;{{Rating|4.5|5}}&nbsp;<ref>{{cite web|last=Weiss|first=Brett Alan|title=Tetris|url=http://www.allgame.com/game.php?id=1331&tab=review|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100216081022/http://allgame.com/game.php?id=1331&tab=review|archive-date=February 16, 2010|publisher=AllGame |url-status=dead|accessdate=June 9, 2014}}</ref>\n| CVG = 94%<ref name=\"CVG-1989-review\">{{cite magazine |url=http://live.worldofspectrum.org/files/thumb/4f2e51c9cdbbfbe/800/800 |title=Tetris Mastertronic |magazine=[[Computer and Video Games]] |issue=92 |page=74 |date=June 1989 |accessdate=November 22, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190417032455/http://live.worldofspectrum.org/files/thumb/4f2e51c9cdbbfbe/800/800 |archive-date=April 17, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| CRASH = 77%<ref name=\"Crash-19880review\">{{cite magazine |url=http://live.worldofspectrum.org/files/thumb/78d7602b35d0e2d/800/800 |title=Reviews: Tetris |magazine=[[Crash (magazine)|Crash]] |issue=50 |page=10 |date=March 1988 |accessdate=November 22, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190417032452/http://live.worldofspectrum.org/files/thumb/78d7602b35d0e2d/800/800 |archive-date=April 17, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| SUser = {{Rating|10|10}}<ref name=\"SinclairU-1988-review\">{{cite web |url=http://live.worldofspectrum.org/files/thumb/c53e67fb08dbe15/800/800 |title=TET\u042fIS: Arcade Review |magazine=[[Sinclair User]] |issue=1988 |page=13 |date=February 1988 |accessdate=November 22, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190417032457/http://live.worldofspectrum.org/files/thumb/c53e67fb08dbe15/800/800 |archive-date=April 17, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| YSinclair = 9/10<ref>{{cite web|last=Worrall|first=Tony|title=Tetris|url=http://www.ysrnry.co.uk/articles/tetris.htm|publisher=The Your Sinclair Rock'n'Roll Years|accessdate=August 8, 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120427113515/http://www.ysrnry.co.uk/articles/tetris.htm|archivedate=April 27, 2012}}</ref>\n| rev1 = ''[[Zzap!64]]''\n| rev1Score = 98%<ref>{{cite web|title=Gold Standard|url=http://www.zzap64.co.uk/zzap100/100thspec5.html|publisher=The Def Gui to Zzap!64|accessdate=August 8, 2012|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6Dzo6NOv6?url=http://www.zzap64.co.uk/zzap100/100thspec5.html|archive-date=January 28, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[ACE (games magazine)|ACE]]''\n| rev2Score = 95%<ref name=\"ACE-1988-review\">{{cite web |url=http://live.worldofspectrum.org/files/thumb/4852d3d00d9894b/800/800 |title=Tetris: Can MIRRORSOFT pack them in? |publisher=[[ACE (games magazine)|ACE]] |issue=5 |page=49 |date=February 1988 |accessdate=November 22, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190417035859/http://live.worldofspectrum.org/files/thumb/4852d3d00d9894b/800/800 |archive-date=April 17, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| award1Pub = Zzap!64\n| award1 = Gold Medal\n| award2Pub = Sinclair User\n| award2 = SU Classic\n}}\n''[[Compute!]]'' called the IBM version of ''Tetris'' \"one of the most addictive computer games this side of the [[Berlin Wall]] ... [it] is ''not'' the game to start if you have work to do or an appointment to keep. Consider yourself warned\".<ref name=\"weatherman198807\">{{cite news | url=https://archive.org/stream/1988-07-compute-magazine/Compute_Issue_098_1988_Jul#page/n73/mode/2up | title=Tetris | work=Compute! | date=July 1988 | accessdate=November 10, 2013 | author=Weatherman, Lynne | page=72 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140316211621/https://archive.org/stream/1988-07-compute-magazine/Compute_Issue_098_1988_Jul#page/n73/mode/2up | archive-date=March 16, 2014 | url-status=live }}</ref> [[Orson Scott Card]] joked that the game \"proves that Russia still wants to [[We will bury you|bury us]]. I shudder to think of the blow to our economy as computer productivity drops to 0\". Noting that ''Tetris'' was not copy-protected, he wrote \"Obviously, the game is meant to find its way onto every American machine\".<ref name=\"card198904\">{{cite news | url=https://archive.org/stream/1989-04-compute-magazine/Compute_Issue_107_1989_Apr#page/n11/mode/2up | title=Gameplay | work=Compute! | date=April 1989 | accessdate=November 10, 2013 | author=Card, Orson Scott | page=11 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140316211723/https://archive.org/stream/1989-04-compute-magazine/Compute_Issue_107_1989_Apr#page/n11/mode/2up | archive-date=March 16, 2014 | url-status=live }}</ref> The IBM version of the game was reviewed in 1988 in ''[[Dragon (magazine)|Dragon]]'' No. 135 by Hartley, Patricia, and Kirk Lesser in \"The Role of Computers\" column. The reviewers gave the game 4.5 out of 5 stars.<ref name=\"Dragon135\">{{cite journal|title=The Role of Computers|last1=Lesser|last2=Lesser|last3=Lesser|first1=Hartley|first2=Patricia|first3=Kirk|journal=Dragon|issue=135|date=July 1988|pages=82\u201389}}</ref> The Lessers later reviewed Spectrum HoloByte's [[Macintosh]] version of ''Tetris'' in 1989 in ''Dragon'' No. 141, giving that version 5 out of 5 stars.<ref name=\"Dragon141\">{{cite journal|title= The Role of Computers|last1=Lesser|last2=Lesser|last3=Lesser|first1=Hartley|first2=Patricia|first3=Kirk|journal=Dragon|issue=141|date= January 1989|pages=72\u201378}}</ref> ''[[Macworld]]'' reviewed the Macintosh version of ''Tetris'' in 1988, praising its stategic gameplay, stating that \"''Tetris'' offers the rare combination of being simple to learn but extremely challenging to play\", and also praising the inclusion of the [[Desk Accessory]] version, which uses less RAM. ''Macworld'' summarized their review by listing ''Tetris' ''pros and cons, stating that ''Tetris'' is \"Elegant; easy to play; challenging and addicting; requires quick thinking, long-term strategy, and lightning reflexes\" and listed ''Tetris''' cons as \"None.\"<ref>{{cite magazine|last = Buderi|first = Robert|title = Tetris 1.0 Review|date = December 1988|url = https://archive.org/details/MacWorld_8812_December_1988/page/n181|magazine = Macworld|publisher = Mac Publishing|page = 178}}</ref>\n\nIn 1993, the ZX Spectrum version of the game was voted number 49 in the ''[[Your Sinclair]] Official Top 100 Games of All Time''.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Top 100 Games of All Time|journal=Your Sinclair|date=September 1993}}</ref> In 1996, ''Tetris Pro'' was ranked the 38th best game of all time by ''[[Amiga Power]]''.<ref>Amiga Power magazine issue 64, Future Publishing, August 1996</ref> ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' picked the game as the #8 greatest game available in 1991, saying: \"Thanks to Nintendo\u2019s endless promotion, Tetris has become one of the most popular video games.\"<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://ew.com/article/1991/11/22/video-games-guide/ | title=Video Games Guide | access-date=September 9, 2018 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170219184932/http://ew.com/article/1991/11/22/video-games-guide/ | archive-date=February 19, 2017 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n''Computer Gaming World'' gave ''Tetris'' the 1989 Compute! Choice Award for Arcade Game, describing it as \"by far, the most addictive game ever\".<ref name=\"compute198901\">{{cite news | url=https://archive.org/stream/1989-01-compute-magazine/Compute_Issue_104_1989_Jan#page/n25/mode/2up | title=The 189 Compute! Choice Awards | work=Compute! | date=January 1989 | accessdate=November 10, 2013 | page=24 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140316200847/https://archive.org/stream/1989-01-compute-magazine/Compute_Issue_104_1989_Jan#page/n25/mode/2up | archive-date=March 16, 2014 | url-status=live }}</ref> The game won three [[Software Publishers Association]] Excellence in Software Awards in 1989, including Best Entertainment Program and the Critic's Choice Award for consumers.<ref name=\"scisco198908\">{{cite news | url=https://archive.org/stream/1989-08-compute-magazine/Compute_Issue_111_1989_Aug#page/n7/mode/2up | title=the Envelope, Please | work=Compute! | date=August 1989 | accessdate=November 11, 2013 | author=Scisco, Peter | page=6 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140316211940/https://archive.org/stream/1989-08-compute-magazine/Compute_Issue_111_1989_Aug#page/n7/mode/2up | archive-date=March 16, 2014 | url-status=live }}</ref> ''Computer Gaming World'' in 1996 ranked it 14th on the magazine's list of the most innovative computer games.<ref name=\"cgw199611mostinnovative\">{{cite news | url=http://www.cgwmuseum.org/galleries/index.php?year=1996&pub=2&id=148 | title=The 15 Most Innovative Computer Games | work=Computer Gaming World | date=November 1996 | accessdate=March 25, 2016 | pages=102 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160408023915/http://cgwmuseum.org/galleries/index.php?year=1996&pub=2&id=148 | archive-date=April 8, 2016 | url-status=live }}</ref> That same year, ''[[Next Generation (magazine)|Next Generation]]'' listed it as number 2 on their \"Top 100 Games of All Time\", commenting that, \"There is something so perfect, so [[Zen]] about the falling blocks of ''Tetris'' that the game has captured the interest of everyone who has ever played it.\"<ref>{{cite magazine|last=|first= |title=Top 100 Games of All Time |magazine=[[Next Generation (magazine)|Next Generation]]|issue=21 |publisher=[[Imagine Media]] |date=September 1996|page=71}}</ref> On March 12, 2007, ''[[The New York Times]]'' reported that ''Tetris'' was named to a list of the ten most important video games of all time, the so-called [[game canon]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/03/12/arts/design/12vide.html?ex=1331352000&en=380fc9bb18694da5&ei=5124&partner=permalink&exprod=permalink|title=Is That Just Some Game? No, It's a Cultural Artifact|newspaper=[[nytimes.com]]|first=HEATHER|last=CHAPLIN|date=March 12, 2007|accessdate=November 1, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151204212137/http://www.nytimes.com/2007/03/12/arts/design/12vide.html?ex=1331352000&en=380fc9bb18694da5&ei=5124&partner=permalink&exprod=permalink|archive-date=December 4, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> After announced at the 2007 [[Game Developers Conference]], the [[Library of Congress]] took up the video game preservation proposal and began with these 10 games, including ''Tetris''.<ref name=\"Joystiq\">{{cite web|url=http://www.joystiq.com/2007/03/12/10-most-important-video-games-of-all-time-as-judged-by-2-design/ |title=10 most important video games of all time, as judged by 2 designers, 2 academics, and 1 lowly blogger |last=Ransom-Wiley |first=James |publisher=Joystiq |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140422035847/http://www.joystiq.com/2007/03/12/10-most-important-video-games-of-all-time-as-judged-by-2-design/ |archivedate=April 22, 2014 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.loc.gov/digitalpreservation/2012/09/yes-the-library-of-congress-has-video-games-an-interview-with-david-gibson/ |title=Yes, The Library of Congress Has Video Games: An Interview with David Gibson |date=September 26, 2012 |accessdate=January 18, 2013 |publisher=blogs.loc.gov |first=Trevor |last=Owens |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131205100245/http://blogs.loc.gov/digitalpreservation/2012/09/yes-the-library-of-congress-has-video-games-an-interview-with-david-gibson/ |archivedate=December 5, 2013 |df= }}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, video game website [[GameFAQs]] hosted its sixth annual \"[[GameFAQs#Contests|Character Battle]]\", in which the users nominate their favorite video game characters for a popularity contest in which characters participate. The L-shaped ''Tetris'' piece (or \"L-Block\" as it was called) entered the contest as a joke character, but on November 4, 2007, it won the contest.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamefaqs.com/features/contest/cb6|title=Fall 2007: The Great GameFAQs Character Battle VI|website=GameFAQs|accessdate=November 29, 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071029201304/http://www.gamefaqs.com/features/contest/cb6|archive-date=October 29, 2007|url-status=live}}</ref> On June 6, 2009, Google honored ''Tetris''{{'}} 25-year anniversary by changing its logotype to a version drawn with ''Tetris'' blocks \u2013 the \"l\" letter being the long ''Tetris'' block lowering into its place,<ref>{{cite web|title=Google Features TETRIS Look For Game's 25th Anniversary|url=http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20090605005609/en|publisher=Electronic Arts|date=June 5, 2009|quote=Google will roll out the TETRIS-inspired design in 24-hour periods, starting first at 1:00&nbsp;pm EDT in Japan, Australia, and New Zealand. From 6:00&nbsp;pm&nbsp; \u2013 7:00&nbsp;pm EDT, the TETRIS-inspired design will begin appearing in Europe, Asia, Africa, and the Middle East. Starting June 6th, at 12:00&nbsp;am EDT, the TETRIS-inspired design will be available in North and South America.|accessdate=September 25, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110216141150/http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20090605005609/en|archive-date=February 16, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> seen here.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.google.com/doodles/25-years-of-tetris-courtesy-of-tetris-holding-llc |title=25 Years of Tetris \u2013 courtesy of Tetris Holding, LLC |date=June 6, 2009 |accessdate=November 22, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121104165253/http://www.google.com/doodles/25-years-of-tetris-courtesy-of-tetris-holding-llc |archive-date=November 4, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> In 2009, ''[[Game Informer]]'' put ''Tetris'' 3rd on their list of \"The Top 200 Games of All Time\", saying that \"If a game could be considered ageless, it's ''Tetris''\".<ref name=\"gi_best\">{{cite journal|author=The ''Game Informer'' staff|title=The Top 200 Games of All Time|pages=44\u201379|issue= 200|date=December 2009|journal=Game Informer|issn=1067-6392|oclc=27315596}}</ref> The ''Game Informer'' staff also placed it third on their 2001 list of the 100 best games ever.<ref>{{cite web |title=Game Informer's Top 100 Games of All Time (Circa Issue 100) |url=http://www.gameinformer.com/b/features/archive/2009/11/16/game-informer-s-top-100-games-of-all-time-circa-issue-100.aspx |work=[[Game Informer]] |last=Cork |first=Jeff |date=November 16, 2009 |accessdate=December 10, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100408113757/http://gameinformer.com/b/features/archive/2009/11/16/game-informer-s-top-100-games-of-all-time-circa-issue-100.aspx |archive-date=April 8, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n''[[Electronic Gaming Monthly]]''{{'}}s 100th issue had ''Tetris'' as first place in the \"100 Best Games of All Time\", commenting that \"''Tetris'' is as pure as a video game can get. ... When the right blocks come your way - and if you can manage to avoid mistakes - the game can be relaxing. One mislaid block, however, and your duties switch to damage control, a mad, panicky dash to clean up your mess or die.\" ''Tetris'' was also the only game for which the list did not specify one or two versions; the editors explained that after deadlocking over which version was best, they concluded that there was no wrong version of ''Tetris'' to play.<ref>{{cite magazine |title=100 Best Games of All Time |magazine=[[Electronic Gaming Monthly]]|issue=100 |publisher=[[Ziff Davis]] |date=November 1997|page=160}} Note: Contrary to the title, the intro to the article (on page 100) explicitly states that the list covers console video games only, meaning PC games and arcade games were not eligible.</ref> In 2007, ''Tetris'' came in second place in [[IGN]]'s \"100 Greatest Video Games of All Time\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://top100.ign.com/2007/ign_top_game_2.html |title=IGN Top 100 Games of All Time \u2013 2007 |publisher=Top100.ign.com |date= |accessdate=November 22, 2012|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131107133844/http://top100.ign.com/2007/ign_top_game_2.html|archivedate=November 7, 2013}}</ref> In January 2010, it was announced that the [[List of Tetris variants|''Tetris'' franchise]] had sold more than 170 million copies, approximately 70 million physical copies and over 100 million copies [[Tetris (Electronic Arts)|for cell phones]],<ref name=guardian020609/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.maximejohnson.com/techno/2010/01/tetris-atteint-les-100-millions-de-telechargements-payants-et-une-petite-histoire-du-jeu/ |title=\u00bb Tetris atteint les 100 millions de t\u00e9l\u00e9chargements payants (et une petite histoire du jeu) \u2013 Maximejohnson.com/techno : actualit\u00e9s technologiques, tests et opinions par le j |publisher=Maximejohnson.com |date=January 19, 2011 |accessdate=November 22, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120726141129/http://www.maximejohnson.com/techno/2010/01/tetris-atteint-les-100-millions-de-telechargements-payants-et-une-petite-histoire-du-jeu/ |archive-date=July 26, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> making it one of the [[List of best-selling video game franchises|best-selling video game franchises of all time]]. {{As of|2011|12}}, ''Tetris'' has sold 132{{nbsp}}million paid [[mobile game]] downloads.<ref>{{cite news |title=EA Launches New Tetris\u00ae Game on the App Store Today |url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20111201006159/en/EA-Launches-New-Tetris%C2%AE-Game-App-Store |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=[[Business Wire]] |date=1 December 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 1991, ''[[PC Format]]'' named ''Tetris'' one of the 50 best computer games ever. The editors called it \"incredibly addictive\" and \"one of the best games of all time\".<ref name=pcformat50>{{cite journal | author=Staff | journal=[[PC Format]] | title=The 50 best games EVER! |date=October 1991 | issue=1 | pages=109\u2013111 }}</ref>\n\nThere was a hoax that circulated in February 2019 that the original NES instruction manual for ''Tetris'' had named the seven tetrominos with names like \"Orange Ricky\", \"Hero\" and \"Smashboy\", but was disproven. Despite being disproven by video game historians, a question on the October 7, 2019 airing of ''[[Jeopardy!]]'' alluded to these names.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://kotaku.com/jeopardy-airs-a-hilariously-incorrect-bit-of-tetris-tr-1838889592 | title = Jeopardy! Airs A Hilariously Incorrect Bit Of Tetris Trivia | first = Chris | last = Kohler | date = October 8, 2019 | accessdate = October 8, 2019 | work = [[Kotaku]] }}</ref>\n\n=== In research ===\n''Tetris'' has been the subject of academic research. [[Vladimir Pokhilko]] was the first clinical psychologist to conduct experiments using ''Tetris''.<ref name=\"MarkWolf2012\">{{cite book | author=Mark J. P. Wolf | title=Encyclopedia of Video Games: The Culture, Technology, and Art of Gaming | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=deBFx7QAwsQC&pg=PA642 | accessdate=February 5, 2013 | date=August 31, 2012 | publisher=ABC-CLIO | isbn=978-0-313-37936-9 | page=642 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130528022924/http://books.google.com/books?id=deBFx7QAwsQC&pg=PA642 | archive-date=May 28, 2013 | url-status=live }}</ref> Subsequently, it has been used for research in several fields including the [[theory of computation]], algorithmic theory, and [[cognitive psychology]].\n\nDuring the game of ''Tetris'', blocks appear to [[Adsorption|adsorb]] onto the lower surface of the window. This has led scientists to use tetrominoes \"as a proxy for molecules with a complex shape\" to model their \"[[adsorption]] on a flat surface\" to study the [[thermodynamics]] of [[nanoparticles]].<ref>[https://arstechnica.com/science/news/2009/05/the-thermodynamics-of-tetris.ars The Thermodynamics of Tetiris] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110912220000/http://arstechnica.com/science/news/2009/05/the-thermodynamics-of-tetris.ars |date=September 12, 2011 }}, Ars Technica, 2009.</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.1021/la900196b| pmid=19397254|title = Structure, Thermodynamics, and Solubility in Tetromino Fluids| journal=Langmuir| volume=25| issue=12| pages=6702\u20136716|year = 2009|last1 = Barnes|first1 = Brian C.| last2=Siderius| first2=Daniel W.| last3=Gelb| first3=Lev D.| doi-access=free}}</ref>\n\n== Film ==\n[[Threshold Entertainment]] has teamed up with The Tetris Company to develop a film adaptation of ''Tetris''. Threshold's CEO describes the film as an epic sci-fi adventure that will form part of a trilogy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.movieweb.com/tetris-movie-story|title='Tetris' Movie Planned as an Epic Sci-Fi Adventure|work=Movieweb|date=September 30, 2014|accessdate=September 30, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141001011505/http://www.movieweb.com/tetris-movie-story|archive-date=October 1, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/tetris-movie-be-80m-us-894779|title='Tetris' Movie to Be $80M U.S.-China Co-Production|magazine=The Hollywood Reporter|last=Brzeski|first=Patrick|date=May 17, 2016|access-date=May 17, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160518095550/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/tetris-movie-be-80m-us-894779|archive-date=May 18, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2016, sources reported on a press release claiming the film would be shot in China in 2017 with an $80 million budget. However, no 2017 or later sources confirm the film ever actually went into production.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mashable.com/2016/05/17/tetris-movie-real/|title=Is this 'Tetris' movie for real? Too many key blocks are missing to be sure|last=Dickey|first=Josh|date=May 17, 2016|publisher=Mashable|access-date=June 24, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180624093105/https://mashable.com/2016/05/17/tetris-movie-real/|archive-date=June 24, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n''Tetris'' appeared in the 2010 short animated film [[Pixels (2010 film)|''Pixels'']], and in the 2015 movie ''[[Pixels (2015 film)|Pixels]]'' inspired by the former.<ref>{{Citation|title=Pixels (2015)|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt2120120/movieconnections|accessdate=February 3, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161118041924/http://www.imdb.com/title/tt2120120/movieconnections|archive-date=November 18, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Video Games|1980s|1990s}}\n* ''[[Pentomino]]'' [[tiling puzzle]]s and games are popular in [[recreational mathematics]].\n* ''[[Brain Wall]]'' and ''[[Blokken]]'' \u2014 game shows based on ''Tetris''\n* ''[[Ecstasy of Order: The Tetris Masters]]'' \u2014 2011 documentary about the 2010 ''Tetris'' Championships featuring interviews with Pajitnov and Dr. Richard Haier.\n* ''[[Game Over (book)|Game Over]]'' \u2014 1993 book covering Nintendo history, including interviews with Alexey Pajitnov and others regarding ''Tetris'' licensing.\n* [[List of Tetris variants|List of ''Tetris'' variants]]\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite web | url = http://vadim.oversigma.com/Tetris.htm | title = Tetris Story | last = Gerasimov | first = Vadim | website = [[Vadim Gerasimov|OverSigma]]}}\n* {{cite web | url = http://www.scientificamerican.com/article/mathematicians-prove-tetr/ | title = Mathematicians Prove Tetris Is Tough | last = Graham | first = Sarah | date = October 29, 2002 | website = [[Scientific American]]}}\n* {{cite AV media | url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p00mdqf8 | title = The creation of Tetris | date = December 29, 2012 | website = [[BBC World Service]] | publisher = [[BBC]]}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n===Books===\n* {{Cite book |last=Brzustowski |first=John |title=Can You Win at Tetris? |year=1992 |publisher=University of British Columbia |url=https://open.library.ubc.ca/cIRcle/collections/ubctheses/831/items/1.0079748}}\n* {{Cite book |last=Ichbiah |first=Daniel |title=La Saga des Jeux Vid\u00e9o |language=French |year=1997 |publisher=Pix'N Love Editions |edition=1st |pages=84\u2013100 |isbn=2266087630}}\n* {{Cite book |last1=Sheff |first1=David |last2=Eddy |first2=Andy |title=Game Over: Press Start to Continue |publisher=Cyberactive Media Group |year=1999 |edition=1st |pages=295-348 |isbn=0966961706}}\n* {{Cite book |last=Kent |first=Steven |title=The Ultimate History of Video Games: From Pong to Pokemon: The Story Behind the Craze That Touched Our Lives and Changed the World |publisher=Three Rivers Press |year=2001 |edition=1st |pages=377-381 |isbn=9780761536437}}\n* {{Cite book |last1=Loguidice |first1=Bill |last2=Barton |first2=Matt |year=2009 |title=Vintage Games: An Insider Look at the History of the Most Influential Games of All Time |url=https://www.routledge.com/Vintage-Games-An-Insider-Look-at-the-History-of-Grand-Theft-Auto-Super/Loguidice-Barton/p/book/9780240811468 |edition=1st |publisher=[[Focal Press]] |pages=291\u2013301 