{"title_page": "Zack Snyder", "text_new": "{{pp-pc1|small=yes}}\n{{short description|American film director, film producer, and screenwriter}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name           = Zack Snyder\n| image          = Zack Snyder by Gage Skidmore 2.jpg\n| caption        = Snyder at the 2016 [[San Diego Comic-Con International]]\n| birth_name     = Zachary Edward Snyder\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1966|03|01}}\n| birth_place    = [[Green Bay, Wisconsin]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n| citizenship    = American\n| alma_mater      = [[Art Center College of Design]]\n| residence      = [[Pasadena, California|Pasadena]], [[California]], U.S.{{Citation needed|date=February 2019}}\n| occupation     = {{hlist|Film director|film producer|screenwriter}}\n| years_active   = 1990\u2013present\n| religion       = \n| spouse         = Denise Weber (divorced)<br />{{marriage|[[Deborah Snyder]]|2004|}}\n| children       = 8 (1 deceased, 4 adopted)<ref>{{cite web |title=Justice League: Zack Snyder quits movie after daughter kills herself |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2017/may/23/justice-league-zack-snyder-quits-joss-whedon |website=The Guardian |accessdate=February 13, 2019 |date=23 May 2017}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Zachary Edward Snyder''' (born March 1, 1966) is an American film director, producer, and screenwriter. He made his feature film debut in 2004 with [[Dawn of the Dead (2004 film)|a remake]] of the 1978 horror film ''[[Dawn of the Dead (1978 film)|Dawn of the Dead]]''. Since then, he has directed or produced a number of comic book and superhero films, including ''[[300 (film)|300]]'' (2006) and ''[[Watchmen (film)|Watchmen]]'' (2009), as well as the [[Superman]] film that started the [[DC Extended Universe]], ''[[Man of Steel (film)|Man of Steel]]'' (2013) and its follow-ups, ''[[Batman v Superman: Dawn of Justice]]'' (2016) and the dreadfully awful ''[[Justice League (film)|Justice League]]'' (2017). If you want to see a cool Modern Day with Superman just watch \u201cThe Boys\u201d on Amazon Prime. Seriously Homelander makes Snyder\u2019s Superman look like Spongebob. He also served as co-screenwriter for ''300'', ''[[Sucker Punch (2011 film)|Sucker Punch]]'' (2011), and ''[[300: Rise of an Empire]]'' (2014), an executive producer for ''[[Suicide Squad (2016 film)|Suicide Squad]]'' (2016) and ''[[Aquaman (film)|Aquaman]]'' (2018), and as co-writer of the story for ''[[Wonder Woman (2017 film)|Wonder Woman]]'' (2017) and ''Justice League''.\n\nSnyder is the co-founder of [[The Stone Quarry]], which was formerly known as Cruel and Unusual Films, a production company he established in 2004, alongside his wife [[Deborah Snyder]] and producing partner Wesley Coller.<ref name=\"Louie\" />\n\n== Early life ==\nSnyder was born in [[Green Bay, Wisconsin|Green Bay]], [[Wisconsin]], and raised in [[Riverside, Connecticut|Riverside]], [[Connecticut]]. His mother, Marsha Manley (n\u00e9e Reeves) (d. 2010)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.geni.com/people/Marsha-Snyder/6000000041194133936|title=Marsha Manley Snyder|website=geni_family_tree|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-23}}</ref>, was a painter and a photography teacher at [[Daycroft School]], which Snyder later attended. His father, Charles Edward \"Ed\" Snyder (1936\u20132008)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.geni.com/people/Charles-Snyder/6000000069140003863|title=Charles Edward \"Ed\" Snyder|website=geni_family_tree|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-23}}</ref>, worked as an executive recruiter.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=PBEB&p_theme=pbeb&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=117C5D13549DA238&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM | work=[[The Berkshire Eagle]] | title=Fan makes a film | date=8 March 2007 |access-date=8 October 2013|last=Everhart |first=Bill}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.legacy.com/obituaries/berkshire/obituary.aspx?n=marsha-snyder&pid=144455179 |title=Marsha Snyder Obituary \u2013 Pittsfield, MA|work=[[The Berkshire Eagle]]|publisher=Legacy.com |date= |accessdate=8 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/54776720/ |title=The North Adams Transcript from North Adams, Massachusetts \u00b7 Page 15 |publisher=Newspapers.com |date=1958-05-05 |accessdate=8 August 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151208082151/http://www.newspapers.com/newspage/54776720/ |archivedate=8 December 2015 }}</ref> He has an older sister, Audrey, and was raised as a [[Christian Scientist]].<ref name=\"Louie\">{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/02/20/fashion/weddings/20UNIONS.html |title=Off Screen, a Long-Running Romance |last=Louie |first=Elaine |date=18 February 2011 |work=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=2 October 2014 |quote=}}</ref> Snyder attended Camp Owatonna in Harrison, Maine, during the summer months as a child. Snyder studied painting a year after high school at [[Heatherley School of Fine Art]] in England, although he had already begun filmmaking. Afterward, Snyder attended [[Art Center College of Design]] in [[Pasadena, California|Pasadena]], California.<ref name=\"Bloomberg\">{{cite web|title=Zack Snyder's Superhero Life|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/features/2016-zack-snyder-profile|last=Leonard|first=Devin|date=1 March 2016|accessdate=1 March 2016|work=[[Bloomberg News]]}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n\nSnyder made his feature film debut with the remake of the horror film ''[[Dawn of the Dead (2004 film)|Dawn of the Dead]]'' (2004), and scored a box office hit with the fantasy war film ''[[300 (film)|300]]'' (2006), adapted from writer-artist [[Frank Miller (comics)|Frank Miller]]'s [[Dark Horse Comics]] [[miniseries]] of [[300 (comics)|the same name]]. His [[Warner Bros.]] film ''[[Watchmen (film)|Watchmen]]'' was released on March 6, 2009 and grossed $185 million worldwide. His follow-up project/animation debut titled ''[[Legend of the Guardians: The Owls of Ga'Hoole]]'' was released on September 24, 2010. Snyder produced, co-wrote, and directed ''[[Sucker Punch (2011 film)|Sucker Punch]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url = http://suicidegirls.com/interviews/Zack+Snyder%3A+Watchmen/|title = Zack Snyder: Watchmen|publisher = [[SuicideGirls]]|date = 5 March 2009|accessdate =5 March 2009}}</ref> which was released on March 25, 2011. The film, based on a script written by Snyder and Steve Shibuya, was about a young woman in a mental hospital who fantasizes of escape with her fellow inmates.\n\nHe directed 2013's ''[[Man of Steel (film)|Man of Steel]]'' for Warner Bros., a reboot of the Superman franchise. He signed on direct a yet-to-be-produced remake of the 1969 film ''[[The Illustrated Man (film)|The Illustrated Man]]'',<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.comingsoon.net/movies/news/79924-updates-on-the-jetsons-zack-snyders-the-illustrated-man |title=Updates on The Jetsons & Zack Snyder's The Illustrated Man |last=Douglas |first=Edward |website=ComingSoon.net |date=4 October 2010 |accessdate=13 June 2016}}</ref> and produced the prequel/sequel to ''300'', ''[[300: Rise of an Empire]]'' (2014). He also wants to direct a segment for an upcoming ''[[Heavy Metal (film)#Remake|Heavy Metal 3]]'', and plans to write and direct a sequel to ''Legend of the Guardians''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.deadline.com/2010/10/zack-snyder-directing-superman/ |title=SCOOP: Zack Snyder Directing 'Superman' |work=Deadline.com |author=Fleming, Mike |date=4 October 2010 |accessdate=4 October 2010}}</ref>\n\nDuring Comic Con 2013, Snyder announced that [[Batman]] and [[Superman]] would share the screen in ''[[Batman v Superman: Dawn of Justice]]'', released in 2016. Snyder directed, Cavill reprised his role as Superman, and [[Ben Affleck]] played Batman.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.slashfilm.com/zack-snyder-will-direct-supermanbatman-movie-inspired-by-frank-millers-the-dark-knight-returns/ |title=Zack Snyder Will Direct Superman/Batman Movie Inspired by Frank Miller's 'The Dark Knight Returns' |last=Fischer |first=Russ |date=20 July 2013 |website=[[/Film]] |publisher= |access-date=20 July 2013 |quote=}}</ref> Snyder directed Warner Bros.' 2017 ''[[Justice League (film)|Justice League]]'', but was replaced with [[Joss Whedon]] after having to leave during post-production to deal with the death of his daughter.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://blogs.wsj.com/speakeasy/2014/04/27/warner-bros-details-plans-for-justice-league-movie-exclusive/|title=Warner Bros. Plans 'Justice League' Movie Directed by Zack Snyder (Exclusive)|last=Fritz|first=Ben|work=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|date=26 April 2014|accessdate=27 April 2014}}</ref>\n\nAs of March 2016, Snyder was working on ''The Last Photograph'', a drama about a war photographer in South-America. He is also currently working on an adaptation of the 1943 novel ''[[The Fountainhead]]'' by [[Ayn Rand]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://screenanarchy.com/2011/08/breaking-zack-snyder-taking-directors-chair-on-the-last-photograph.html | title=BREAKING: Zack Snyder Taking Director's Chair On THE LAST PHOTOGRAPH |last=Brown |first=Todd | publisher=[[Screen Anarchy]] | date=2 August 2011 | accessdate=8 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/batman-v-superman-married-creative-874799 | title='Batman v. Superman': Married Creative Duo on That R-Rated DVD, Plans for DC Superhero Universe |last=Siegel |first=Tatiana | work=The Hollywood Reporter | date=17 March 2016 | accessdate=4 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2018/05/zack-snyder-the-fountainhead-adaptation|title=Zack Snyder's Next Project Is an Adaptation of The Fountainhead|last=Desta|first=Yohana|work=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]|date=29 May 2018|access-date=29 May 2018|language=en}}</ref>. He has also expressed an interest in making a film, in the style of ''[[300 (film)|300]]'', about [[George Washington]], the first president of the United States of America.<ref>Jacob Hall, [https://www.slashfilm.com/zack-snyder-george-washington-movie/ \"Zack Snyder Wants to Make a George Washington Movie\"], ''SlashFilm'', 2 March 2016</ref>\n\nOn January 29, 2019, Snyder announced that he has signed on to helm ''[[Army of the Dead (upcoming film)|Army of the Dead]]'', a zombie horror thriller, for [[Netflix]]. Snyder will direct and produce with his partner and wife, Deborah Snyder, via their newly rebranded production company, [[The Stone Quarry]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/zack-snyder-returns-movies-zombie-pic-army-dead-1178979|title=Zack Snyder Returning to Movies With Zombie Action Pic 'Army of the Dead' (Exclusive)|website=The Hollywood Reporter|language=en|access-date=2019-01-31}}</ref>\n\n== Style ==\nSnyder often uses [[slow motion]] in and out of the fight scenes in his films, which Amy Nicholson of ''[[BoxOffice (magazine)|BoxOffice]]'' magazine remarked separates the director from other filmmakers who make multiple cuts and close-ups during a fight. A minute-long shot from ''300'' shows King Leonidas slaughtering his enemies, the camera zooming in and out to emphasize each kill and move Leonidas makes.<ref>{{cite news|last=Nicholson|first=Amy |magazine=Box Office Magazine |date=26 February 2009 |url=http://boxoffice.com/editors-desk/slow-and-steady.php |title=Slow and Steady |accessdate=28 March 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090303045524/http://boxoffice.com/editors-desk/slow-and-steady.php |archivedate=3 March 2009 }}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nSnyder lives in Pasadena with his second wife, producer [[Deborah Snyder|Deborah Johnson]]. The couple first met in 1996, started dating in 2002, and married on September 25, 2004 at [[St. Bartholomew's Episcopal Church, New York|St. Bartholomew's Episcopal Church]] in Manhattan, New York.<ref name=\"Weddings\">{{cite news|title = WEDDINGS/CELEBRATIONS: VOWS; Deborah Johnson and Zack Snyder \u2013 New York Times|url = https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9F05E3DA1338F930A35753C1A9629C8B63&fta=y|date = 3 October 2004|last = Louie|first = Elaine|publisher = [[The New York Times Company]]|work = [[The New York Times]]|accessdate = 25 July 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.filmjournal.com/filmjournal/content_display/news-and-features/features/movies/e3i8f6bf92e292731581559af0969092ce9?pn=2|author=Frank Lovece|title=CGI: 'Watchmen'--Zack Snyder brings superhero saga to the finish line|journal=Film Journal International|date=19 February 2009|accessdate=19 February 2009}}</ref> He was previously married to Denise Weber.\n\nSnyder has eight children, half of whom are adopted: Olivia, Willow, Autumn, Eli, Ezekiel, Jett, Sage and Cash. He and Denise had Olivia and Eli, and adopted Willow and Autumn from China. Two younger sons, Ezekiel and Jett, are from his relationship with Kirsten Elin, who was his line producer on commercials for some time.<ref name=\"Louie\" /> Snyder and Deborah adopted Sage and Cash during the course of making ''[[Man of Steel (film)|Man of Steel]]''.<ref name=\"Bloomberg\" />\n\nOn March 12, 2017,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mec.lacounty.gov/case-detail/?caseNumber=2017-02042 |title=Los Angeles County Department of Medical Examiner \u2013 Coroner \u2013 Case Detail |last= |first= |date= |website=[[Los Angeles County Department of Medical Examiner-Coroner]] |publisher= |access-date=24 May 2017 |quote=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/179621277 |title=Autumn Snyder (1996\u20132017) |last= |first= |date= |website=[[Find a Grave]] |publisher= |access-date=24 May 2017 |quote=}}</ref> the suicide of his daughter Autumn prompted Snyder to withdraw from post-production work on ''[[Justice League (film)|Justice League]]'' in May 2017 to be with his family.<ref>{{citeweb|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/zack-snyder-steps-down-justice-league-deal-family-tragedy-1006455|title=Zack Snyder Steps Down From 'Justice League' to Deal With Family Tragedy|date=22 May 2017|accessdate=23 September 2018|publisher=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|first=Borys|last=Kit}}</ref>\n\n== Filmography ==\n=== Films ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Year\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Film\n! colspan=\"3\" |Functioned as\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Notes\n|-\n! width=\"65\" |[[Film director|Director]]\n! width=\"65\" |[[Screenwriter|Writer]]\n! width=\"65\" |[[Film producer|Producer]]\n|-\n|2004\n|''[[Dawn of the Dead (2004 film)|Dawn of the Dead]]''\n|{{yes}}\n|{{no}}\n|{{no}}\n|\n|-\n|2007\n|''[[300 (film)|300]]''\n|{{yes}}\n|{{yes}}\n|{{no}}\n| Co-screenwriter with [[Kurt Johnstad]] and Michael B. Gordon\n|-\n|2009\n|''[[Watchmen (film)|Watchmen]]''\n|{{yes}}\n|{{no}}\n|{{no}}\n|\n|-\n|2010\n|''[[Legend of the Guardians: The Owls of Ga'Hoole]]''\n|{{yes}}\n|{{no}}\n|{{no}}\n|\n|-\n|2011\n|''[[Sucker Punch (2011 film)|Sucker Punch]]''\n|{{yes}}\n|{{yes}}\n|{{yes}}\n| Co-screenwriter with [[Steve Shibuya]]\n|-\n|2013\n|''[[Man of Steel (film)|Man of Steel]]''\n|{{yes}}\n|{{no}}\n|{{no}}\n|\n|-\n|2014\n|''[[300: Rise of an Empire]]''\n|{{no}}\n|{{yes}}\n|{{yes}}\n| Co-screenwriter with Kurt Johnstad\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |2016\n|''[[Batman v Superman: Dawn of Justice]]''\n|{{yes}}\n|{{no}}\n|{{no}}\n|\n|-\n|''[[Suicide Squad (film)|Suicide Squad]]''\n|{{no}}\n|{{no}}\n|{{yes|Executive}}\n|Directed the [[Flash (Barry Allen)|Flash]] cameo scene\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|2017\n|''[[Wonder Woman (2017 film)|Wonder Woman]]''\n|{{no}}\n|{{partial|Story}}\n|{{Yes}}\n| Story co-written with [[Allan Heinberg]] and [[Jason Fuchs]]\n|-\n|''[[Justice League (film)|Justice League]]''\n|{{yes}}\n|{{partial|Story}}\n|{{no}}\n| Story co-written with [[Chris Terrio]]\n|-\n|2018\n|''[[Aquaman (film)|Aquaman]]''\n|{{no}}\n|{{no}}\n|{{yes|Executive}}\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|2020\n|''[[Wonder Woman 1984]]''\n|{{no}}\n|{{no}}\n|{{Yes}}\n|\n|-\n|''[[Army of the Dead]]''\n|{{Yes}}\n|{{yes}}\n|{{yes}}\n| Also cinematographer<br>Co-screenwriter with [[Shay Hatten]] and [[Joby Harold]]\n|-\n|}\n\n=== Short films ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Year\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Film\n! colspan=\"3\" |Functioned as\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Notes\n|-\n! width=\"65\" |[[Film director|Director]]\n! width=\"65\" |[[Screenwriter|Writer]]\n! width=\"65\" |[[Film producer|Producer]]\n|-\n|2013\n|''Superman 75th Anniversary ''\n|{{Yes}}\n|{{partial|Story}}\n|{{no}}\n| Story co-written with [[Bruce Timm]]\n|-\n|2017\n|''Snow Steam Iron''\n|{{yes}}\n|{{partial|Story}}\n|{{yes}}\n| Also cinematographer\n|-\n|}\n\n=== Music videos ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Artist\n! Song\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"|1992 || [[Peter Murphy (musician)|Peter Murphy]] || \"[[You're So Close]]\"\n|-\n| [[Morrissey]] || \"[[Tomorrow (Morrissey song)|Tomorrow]]\"\n|-\n| [[Soul Asylum]] || \"[[Somebody to Shove]]\"\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|1993 || [[Soul Asylum]] || \"[[Black Gold (song)|Black Gold]]\"\n|-\n| [[Alexander O'Neal]] || \"[[In the Middle (Alexander O'Neal song)|In the Middle]]\"\n|-\n| 1994 || [[Dionne Farris]] || \"[[I Know (Dionne Farris song)|I Know]]\"\n|-\n| 2009 || [[My Chemical Romance]] || \"[[Desolation Row]]\"\n|}\n\n== Collaborations ==\n\n* Snyder's wife Deborah Snyder has produced all of his films dating back to ''300'' (executive producer on ''300'' and ''Legend of the Guardians: The Owls of Ga'Hoole'').\n* [[Larry Fong]] and [[William Hoy]] were Snyder's cinematographer and film editor, respectively, on the films ''300'', ''Watchmen'' and ''Sucker Punch''. Fong is also the cinematographer for ''Batman v Superman: Dawn of Justice''.\n* John \"D.J.\" Desjardin was the visual effects supervisor on ''Watchmen'', ''Sucker Punch'', ''Man of Steel'', ''Batman v Superman: Dawn of Justice'' and ''Justice League''.\n* David Brenner served as film editor on ''Man of Steel'', ''Batman v Superman: Dawn of Justice'', ''Justice League'' and the short film ''Snow Steam Iron''.\n\n== Reception ==\n{{Expand section|date=September 2016}}\n\nCritical, public and commercial reception to films Zack Snyder has directed as of November 26, 2017:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Film\n! [[Rotten Tomatoes]]<ref>{{cite web | title=Zack Snyder | url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/celebrity/zack_snyder | website=Rotten Tomatoes | accessdate=26 April 2015}}</ref>\n! [[Metacritic]]<ref>{{cite web | title=Zack Snyder Movies Profile |url=https://www.metacritic.com/person/zack-snyder | website=Metacritic |accessdate=26 April 2015}}</ref>\n! [[CinemaScore]]<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.cinemascore.com/ | title=Cinemascore | website=CinemaScore | accessdate=26 April 2015}}</ref>\n! Budget\n! Box office<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/people/chart/?id=zacksnyder.htm | title=Zack Snyder Movie Box Office Results | publisher=[[Amazon.com]] | work=[[Box Office Mojo]] | accessdate=23 January 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2004 || ''Dawn of the Dead'' || 75% (187 reviews) || 59 (37 reviews) || B || $26 million || $102.4 million\n|-\n| 2006 || ''300'' || 60% (231 reviews) || 52 (42 reviews) || A\u2212 || $65 million || $456.1 million\n|-\n| 2009 || ''Watchmen'' || 64% (307 reviews) || 56 (39 reviews) || B || $130 million || $185.3 million\n|-\n| 2010 || ''Legend of the Guardians: The Owls of Ga'Hoole'' || 51% (130 reviews) || 53 (21 reviews) || A\u2212 || $80 million || $140.1 million\n|-\n| 2011 || ''Sucker Punch'' || 22% (216 reviews) || 33 (29 reviews) || B\u2212 || $82 million || $89.8 million\n|-\n| 2013 || ''Man of Steel'' || 56% (330 reviews) || 55 (47 reviews) || A\u2212 || $225 million || $668.0 million\n|-\n| 2016 || ''Batman v Superman: Dawn of Justice'' || 28% (413 reviews) || 44 (51 reviews) || B || $250 million || $873.6 million\n|-\n| 2017 || ''Justice League'' || 40% (382 reviews) || 45 (52 reviews) || B+ ||  $300 million  || $657.9 million\n|}\n\n== Awards and nominations ==\n{{BLP unsourced section|date=August 2018}}\nSnyder's body of work has earned him a number of awards, including two [[Clio Award]]s and a Gold Lion Award for his [[Jeep]] \"[[Frisbee]]\" commercial. He also won the Society of British Advertisers Award for Humor for his controversial [[Elbrewery|EB Beer]] commercial \"General's Party.\"<ref>{{citeweb|url=http://haydenclement.com/audio-with-video.html|publisher=Hayden Clement|title=Music and Sound for Picture}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Award !! Category !! Nominee !! Result\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|2007 || [[Golden Schmoes Award]] || Best Director of the Year || rowspan=\"4\"|''[[300 (film)|300]]'' || {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Hollywood Film Awards|Hollywood Film Award]] || Hollywood Movie of the Year || {{won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|2008 || rowspan=\"2\"|[[Saturn Award]] || [[Saturn Award for Best Director|Best Director]] || {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Saturn Award for Best Writing|Best Writing]]<br /><small>Shared with Michael B. Gordon & [[Kurt Johnstad]]</small> || {{nom}}\n|-\n| 2009 || [[National Association of Theatre Owners|ShoWest Award]] || Director of the Year || rowspan=\"3\" |''[[Watchmen (film)|Watchmen]]''|| {{won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"|2010 || [[Saturn Award]] || Best Director || {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[SFX (magazine)|SFX Award]] || Best Director || {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[St. Louis Gateway Film Critics Association|St. Louis Film Critics Association Award]] || Best Animated Feature Film || ''[[Legend of the Guardians: The Owls of Ga'Hoole]]'' || {{nom}}\n|-\n| 2013 || [[Hollywood Film Awards|Hollywood Film Award]] || Hollywood Movie of the Year || rowspan=\"2\"|''[[Man of Steel (film)|Man of Steel]]'' || {{nom}}\n|-\n| 2014 || [[Jupiter Award (film award)|Jupiter Award]] || Best International Film || {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"|2017 || [[37th Golden Raspberry Awards|Golden Raspberry Award]] || [[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Director|Worst Director]] || rowspan=\"2\"|''[[Batman v Superman: Dawn of Justice]]'' || {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Jupiter Award (film award)|Jupiter Award]] || Best International Film || {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Satellite Awards]] || [[Satellite Award for Best Adapted Screenplay|Best Adapted Screenplay]]<br /><small>Shared with [[Allan Heinberg]] & [[Jason Fuchs]]</small> || rowspan=\"4\"| ''[[Wonder Woman (2017 film)|Wonder Woman]]'' || {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"|2018|| [[American Film Institute]]||Top Ten Films of the Year<br /><small>Shared with [[Charles Roven]], [[Richard Suckle]] & [[Deborah Snyder]]</small>|| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Producers Guild of America Awards]]||[[Producers Guild of America Award for Best Theatrical Motion Picture|Best Theatrical Motion Picture]]<br /><small>Shared with Charles Roven, Richard Suckle & Deborah Snyder</small>|| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Saturn Award]] || [[Saturn Award for Best Writing|Best Writing]]<br /><small>Shared with [[Allan Heinberg]] & [[Jason Fuchs]]</small>|| {{nom}}\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Zack Snyder}}\n* [http://www.cruelfilms.com/ Cruel and Unusual Films] \u2013 Snyder's production company\n* {{IMDb name|811583}}\n* {{tcmdb name|id=524957|name=Zack Snyder}}\n\n{{Zack Snyder}}\n{{Saturn Award for Best Direction}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Snyder, Zack}}\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n[[Category:Action film directors]]\n[[Category:American Christian Scientists]]\n[[Category:Advertising directors]]\n[[Category:American male screenwriters]]\n[[Category:American music video directors]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Green Bay, Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:People from Riverside, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Science fiction film directors]]\n[[Category:Writers from Greenwich, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Film directors from Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Film directors from Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:Screenwriters from Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:Screenwriters from Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Film producers from Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:Film producers from Connecticut]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-pc1|small=yes}}\n{{short description|American film director, film producer, and screenwriter}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name           = Zack Snyder\n| image          = Zack Snyder by Gage Skidmore 2.jpg\n| caption        = Snyder at the 2016 [[San Diego Comic-Con International]]\n| birth_name     = Zachary Edward Snyder\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1966|03|01}}\n| birth_place    = [[Green Bay, Wisconsin]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n| citizenship    = American\n| alma_mater      = [[Art Center College of Design]]\n| residence      = [[Pasadena, California|Pasadena]], [[California]], U.S.{{Citation needed|date=February 2019}}\n| occupation     = {{hlist|Film director|film producer|screenwriter}}\n| years_active   = 1990\u2013present\n| religion       = \n| spouse         = Denise Weber (divorced)<br />{{marriage|[[Deborah Snyder]]|2004|}}\n| children       = 8 (1 deceased, 4 adopted)<ref>{{cite web |title=Justice League: Zack Snyder quits movie after daughter kills herself |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2017/may/23/justice-league-zack-snyder-quits-joss-whedon |website=The Guardian |accessdate=February 13, 2019 |date=23 May 2017}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Zachary Edward Snyder''' (born March 1, 1966) is an American film director, producer, and screenwriter. He made his feature film debut in 2004 with [[Dawn of the Dead (2004 film)|a remake]] of the 1978 horror film ''[[Dawn of the Dead (1978 film)|Dawn of the Dead]]''. Since then, he has directed or produced a number of comic book and superhero films, including ''[[300 (film)|300]]'' (2006) and ''[[Watchmen (film)|Watchmen]]'' (2009), as well as the [[Superman]] film that started the [[DC Extended Universe]], ''[[Man of Steel (film)|Man of Steel]]'' (2013) and its follow-ups, ''[[Batman v Superman: Dawn of Justice]]'' (2016) and ''[[Justice League (film)|Justice League]]'' (2017). He also served as co-screenwriter for ''300'', ''[[Sucker Punch (2011 film)|Sucker Punch]]'' (2011), and ''[[300: Rise of an Empire]]'' (2014), an executive producer for ''[[Suicide Squad (2016 film)|Suicide Squad]]'' (2016) and ''[[Aquaman (film)|Aquaman]]'' (2018), and as co-writer of the story for ''[[Wonder Woman (2017 film)|Wonder Woman]]'' (2017) and ''Justice League''.\n\nSnyder is the co-founder of [[The Stone Quarry]], which was formerly known as Cruel and Unusual Films, a production company he established in 2004, alongside his wife [[Deborah Snyder]] and producing partner Wesley Coller.<ref name=\"Louie\" />\n\n== Early life ==\nSnyder was born in [[Green Bay, Wisconsin|Green Bay]], [[Wisconsin]], and raised in [[Riverside, Connecticut|Riverside]], [[Connecticut]]. His mother, Marsha Manley (n\u00e9e Reeves) (d. 2010)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.geni.com/people/Marsha-Snyder/6000000041194133936|title=Marsha Manley Snyder|website=geni_family_tree|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-23}}</ref>, was a painter and a photography teacher at [[Daycroft School]], which Snyder later attended. His father, Charles Edward \"Ed\" Snyder (1936\u20132008)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.geni.com/people/Charles-Snyder/6000000069140003863|title=Charles Edward \"Ed\" Snyder|website=geni_family_tree|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-23}}</ref>, worked as an executive recruiter.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=PBEB&p_theme=pbeb&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=117C5D13549DA238&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM | work=[[The Berkshire Eagle]] | title=Fan makes a film | date=8 March 2007 |access-date=8 October 2013|last=Everhart |first=Bill}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.legacy.com/obituaries/berkshire/obituary.aspx?n=marsha-snyder&pid=144455179 |title=Marsha Snyder Obituary \u2013 Pittsfield, MA|work=[[The Berkshire Eagle]]|publisher=Legacy.com |date= |accessdate=8 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/54776720/ |title=The North Adams Transcript from North Adams, Massachusetts \u00b7 Page 15 |publisher=Newspapers.com |date=1958-05-05 |accessdate=8 August 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151208082151/http://www.newspapers.com/newspage/54776720/ |archivedate=8 December 2015 }}</ref> He has an older sister, Audrey, and was raised as a [[Christian Scientist]].<ref name=\"Louie\">{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/02/20/fashion/weddings/20UNIONS.html |title=Off Screen, a Long-Running Romance |last=Louie |first=Elaine |date=18 February 2011 |work=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=2 October 2014 |quote=}}</ref> Snyder attended Camp Owatonna in Harrison, Maine, during the summer months as a child. Snyder studied painting a year after high school at [[Heatherley School of Fine Art]] in England, although he had already begun filmmaking. Afterward, Snyder attended [[Art Center College of Design]] in [[Pasadena, California|Pasadena]], California.<ref name=\"Bloomberg\">{{cite web|title=Zack Snyder's Superhero Life|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/features/2016-zack-snyder-profile|last=Leonard|first=Devin|date=1 March 2016|accessdate=1 March 2016|work=[[Bloomberg News]]}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n\nSnyder made his feature film debut with the remake of the horror film ''[[Dawn of the Dead (2004 film)|Dawn of the Dead]]'' (2004), and scored a box office hit with the fantasy war film ''[[300 (film)|300]]'' (2006), adapted from writer-artist [[Frank Miller (comics)|Frank Miller]]'s [[Dark Horse Comics]] [[miniseries]] of [[300 (comics)|the same name]]. His [[Warner Bros.]] film ''[[Watchmen (film)|Watchmen]]'' was released on March 6, 2009 and grossed $185 million worldwide. His follow-up project/animation debut titled ''[[Legend of the Guardians: The Owls of Ga'Hoole]]'' was released on September 24, 2010. Snyder produced, co-wrote, and directed ''[[Sucker Punch (2011 film)|Sucker Punch]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url = http://suicidegirls.com/interviews/Zack+Snyder%3A+Watchmen/|title = Zack Snyder: Watchmen|publisher = [[SuicideGirls]]|date = 5 March 2009|accessdate =5 March 2009}}</ref> which was released on March 25, 2011. The film, based on a script written by Snyder and Steve Shibuya, was about a young woman in a mental hospital who fantasizes of escape with her fellow inmates.\n\nHe directed 2013's ''[[Man of Steel (film)|Man of Steel]]'' for Warner Bros., a reboot of the Superman franchise. He signed on direct a yet-to-be-produced remake of the 1969 film ''[[The Illustrated Man (film)|The Illustrated Man]]'',<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.comingsoon.net/movies/news/79924-updates-on-the-jetsons-zack-snyders-the-illustrated-man |title=Updates on The Jetsons & Zack Snyder's The Illustrated Man |last=Douglas |first=Edward |website=ComingSoon.net |date=4 October 2010 |accessdate=13 June 2016}}</ref> and produced the prequel/sequel to ''300'', ''[[300: Rise of an Empire]]'' (2014). He also wants to direct a segment for an upcoming ''[[Heavy Metal (film)#Remake|Heavy Metal 3]]'', and plans to write and direct a sequel to ''Legend of the Guardians''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.deadline.com/2010/10/zack-snyder-directing-superman/ |title=SCOOP: Zack Snyder Directing 'Superman' |work=Deadline.com |author=Fleming, Mike |date=4 October 2010 |accessdate=4 October 2010}}</ref>\n\nDuring Comic Con 2013, Snyder announced that [[Batman]] and [[Superman]] would share the screen in ''[[Batman v Superman: Dawn of Justice]]'', released in 2016. Snyder directed, Cavill reprised his role as Superman, and [[Ben Affleck]] played Batman.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.slashfilm.com/zack-snyder-will-direct-supermanbatman-movie-inspired-by-frank-millers-the-dark-knight-returns/ |title=Zack Snyder Will Direct Superman/Batman Movie Inspired by Frank Miller's 'The Dark Knight Returns' |last=Fischer |first=Russ |date=20 July 2013 |website=[[/Film]] |publisher= |access-date=20 July 2013 |quote=}}</ref> Snyder directed Warner Bros.' 2017 ''[[Justice League (film)|Justice League]]'', but was replaced with [[Joss Whedon]] after having to leave during post-production to deal with the death of his daughter.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://blogs.wsj.com/speakeasy/2014/04/27/warner-bros-details-plans-for-justice-league-movie-exclusive/|title=Warner Bros. Plans 'Justice League' Movie Directed by Zack Snyder (Exclusive)|last=Fritz|first=Ben|work=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|date=26 April 2014|accessdate=27 April 2014}}</ref>\n\nAs of March 2016, Snyder was working on ''The Last Photograph'', a drama about a war photographer in South-America. He is also currently working on an adaptation of the 1943 novel ''[[The Fountainhead]]'' by [[Ayn Rand]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://screenanarchy.com/2011/08/breaking-zack-snyder-taking-directors-chair-on-the-last-photograph.html | title=BREAKING: Zack Snyder Taking Director's Chair On THE LAST PHOTOGRAPH |last=Brown |first=Todd | publisher=[[Screen Anarchy]] | date=2 August 2011 | accessdate=8 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/batman-v-superman-married-creative-874799 | title='Batman v. Superman': Married Creative Duo on That R-Rated DVD, Plans for DC Superhero Universe |last=Siegel |first=Tatiana | work=The Hollywood Reporter | date=17 March 2016 | accessdate=4 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2018/05/zack-snyder-the-fountainhead-adaptation|title=Zack Snyder's Next Project Is an Adaptation of The Fountainhead|last=Desta|first=Yohana|work=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]|date=29 May 2018|access-date=29 May 2018|language=en}}</ref>. He has also expressed an interest in making a film, in the style of ''[[300 (film)|300]]'', about [[George Washington]], the first president of the United States of America.<ref>Jacob Hall, [https://www.slashfilm.com/zack-snyder-george-washington-movie/ \"Zack Snyder Wants to Make a George Washington Movie\"], ''SlashFilm'', 2 March 2016</ref>\n\nOn January 29, 2019, Snyder announced that he has signed on to helm ''[[Army of the Dead (upcoming film)|Army of the Dead]]'', a zombie horror thriller, for [[Netflix]]. Snyder will direct and produce with his partner and wife, Deborah Snyder, via their newly rebranded production company, [[The Stone Quarry]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/zack-snyder-returns-movies-zombie-pic-army-dead-1178979|title=Zack Snyder Returning to Movies With Zombie Action Pic 'Army of the Dead' (Exclusive)|website=The Hollywood Reporter|language=en|access-date=2019-01-31}}</ref>\n\n== Style ==\nSnyder often uses [[slow motion]] in and out of the fight scenes in his films, which Amy Nicholson of ''[[BoxOffice (magazine)|BoxOffice]]'' magazine remarked separates the director from other filmmakers who make multiple cuts and close-ups during a fight. A minute-long shot from ''300'' shows King Leonidas slaughtering his enemies, the camera zooming in and out to emphasize each kill and move Leonidas makes.<ref>{{cite news|last=Nicholson|first=Amy |magazine=Box Office Magazine |date=26 February 2009 |url=http://boxoffice.com/editors-desk/slow-and-steady.php |title=Slow and Steady |accessdate=28 March 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090303045524/http://boxoffice.com/editors-desk/slow-and-steady.php |archivedate=3 March 2009 }}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nSnyder lives in Pasadena with his second wife, producer [[Deborah Snyder|Deborah Johnson]]. The couple first met in 1996, started dating in 2002, and married on September 25, 2004 at [[St. Bartholomew's Episcopal Church, New York|St. Bartholomew's Episcopal Church]] in Manhattan, New York.<ref name=\"Weddings\">{{cite news|title = WEDDINGS/CELEBRATIONS: VOWS; Deborah Johnson and Zack Snyder \u2013 New York Times|url = https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9F05E3DA1338F930A35753C1A9629C8B63&fta=y|date = 3 October 2004|last = Louie|first = Elaine|publisher = [[The New York Times Company]]|work = [[The New York Times]]|accessdate = 25 July 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.filmjournal.com/filmjournal/content_display/news-and-features/features/movies/e3i8f6bf92e292731581559af0969092ce9?pn=2|author=Frank Lovece|title=CGI: 'Watchmen'--Zack Snyder brings superhero saga to the finish line|journal=Film Journal International|date=19 February 2009|accessdate=19 February 2009}}</ref> He was previously married to Denise Weber.\n\nSnyder has eight children, half of whom are adopted: Olivia, Willow, Autumn, Eli, Ezekiel, Jett, Sage and Cash. He and Denise had Olivia and Eli, and adopted Willow and Autumn from China. Two younger sons, Ezekiel and Jett, are from his relationship with Kirsten Elin, who was his line producer on commercials for some time.<ref name=\"Louie\" /> Snyder and Deborah adopted Sage and Cash during the course of making ''[[Man of Steel (film)|Man of Steel]]''.<ref name=\"Bloomberg\" />\n\nOn March 12, 2017,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mec.lacounty.gov/case-detail/?caseNumber=2017-02042 |title=Los Angeles County Department of Medical Examiner \u2013 Coroner \u2013 Case Detail |last= |first= |date= |website=[[Los Angeles County Department of Medical Examiner-Coroner]] |publisher= |access-date=24 May 2017 |quote=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/179621277 |title=Autumn Snyder (1996\u20132017) |last= |first= |date= |website=[[Find a Grave]] |publisher= |access-date=24 May 2017 |quote=}}</ref> the suicide of his daughter Autumn prompted Snyder to withdraw from post-production work on ''[[Justice League (film)|Justice League]]'' in May 2017 to be with his family.<ref>{{citeweb|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/zack-snyder-steps-down-justice-league-deal-family-tragedy-1006455|title=Zack Snyder Steps Down From 'Justice League' to Deal With Family Tragedy|date=22 May 2017|accessdate=23 September 2018|publisher=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|first=Borys|last=Kit}}</ref>\n\n== Filmography ==\n=== Films ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Year\n! rows